    "final_proposal": "### Core Hypothesis\nFive-shot in-context learning with a frozen 7B-parameter LLM will only outperform task-specific fine-tuning of a 300M-parameter encoder on low-resource text classification when the LLM\u2019s tokenizer efficiency for the target language approaches parity with the encoder's. In languages with non-Latin scripts, tokenizer fragmentation (Token Fertility) will severely penalize the LLM's parametric reasoning, allowing the much smaller encoder to achieve a higher Macro-F1 despite relying on limited explicit gradient updates (<1,000 examples).\n\n### Minimal Viable Design\n**1. Dataset & Languages (Semantic Control)**\nWe use the **SIB-200** dataset (7-way topic classification) because it provides exact, semantically parallel translated test sets across languages, isolating representational efficiency from task difficulty. We select 4 languages from 4 distinct families, mixing Latin and non-Latin scripts:\n*   **Amharic** (Afroasiatic | Ge'ez script)\n*   **Yoruba** (Niger-Congo | Latin script)\n*   **Marathi** (Indo-Aryan | Devanagari script)\n*   **Burmese** (Sino-Tibetan | Burmese script)\n\n**2. Models**\n*   **Few-Shot Model:** Mistral-7B-v0.1 (Single 7B decoder-only LLM, strictly frozen).\n*   **Fine-Tuned Model:** XLM-RoBERTa-base (~278M multilingual encoder, standard classification head).\n\n**3. Experimental Protocol**\n*   **5-Shot In-Context Learning:** For each test example, sample 5 random examples from the training set (N=704) using 3 fixed seeds. Strictly formatted as `Text: {text}\\nLabel: {label}`. The LLM's prediction is derived via **logit-based scoring** (selecting the valid class label with the highest log-probability).\n*   **Task-Specific Fine-Tuning:** Fine-tune the encoder using a scaling curve of N=100, N=300, and N=704 (maximum available training data) across 3 random seeds to pinpoint the exact data volume needed to intercept 5-shot LLM performance.\n\n### Primary Outcome\nThe primary metric is **Macro-F1** measured on the parallel, held-out test sets (N=2,048 per language). \n\nSuccess criteria will be evaluated via a **paired bootstrap resampling test (10,000 resamples, $p < 0.05$)**, comparing the discrete predictions of the best-seed 5-shot 7B LLM against the best-seed fully fine-tuned (N=704) 300M encoder. We will report **95% confidence intervals** for the Macro-F1 difference (ICL minus FT) for each of the 4 languages individually.\n\n### Main Confound and Mitigation\n**Confound:** Generative artifacts and instruction-following failures. A frozen base LLM might fail to output the exact label string (e.g., generating \"The topic is Sports\" instead of \"Sports\", or translating the label). In a standard string-matching evaluation, this artificially deflates the LLM's Macro-F1, confounding the comparison with an encoder that is architecturally constrained to valid outputs. \n**Mitigation:** We evaluate the 7B LLM using **logit-based scoring** rather than open-ended generation. By forcing the LLM to choose the highest-probability allowable label given the context, we guarantee it functions purely as a classifier. Any performance degradation is strictly attributable to underlying representational limits rather than formatting non-compliance.\n\n### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Cross-Benchmark Evaluation (Direction B):** We considered evaluating across two distinct datasets (e.g., MasakhaNEWS and IndicNLP) to demonstrate generalizability. We discarded this because it introduces severe causal confounds. Differing annotation guidelines, semantic complexity, and class distributions across datasets make it impossible to definitively attribute performance gaps to model architecture or tokenization. SIB-200's perfectly parallel corpora provide stronger, cleaner evidence.\n2.  **Varying Few-Shot Examples (Direction C):** We considered mapping an LLM scaling curve by varying the prompt from 1-shot to 5-shot. We discarded this because varying shot counts interacts aggressively with context-window limits on inefficient non-Latin tokenizers, creating a secondary variable. Furthermore, the brief explicitly demands a 5-shot baseline. Modulating the *encoder's* data scale (N=100 to N=704) is a cleaner way to contextualize the fixed 5-shot LLM's performance threshold.\n\n---"
  },
