    "final_proposal": "### Final Research Proposal\n\n#### Core Hypothesis\nThe \"Generalist-Specialist\" Hypothesis: Frozen 7B-parameter decoder-only LLMs leverage emergent linguistic hierarchies that provide a statistically superior classification baseline in low-resource (N=500) settings compared to the limited representational capacity of fine-tuned 300M-parameter encoders, regardless of variation in prompt selection or weight initialization.\n\n#### Minimal Viable Design\n*   **Models:** Llama-3-8B (frozen) vs. XLM-R Base (fine-tuned on 500 examples, 10 epochs).\n*   **Languages:** Yoruba (Niger-Congo), Burmese (Sino-Tibetan), Amharic (Afroasiatic).\n*   **Protocol:** \n    *   For each language, execute a **3x3 cross-seed matrix**: 3 random-seed 5-shot prompts (LLM) vs. 3 random-seed classification head initializations (Encoder).\n    *   This generates 9 paired performance outcomes per language.\n    *   **Statistical Analysis:** 10,000-resample bootstrap test calculated across the 9-point distribution to generate $p$-values and 95% CIs.\n\n#### Primary Outcome\nThe primary outcome is the **Mean Difference ($\\Delta$) in Macro-F1** between the LLM and the Encoder. We define success as the lower bound of the 95% CI being $> 0$ with $p < 0.05$, confirming that the LLM's performance gain is robust against both \"lucky\" prompts and \"lucky\" model initializations.\n\n#### Main Confound and Mitigation\n*   **Confound:** \"Seed-sensitive performance\" (the risk that observed superiority is merely an artifact of a high-performing random prompt or weight initialization).\n*   **Mitigation:** The 3x3 seed-grid. By incorporating variance from *both* sampling (prompts) and optimization (initialization) into the bootstrap test, we produce a significance result that is structurally hardened against anecdotal performance gains.\n\n#### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Complexity-focused (Scaling):** Evaluating performance at N=50, N=500, and N=1000. *Rejected to prevent statistical \"noise\" and ensure the bootstrap test remains focused on the primary N=500 comparison.*\n2.  **Architecture-focused (Encoder diversity):** Comparing XLM-R against mBERT. *Rejected to focus on the LLM vs. Encoder architectural dichotomy rather than encoder-specific variations.*"
