    "brief_id": "nlp_01",
    "domain": "natural language processing",
    "objective": "Does few-shot in-context learning (5-shot) with a frozen 7B-parameter LLM achieve higher macro-F1 than task-specific fine-tuning of a 300M-parameter encoder model on text classification for languages with fewer than 10,000 labeled training examples?",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "Few-shot model must be a single 7B-parameter decoder-only LLM with no gradient updates",
      "Fine-tuned model must be a pre-trained multilingual encoder (e.g., XLM-R base, 270-300M parameters)",
      "Evaluation languages must have fewer than 10,000 labeled training examples in the chosen dataset",
      "Minimum 3 low-resource languages evaluated, each from a different language family",
      "Primary metric is macro-F1 on a held-out test set of at least 500 examples per language",
      "Few-shot examples selected randomly with a fixed seed; no manual curation or chain-of-thought"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "Using chain-of-thought, scratchpad, or multi-step reasoning in the few-shot prompt",
      "Fine-tuning the 7B LLM (LoRA, adapters, or full) instead of keeping it frozen",
      "Evaluating only on high-resource languages (more than 10,000 labeled examples)",
      "Ensembling multiple models or combining few-shot and fine-tuned predictions",
      "Translating test data into English before classification"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "# Final Research Proposal\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\n5-shot in-context learning with a frozen 7B-parameter decoder-only LLM (Mistral-7B-v0.1) does not achieve higher macro-F1 than task-specific fine-tuning of a 270M-parameter multilingual encoder (XLM-R Base) on 7-class news topic classification in low-resource African languages. The comparison is made on languages with fewer than 10,000 labeled training examples, evaluated on held-out test sets of at least 500 examples per language, across three typologically distinct languages. The direction of the difference is not pre-specified; the test is two-tailed.\n\n**Operationalisation of \"higher\":** A difference of at least 3 macro-F1 points in either direction is required for a result to be interpreted as practically meaningful, in addition to statistical significance at BH-corrected p < 0.05 across three paired bootstrap tests.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Dataset\nMasakhaNEWS (`masakhane/masakhanews`, Adelani et al. 2023). Seven-class news topic classification. Fixed train/dev/test splits. Test sets verified at 957 (Yoruba), 1,290 (Hausa), and 1,115 (Swahili) examples respectively, all exceeding the 500-example minimum.\n\n### Languages\n\n| Language | Family | Subfamily | Train Examples | Test Examples |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Yoruba (yor) | Niger-Congo | Volta-Niger | 3,344 | 957 |\n| Hausa (hau) | Afro-Asiatic | West Chadic | 4,519 | 1,290 |\n| Swahili (swa) | Niger-Congo | Bantu | 3,901 | 1,115 |\n\nTypological diversity is operationalised at the subfamily level, which is pre-registered as the operative definition. Yoruba and Swahili share a top-level family label but are as distant within Niger-Congo as Romance and Germanic are within Indo-European. All three languages differ in morphological type (isolating/tonal, agglutinative/Chadic, agglutinative/noun-class), script environment (all Latin-script but with distinct orthographic conventions), and geographic region. This is documented explicitly in the paper and pre-registered before data access.\n\n### Models\n\n**Model A \u2014 Frozen Few-Shot LLM:**\n- Mistral-7B-v0.1, weights fully frozen, no gradient updates of any kind\n- 5 examples drawn randomly from the training split using `random.sample`, seeded at {42, 123, 7}\n- Greedy decoding (temperature=0, do_sample=False), max 10 new tokens\n- Single fixed prompt template: category list, five labeled examples, test article, \"Category:\" continuation cue\n- No chain-of-thought, no system prompt, no instruction-tuning wrapper\n- Output parsed by case-insensitive prefix match against label strings; fallback to most frequent training label if no match, logged as parse failure\n\n**Model B \u2014 Fine-Tuned Encoder:**\n- XLM-R Base (270M parameters), linear classification head on [CLS] token\n- Full encoder fine-tuned on the training split of each language separately\n- AdamW, lr=2e-5, batch size=32, max 10 epochs, early stopping patience=3 on dev macro-F1\n- Seeds {42, 123, 7} control initialisation and data shuffling\n- Dev split used only for early stopping; never seen by the few-shot model and excluded from all test evaluation\n\n### Execution\nTotal runs: 18 primary (3 languages \u00d7 2 models \u00d7 3 seeds) plus 18 secondary inference-only runs (k=1,3 for the LLM). Fine-tuning is the only step requiring sustained GPU time; estimated at under 3 hours total on a single A100 80GB. LLM inference is the bottleneck at 6\u201313 hours on the same hardware.\n\n### Seed Aggregation\nFor each model and language, majority vote is taken across the 3 seed-specific prediction vectors, instance by instance, producing one aggregated prediction vector per model per language. This aggregated vector enters the bootstrap. Ties (possible with K=3 seeds) are broken by alphabetical label order, pre-registered.\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\nFor each language $l$, the primary outcome is:\n\n$$\\Delta_l = \\text{macro-F1}(\\text{few-shot}_l) - \\text{macro-F1}(\\text{fine-tuned}_l)$$\n\ncomputed on seed-aggregated predictions against the held-out test set.\n\nStatistical inference uses a paired bootstrap test (10,000 resamples, bootstrap seed fixed at 0) with the shift method to centre the null distribution. The same resample indices are applied to both models' prediction vectors simultaneously, preserving the paired structure. Two-tailed p-values are computed per language and corrected for three simultaneous comparisons using Benjamini-Hochberg at FDR=0.05.\n\nResults are reported as:\n\n- Mean macro-F1 \u00b1 std across 3 seeds, per language per model (Table 1)\n- $\\Delta_l$, 95% bootstrap CI, uncorrected p, BH-corrected p, and significance flag per language (Table 2)\n- Per-class F1 breakdown across both models and all three languages (Figure 2)\n- k-shot sensitivity curve for the frozen LLM at k \u2208 {1, 3, 5}, with fine-tuned results as reference lines, no statistical testing (Figure 1, secondary analysis)\n\nA result is interpreted as practically meaningful only if $|\\Delta_l| \\geq 0.03$ and BH-corrected p < 0.05. If the interval crosses zero or $|\\Delta_l| < 0.03$ for all languages, the conclusion is that no practically meaningful difference was detected at this scale, which is itself an informative finding.\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n**Confound: Mistral-7B's multilingual tokenisation quality varies substantially across the three languages.**\n\nMistral-7B was trained predominantly on English and high-resource European languages. For Yoruba, Hausa, and Swahili, the tokeniser may fragment words into many subword units, increasing sequence length, diluting contextual signal in the 5-shot examples, and increasing the probability of malformed or off-distribution outputs. This is a structural disadvantage for the few-shot model that does not apply to XLM-R, which was explicitly pre-trained on 100 languages including all three targets. If the few-shot model underperforms, tokenisation quality is a plausible partial explanation that would limit the interpretability of the result as a general claim about model scale versus fine-tuning.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n\nToken fertility (mean subword tokens per whitespace-delimited word) is computed for both tokenisers on the test split of each language and reported in Appendix F. If Mistral-7B fertility exceeds 5 tokens per word for any language \u2014 a threshold indicating severe fragmentation \u2014 this is flagged prominently in the discussion as a confound that partially decouples the comparison from the intended question of scale versus supervision. The result for that language is reported with a caveat rather than excluded.\n\nThis mitigation is observational, not interventional, which is correct: intervening on tokenisation (e.g., by switching to a model with better multilingual coverage) would change the model specification and violate the hard constraint fixing the few-shot model as Mistral-7B-v0.1. The fertility analysis is therefore a diagnostic that bounds the interpretive claims, not a fix.\n\nParse failure rate serves as a second diagnostic: high failure rates on a particular language are a behavioural signal of the same underlying tokenisation and distributional problem, and are logged and reported separately per the pre-registered protocol.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Four Languages Across Two Benchmarks (MasakhaNEWS + IndicNLPSuite)\n\n**Description:** Evaluate on 2 African languages from MasakhaNEWS and 2 South Asian languages from IndicNLPSuite, testing whether the few-shot vs. fine-tuned comparison generalises across benchmark families and language regions.\n\n**Why not chosen:** Introduces label-space heterogeneity as an uncontrolled variable. MasakhaNEWS and IndicNLPSuite have different classification schemas, different numbers of classes, and different domain distributions. Any difference in results across benchmarks would be confounded by task difficulty, label granularity, and domain shift, making it impossible to attribute the difference cleanly to language properties. The single-benchmark design with three languages provides a cleaner test of the core hypothesis. Cross-benchmark generality is a legitimate follow-on question but is not answerable within this design without adding complexity that the current brief does not justify.\n\n**What it would add if chosen:** External validity across benchmark families and geographic regions; stronger claim about generality of the few-shot vs. fine-tuning gap. This remains a well-motivated direction for a subsequent study.\n\n### Alternative 2: Fine-Tuning Data Subsampled to Exactly 1,000 Examples Per Language\n\n**Description:** Rather than using the full available training split (3,344\u20134,519 examples), subsample each language's training data to exactly 1,000 examples, making the data regime more uniform and more severely low-resource.\n\n**Why not chosen:** Introduces a subsampling decision that is not motivated by the hard constraint (which requires only <10,000 examples, not exactly 1,000) and that would artificially handicap the fine-tuned model relative to what it could achieve with naturally available data. The research question asks whether few-shot LLMs outperform fine-tuned encoders in the low-resource regime as it naturally exists, not in a regime constructed to make fine-tuning harder. Using the full available training data for fine-tuning is the more conservative and more externally valid choice: if few-shot wins against a fully-trained encoder, the result is stronger; if fine-tuning wins, the result reflects realistic practice. Subsampling to 1,000 would also introduce a new free parameter (the subsample size) requiring justification.\n\n**What it would add if chosen:** A more controlled comparison at a fixed data size; direct relevance to practitioners who have exactly 1,000 labeled examples. This is a legitimate secondary analysis that could be added in a follow-on study without violating any constraint, but it is not the primary question and is excluded here to keep the design minimal.\n\n---"
  },
