    "brief_id": "epi_01",
    "domain": "epidemiology",
    "objective": "Determine whether long-term ambient PM2.5 exposure is associated with increased childhood asthma incidence after adjusting for socioeconomic and indoor-environment confounders.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "retrospective cohort design only, no randomization of exposure",
      "exposure metric must be annual-average PM2.5 at residential address, not self-reported",
      "cohort must include at least 5000 children aged 0-12",
      "must use ICD-coded asthma diagnoses, not survey-reported symptoms",
      "must adjust for at least household income and parental smoking status",
      "no proprietary air-quality datasets; only publicly available EPA AQS or equivalent"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add an indoor air-quality monitoring component to the study",
      "expand the outcome to include all respiratory conditions rather than asthma specifically",
      "incorporate genetic or biomarker data to explore biologic mechanisms"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nAmong children aged 0\u201312 years who are asthma-free at cohort entry, **higher annual-average ambient PM2.5 at the residential address is associated with a higher hazard of incident ICD-coded asthma**, after adjustment for **household income, parental smoking status**, and other pre-specified confounders.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal viable design\n**Design:** retrospective cohort study\n\n**Population:**\n- at least **5,000 children**\n- age **0\u201312 years**\n- no prior ICD-coded asthma during a **12-month washout** before cohort entry\n- available residential address history\n- available data on **household income** and **parental smoking status**\n\n**Exposure:**\n- **annual-average PM2.5 at the residential address**\n- assigned from **publicly available EPA AQS or equivalent non-proprietary public data**\n- updated over time when address or calendar year changes\n- if multiple addresses occur within a year, use a **time-weighted annual average**\n\n**Follow-up:**\n- from cohort entry until first asthma diagnosis, disenrollment/loss to follow-up, 13th birthday, or study end\n\n**Primary model, pre-specified before analysis:**\n- **Cox proportional hazards model** with time-varying PM2.5 exposure\n- report **adjusted hazard ratio per 5 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 increase** in annual-average PM2.5 with **95% CI**\n\n**Required sensitivity analysis:**\n- primary exposure window: **prior-year annual-average PM2.5**\n- sensitivity exposure window: **2-year moving average PM2.5**\n\n**One added credibility component:**\n- pre-specified **future-exposure falsification test** using next-year annual-average PM2.5 as a negative-control exposure\n\nThis is the simplest design that answers the objective while still giving reviewers a stronger causal story.\n\n---\n\n## Primary outcome\n**Incident childhood asthma**, defined by the first **ICD-coded asthma diagnosis** during follow-up.\n\nTo reduce outcome misclassification while staying within the hard constraint, the operational definition can be pre-specified as:\n- one inpatient asthma ICD code, or\n- two outpatient asthma ICD codes within a defined interval\n\nThe main reported effect measure is the **adjusted hazard ratio** for incident asthma with **95% confidence interval**.\n\n---\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n### Main confound\nThe most important threat is **socio-environmental confounding**, especially the possibility that children living in higher-PM2.5 areas also differ in ways that independently affect asthma risk, particularly:\n- **household income**\n- **parental smoking**\n- broader neighborhood disadvantage and healthcare access\n\n### Mitigation\nPre-specify a **DAG-informed adjustment set** and include, at minimum:\n- household income\n- parental smoking status\n\nPlus other available confounders such as:\n- age\n- sex\n- race/ethnicity\n- insurance type\n- calendar year\n- neighborhood deprivation\n- baseline healthcare utilization\n\nAdditional mitigation steps:\n- use **time-varying address-based exposure assignment**\n- exclude prevalent asthma with a **12-month washout**\n- use a **future-exposure falsification analysis** to probe residual spatial confounding\n- perform the required **exposure-window sensitivity analysis**\n\n---\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n### 1. Distributed-lag nonlinear model using annual PM2.5\n**Why plausible:** could characterize timing and nonlinearity in more detail.\n\n**Why not chosen:** adds complexity beyond what is needed to identify the target claim. The objective is to determine whether long-term PM2.5 is associated with asthma incidence, not to estimate a detailed lag-response surface. A standard Cox model is simpler, more transparent, and sufficient.\n\n### 2. Matched cohort by high- vs low-PM2.5 ZIP code using propensity scores\n**Why plausible:** can improve balance on measured confounders and is familiar to reviewers.\n\n**Why not chosen:** the hard constraint requires exposure at the **residential address**, and ZIP-code exposure assignment is less faithful to that requirement and more vulnerable to spatial misclassification. Address-level time-varying exposure is the better fit.\n\n---"
  },
