    "domain": "computational social science",
    "objective": "Test whether exposure to algorithmically curated ideologically homogeneous content feeds on social media increases users' affective polarization scores over a 6-week period compared to exposure to ideologically diverse feeds.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "randomized controlled experiment with exactly 2 conditions (homogeneous feed vs diverse feed)",
      "sample size between 800 and 2000 adult U.S. social media users recruited via a platform partnership or browser extension",
      "affective polarization measured using the feeling thermometer difference score (in-party minus out-party warmth) administered pre and post",
      "intervention period must last exactly 6 weeks with compliance verified by feed exposure logs",
      "participants must not be informed of which condition they are assigned to during the study",
      "single platform only, no cross-platform analysis",
      "no deception beyond standard randomized assignment; study must receive IRB approval before data collection"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a survey-based measure of issue position extremity as a primary outcome alongside affective polarization",
      "include a no-intervention control group that receives their unmodified organic feed",
      "analyze behavioral outcomes such as sharing, commenting, or content creation during the study",
      "extend the study to non-U.S. populations or multiple countries"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nExposure to an algorithmically curated **ideologically homogeneous** social media feed for **6 weeks** will produce a **larger increase in affective polarization** than exposure to an **ideologically diverse** feed, as measured by the **feeling thermometer difference score** (in-party warmth minus out-party warmth) from pre to post.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n**Design type:** Two-arm randomized controlled experiment.\n\n**Population and sample:**  \n- **800\u20132000 adult U.S. social media users**\n- Recruited via a **browser extension partnership** on a single platform, most plausibly **Twitter/X**\n- Single-platform only\n\n**Conditions (exactly 2):**\n1. **Homogeneous feed condition:** The browser extension re-ranks the participant\u2019s existing feed to emphasize ideologically similar sources/posts.\n2. **Diverse feed condition:** The browser extension re-ranks the feed to increase exposure to ideologically mixed sources/posts.\n\n**Intervention period:**  \n- Exactly **6 weeks**\n- Compliance verified through **feed exposure logs** captured by the extension\n\n**Blinding:**  \n- Participants are **not informed of their assigned condition** during the study\n\n**Randomization:**  \n- Individual-level random assignment to one of the two feed conditions\n\n**Measurement schedule:**  \n- **Pre-intervention** feeling thermometer difference score\n- **Post-intervention** feeling thermometer difference score at week 6\n\n**Analysis plan:**  \n- Estimate the **between-condition difference in pre-post change** in affective polarization\n- Report **95% confidence intervals**\n- Estimate a **complier average causal effect (CACE)** using logged compliance to account for participants who do not fully receive their assigned feed condition\n- Include a **heterogeneity analysis** by one pre-registered moderator, preferably **party affiliation** or **baseline polarization**\n\n## Primary outcome\nThe primary outcome is the **change in affective polarization** over 6 weeks, operationalized as:\n\n**Feeling thermometer difference score = in-party warmth \u2212 out-party warmth**\n\nMeasured **pre** and **post** intervention, with the main estimand being the **difference in change scores between the two randomized conditions**.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n**Main confound:** Differential compliance with the assigned feed condition, since participants may not fully engage with the browser extension or may access the platform outside the intervention path.\n\n**Mitigation:**  \n- Use **feed exposure logs** from the browser extension to quantify actual exposure\n- Predefine compliance thresholds\n- Estimate both:\n  - the **intention-to-treat effect** for the randomized comparison\n  - the **CACE** for participants whose logged exposure indicates substantial adherence\n- Keep the platform and intervention mechanism constant across both arms to reduce structural differences unrelated to feed ideology\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Custom mobile app with a simulated feed drawn from real posts**  \n   - Plausible because it gives the cleanest control over exposure.\n   - Not chosen because it departs from users\u2019 organic platform environment and is more intrusive than necessary for the target claim.\n\n2. **Partnership with the platform to randomize the feed algorithm\u2019s diversity parameter**  \n   - Plausible because it would be highly ecologically valid and could directly manipulate curation.\n   - Not chosen because it depends on platform cooperation that may be harder to secure than a browser-extension implementation."
  },
