    "final_proposal": "### Core Hypothesis\nMandatory ESG disclosure reduces the cost of equity capital by forcing the resolution of \"worst-case\" estimation risk. Consequently, the reduction in the implied cost of equity will be most pronounced among previously opaque firms operating in structurally high-risk industries, where environmental and social liabilities were historically the most ambiguous to investors.\n\n### Minimal Viable Design\nThe design is an **Intent-to-Treat (ITT) Triple-Difference (DDD)** exploiting the EU Non-Financial Reporting Directive (NFRD). \n*   **Window:** 2013\u20132019, providing pre- and post-mandate periods without overlapping the 2008 financial crisis or exceeding the 10-year limit.\n*   **Sample:** EU-listed non-financial firms drawn from Compustat Global, Datastream, and I/B/E/S. To strictly isolate the *mandate* effect, any firm that voluntarily published sustainability reports prior to 2014 is permanently dropped from the sample. \n*   **Treatment 1 (The Mandate):** To prevent endogenous sorting bias, firms are assigned treatment strictly based on their pre-announcement 2013 employee count. Treated $= 1$ for $>500$ employees; Control $= 0$ for matched firms with $250\u2013500$ employees.\n*   **Treatment 2 (The Mechanism):** The sample is partitioned by structural industry risk ($HighStructRisk = 1$) using objective public SIC codes for historically high-emission/liability sectors (e.g., mining, heavy chemicals), avoiding banned proprietary ESG scores.\n*   **Specification:** The primary coefficient of interest is the three-way interaction: $Post \\times Treated \\times HighStructRisk$.\n\n### Primary Outcome\nThe sole primary outcome variable is the **Implied Cost of Capital (ICC)**, measured as an annual percentage. It is estimated strictly using the **Easton (2004) PEG ratio model**, which relies on 1-year ahead and 2-year ahead analyst earnings per share (EPS) forecasts from I/B/E/S and current stock prices. CAPM beta is entirely excluded from the analysis. \n\n### Main Confound and Mitigation\n**Confound:** The primary threat to validity is the combination of concurrent country-level regulatory changes (e.g., tax reforms) and secular size trends (i.e., the cost of capital for large-cap firms naturally dropping relative to mid-cap firms during the late 2010s for non-ESG reasons).\n**Mitigation:** \n1.  **Fixed Effects:** The DDD design permits stringent **Country $\\times$ Year** and **Industry $\\times$ Year** fixed effects, perfectly absorbing concurrent national policies and global sector pricing shocks.\n2.  **In-Sample Placebos:** To decisively rule out secular size trends, we re-run the exact ITT DDD on two in-sample placebo thresholds: Placebo 1 (Treated >1,000 vs Control 600\u2013900; both subject to NFRD) and Placebo 2 (Treated 150\u2013240 vs Control 50\u2013140; neither subject to NFRD). A significant effect at the true 500-employee threshold, paired with null results in both placebos, definitively isolates the regulation.\n\n### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Event study around the SEC climate disclosure rule:** Rejected because the SEC rule is too recent (and legally stayed), meaning there is insufficient post-implementation analyst forecast data (I/B/E/S) to reliably estimate the Implied Cost of Capital. The EU NFRD provides complete, stable retrospective data.\n2.  **Staggered DiD across multiple countries with different adoption dates:** Rejected due to excessive complexity and unobservable confounding. Staggered adoptions across different continents introduce varying macroeconomic baseline conditions and differing enforcement strengths. A single regulatory shock (EU NFRD) using within-country matching is the minimal sufficient complexity required for clean causal identification.\n\n***"
  },
