    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "use a classical planner (RRT, A*) as a baseline or hybrid component",
      "add a privileged state estimator that provides obstacle positions not available through onboard sensors",
      "increase the number of demonstrations beyond 50 in any experimental condition",
      "evaluate in open or outdoor environments rather than cluttered indoor spaces"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Core Hypothesis\nAugmenting a reinforcement-learning (RL) policy by pre-training it on exactly 50 human teleoperation demonstrations prior to online training will significantly reduce the collision rate during point-to-point navigation in highly cluttered, unmapped indoor environments compared to an identical RL policy trained from scratch. \n\n### Minimal Viable Design\n**Platform & Sensors:** A simulated differential-drive mobile robot equipped exclusively with a 2D lidar and an RGB-D camera. The agent processes raw sensor streams directly (e.g., via CNN and RNN/LSTM) to output continuous velocity commands. Explicitly, the agent will not be provided with, nor will it construct, an occupancy grid or map during training or evaluation.\n\n**Environments:** \n*   *Training:* Simulated indoor environments matching the evaluation density constraint.\n*   *Evaluation:* 5 distinct, previously unseen indoor room layouts. Each layout is populated with at least 15 movable obstacles per 25 square meters of floor space.\n\n**Experimental Conditions:**\n1.  **Baseline (Pure RL):** Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) trained from scratch using a standard sparse/dense navigation reward function (e.g., +1 goal, -1 collision, -0.01 step penalty).\n2.  **Demonstration-Augmented (BC + RL):** The exact same PPO architecture is first pre-trained via Behavioral Cloning (BC) on exactly 50 successful human teleoperated point-to-point demonstration trajectories. Post-BC, the policy is fine-tuned using the identical PPO algorithm and identical reward function as the Baseline condition. \n\n**Evaluation Protocol:**\n*   100 point-to-point navigation trials (20 per distinct room layout).\n*   Maximum episode length is bounded at 120 seconds; any episode exceeding this limit is recorded as a failure.\n\n### Primary Outcome\nThe primary outcome is the difference in **collision rate** (reported alongside success rate, both with standard errors) across the 100 evaluation trials between the two conditions. Additionally, the evaluation will capture the mean time-to-goal for successful trials to be evaluated via an independent samples t-test (or Mann-Whitney U test), and will plot learning curves showing evaluation success and collision rates over the course of training steps.\n\n### Main Confound and Mitigation\n**Confound:** Catastrophic forgetting during the RL fine-tuning phase. When transitioning from BC to PPO, initial policy exploration can rapidly overwrite the safe navigation priors learned from the 50 human demonstrations, making the augmented policy indistinguishable from the baseline.\n**Mitigation:** Implement a conservative KL-divergence penalty or a learning-rate warmup during the early stages of PPO fine-tuning. This ensures the policy safely explores around the cloned human priors without destructively updating the weights before the RL value function stabilizes. \n\n### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Reward shaping via Generative Adversarial Imitation Learning (GAIL):** *Rejected due to a hard constraint.* GAIL trains a discriminator to provide supplementary reward signals based on the demonstrations. The brief explicitly enforces that \"both conditions must use the same RL algorithm and reward function,\" which GAIL would violate by dynamically altering the reward formulation for the augmented condition alone.\n2.  **Offline-to-online RL using an Implicit Q-Learning (IQL) replay buffer:** *Rejected due to complexity.* Utilizing IQL requires shifting to an off-policy/offline architecture, which increases algorithmic complexity. Pre-training a standard on-policy algorithm (PPO) with BC is the simplest, most direct method to test the utility of the demonstrations while strictly preserving identical RL phases.\n\n***"
  },
