    "domain": "computational social science",
    "objective": "Test whether exposure to algorithmically curated ideologically homogeneous content feeds on social media increases users' affective polarization scores over a 6-week period compared to exposure to ideologically diverse feeds.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "randomized controlled experiment with exactly 2 conditions (homogeneous feed vs diverse feed)",
      "sample size between 800 and 2000 adult U.S. social media users recruited via a platform partnership or browser extension",
      "affective polarization measured using the feeling thermometer difference score (in-party minus out-party warmth) administered pre and post",
      "intervention period must last exactly 6 weeks with compliance verified by feed exposure logs",
      "participants must not be informed of which condition they are assigned to during the study",
      "single platform only, no cross-platform analysis",
      "no deception beyond standard randomized assignment; study must receive IRB approval before data collection"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a survey-based measure of issue position extremity as a primary outcome alongside affective polarization",
      "include a no-intervention control group that receives their unmodified organic feed",
      "analyze behavioral outcomes such as sharing, commenting, or content creation during the study",
      "extend the study to non-U.S. populations or multiple countries"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Final Research Proposal\n\n**Core Hypothesis**\nExposure to an algorithmically curated ideologically homogeneous social media feed over exactly 6 weeks will result in a significantly larger increase in affective polarization compared to exposure to an algorithmically curated ideologically diverse feed.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design**\n*   **Sample & Recruitment:** N=1,500 adult U.S. Twitter/X users (targeting ~1,050 completers to remain safely within the 800\u20132000 constraint) recruited via a survey panel. Participants install a custom browser extension designed for Twitter/X desktop.\n*   **Pre-test:** Participants complete an IRB-approved onboarding survey to declare their party affiliation and record baseline affective polarization. \n*   **Intervention (Exactly 2 Conditions):** The extension randomly assigns users to one of two blinded conditions for exactly 6 weeks:\n    *   *Homogeneous Feed:* The extension dynamically alters the Twitter/X DOM to heavily prioritize political tweets from in-party sources while visually hiding out-party sources.\n    *   *Diverse Feed:* The extension reorganizes political tweets to enforce a strict 1:1 alternating visual balance of in-party and out-party sources. \n    *(Note: Non-political tweets are left untouched in both conditions to maintain usability, and no unmodified organic control group is included).*\n*   **Data Logging & Post-test:** The extension passively logs the metadata and source-level partisan scores of tweets that enter the user's visual viewport to verify compliance. At the exact 6-week mark, the extension disables curation and prompts the user to complete the post-test survey and view the debriefing.\n*   **Analysis:** \n    *   An Intention-to-Treat (ITT) OLS regression calculating the between-condition difference in pre-post change.\n    *   A pre-registered heterogeneity analysis testing baseline affective polarization as a moderator. \n\n**Primary Outcome**\nThe pre-post change in the feeling thermometer difference score. This is measured using standard ANES feeling thermometers, calculated as [In-Party Warmth: 0-100] minus [Out-Party Warmth: 0-100]. The success criteria will report the between-condition difference in this change accompanied by 95% confidence intervals. \n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation**\n*   **Confound:** *Device Substitution / Non-Compliance.* Participants may browse Twitter primarily on their mobile devices (where the desktop extension cannot alter the feed or log exposure), heavily diluting the treatment effect.\n*   **Mitigation:** We will estimate a Complier Average Causal Effect (CACE) using a Two-Stage Least Squares (2SLS) Instrumental Variable approach. We will use the randomized condition assignment to predict actual treatment dosage (the ratio of in-party vs. out-party tweets actually viewed, derived entirely from the desktop viewport exposure logs). This isolates the causal effect specifically for participants who complied by receiving the curated feed. To prevent extreme dropout, milestone-based financial incentives and automated reminders for zero-desktop-activity will be used.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n1.  **Platform Partnership:** Randomizing the algorithmic diversity parameter directly via a partnership with a social media company. \n    *   *Why rejected:* Highly vulnerable to corporate veto, sudden API changes, or PR-related cancellations. Relying on a corporate partner introduces fatal risks to guaranteeing the exact 6-week timeline, blinding rules, and sample bounds without adding scientific value over a researcher-controlled extension.\n2.  **Custom Simulated Mobile App:** Building a standalone app that feeds users scraped social media posts under researcher-controlled algorithms.\n    *   *Why rejected:* Low ecological validity. Requiring users to abandon their real social networks to scroll a \"sterile\" app for 6 weeks would cause severe attrition and artificial engagement patterns. The browser extension achieves the necessary algorithmic control while preserving the natural context of their existing social network.\n\n***"
  },
