    "domain": "criminal justice policy",
    "objective": "Test whether jurisdiction-level bail reform policies that eliminate cash bail for misdemeanors reduce the Black-white gap in pretrial detention rates without increasing failure-to-appear rates.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "quasi-experimental design using staggered policy adoption across jurisdictions, no randomization",
      "treatment defined as statutory or administrative elimination of cash bail for all misdemeanor charges, not partial reforms or judicial discretion changes",
      "pretrial detention measured from official jail booking records, not survey data",
      "racial disparity must be operationalized as the Black-white ratio of pretrial detention rates, not raw counts",
      "must include at least 4 reform-adopting jurisdictions and at least 4 comparison jurisdictions",
      "analysis must span at least 2 years pre-reform and 2 years post-reform",
      "failure-to-appear rate must be measured from court administrative records within the same jurisdictions"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a qualitative interview component with judges or defendants",
      "expand the outcome to include felony charges alongside misdemeanors",
      "incorporate recidivism or re-arrest as an outcome measure",
      "use individual-level risk assessment scores as a control variable"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nJurisdiction-level elimination of cash bail for all misdemeanor charges reduces the Black-white ratio of misdemeanor pretrial detention rates by reducing the use of secured-money release conditions, without increasing misdemeanor failure-to-appear rates beyond a pre-specified non-inferiority margin.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Design:** quasi-experimental staggered-adoption event-study difference-in-differences.\n- **Units:** jurisdiction-month panel.\n- **Sample:** at least 4 reform-adopting jurisdictions and at least 4 comparison jurisdictions.\n- **Time window:** minimum 24 months pre-reform and 24 months post-reform.\n- **Treatment:** first implementation date of a statutory or administrative policy that **eliminates cash bail for all misdemeanor charges**.\n- **Exclusions:** partial reforms, reforms limited to judicial discretion changes, ambiguous implementation dates, and jurisdictions lacking required administrative data.\n- **Data sources:**\n  - official jail booking records for misdemeanor bookings, race, and pretrial detention\n  - court administrative records for misdemeanor failure-to-appear\n- **Estimator:** stacked cohort event-study DiD or equivalent staggered-treatment estimator robust to treatment-timing heterogeneity, with jurisdiction and calendar-time fixed effects.\n- **Mechanism check:** estimate whether the reform reduces the misdemeanor secured-money release-condition rate, as the direct policy pathway.\n- **Required robustness:** re-estimate after excluding jurisdictions that simultaneously enacted other criminal justice reforms.\n- **Extra credibility check:** placebo policy-timing test using false pre-period reform dates.\n\n## Primary outcome\n**Black-white ratio of misdemeanor pretrial detention rates**, measured from official jail booking records at the jurisdiction-month level.\n\nConstruction:\n- Black detention rate = detained Black misdemeanor bookings / total Black misdemeanor bookings\n- White detention rate = detained White misdemeanor bookings / total White misdemeanor bookings\n- Primary disparity measure = Black detention rate / White detention rate\n\nReporting:\n- report the estimated post-reform change in this ratio with confidence intervals\n- estimation may use the log ratio for stability, but results should be translated back into ratio terms for presentation\n\nRequired co-primary policy tradeoff outcome:\n- misdemeanor failure-to-appear rate from court administrative records\n- report the post-reform change and assess non-inferiority against a margin specified ex ante\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n**Main confound:** jurisdictions may adopt bail reform alongside other criminal justice reforms or broader court/jail system changes that also affect detention disparity or failure-to-appear.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- strict legal coding so treatment includes only full misdemeanor cash-bail elimination\n- jurisdiction fixed effects to absorb time-invariant differences\n- calendar-time fixed effects to absorb common shocks\n- event-study leads to assess pre-trends\n- required robustness check excluding jurisdictions with simultaneous criminal justice reforms\n- placebo timing test to verify that effects do not appear around false pre-reform dates\n- mechanism check showing that secured-money release conditions decline when the reform takes effect, tightening the link between treatment and outcome\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Interrupted time series with matched comparison jurisdictions**\n   - Plausible and feasible, but less directly aligned with the staggered-adoption structure than event-study DiD.\n   - Matching adds design complexity without clearly improving identification over a clean staggered DiD with fixed effects and pre-trend checks.\n\n2. **Simpler staggered DiD without mechanism testing**\n   - More minimal, but easier for reviewers to criticize as a black-box treatment effect.\n   - The added mechanism test based on secured-money release conditions gives a clearer causal story while remaining feasible and tightly tied to the policy."
  },
