    "run_id": "c5c5608dc704",
    "brief_id": "epi_01",
    "domain": "epidemiology",
    "objective": "Determine whether long-term ambient PM2.5 exposure is associated with increased childhood asthma incidence after adjusting for socioeconomic and indoor-environment confounders.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "retrospective cohort design only, no randomization of exposure",
      "exposure metric must be annual-average PM2.5 at residential address, not self-reported",
      "cohort must include at least 5000 children aged 0-12",
      "must use ICD-coded asthma diagnoses, not survey-reported symptoms",
      "must adjust for at least household income and parental smoking status",
      "no proprietary air-quality datasets; only publicly available EPA AQS or equivalent"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add an indoor air-quality monitoring component to the study",
      "expand the outcome to include all respiratory conditions rather than asthma specifically",
      "incorporate genetic or biomarker data to explore biologic mechanisms"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "# Research Proposal: Long-Term Ambient PM2.5 Exposure and Childhood Asthma Incidence\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nChildren aged 0\u201312 with higher long-term residential exposure to ambient PM2.5 (measured as annual-average concentrations from publicly available monitoring data) will have a statistically significantly higher incidence of ICD-coded asthma diagnoses compared with children in lower-exposure environments, after adjusting for household income, parental smoking status, and other feasible socioeconomic confounders.\n\n*Directional prediction:* Each 1 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 increase in annual-average PM2.5 is associated with a measurable increase in asthma hazard (adjusted HR > 1.0, with a pre-specified minimum clinically meaningful threshold of HR \u2265 1.05 per 1 \u00b5g/m\u00b3).\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Study Architecture\n**Retrospective cohort** drawn from a state Medicaid or CHIP administrative claims database (e.g., a state with a high-density EPA AQS monitor network such as California, Texas, or Pennsylvania), linked to EPA AQS annual PM2.5 summary data (publicly available at https://www.epa.gov/aqs).\n\nThis design is chosen over the matched propensity-score cohort and the distributed-lag model (see *Two Plausible Alternatives*) because it:\n- Directly satisfies the retrospective cohort constraint without requiring the additional complexity of matching or lag-structure specification at the design stage\n- Uses a well-established survival-analysis framework that naturally accommodates time-varying exposure and produces the required HR with 95% CI\n- Minimises analytic assumptions relative to a distributed-lag nonlinear model while remaining sufficient to answer the objective\n\n### Population\n| Parameter | Specification |\n|-----------|--------------|\n| Age at entry | 0\u201312 years (index date = birth or first Medicaid enrollment, whichever is later) |\n| Minimum cohort size | \u2265 5,000 children (hard constraint); target N \u2248 50,000 to ensure \u2265 500 incident cases for stable HR estimation |\n| Observation window | At least 5 calendar years of claims data (e.g., 2010\u20132022) |\n| Exclusion | Prior asthma diagnosis before cohort entry; residence outside a ZIP code assignable to an EPA monitor within 50 km |\n\n### Exposure Assignment\n- **Metric:** Annual-average PM2.5 (\u00b5g/m\u00b3) at residential ZIP code centroid, derived from EPA AQS FRM/FEM monitor data (publicly available, 24-hour averages aggregated to annual means per 40 CFR Part 50)\n- **Spatial assignment:** Inverse-distance-weighted (IDW) interpolation from all EPA AQS monitors within 50 km of each child's residential ZIP code centroid; updated annually to create a **time-varying exposure variable**\n- **Exposure window (primary):** Mean annual PM2.5 averaged over the 3 years preceding each child's asthma diagnosis date (or censoring date); this 3-year window is pre-specified as the primary exposure metric\n- **No proprietary datasets used** (hard constraint satisfied; EPA AQS data are public-domain)\n\n### Outcome\n*See Primary Outcome section below.*\n\n### Primary Statistical Model \u2014 Pre-Specified\n**Cox proportional hazards model with time-varying PM2.5 exposure** (Anderson\u2013Gill counting-process formulation).\n\nPre-specification commitment: The model formula, covariate list, and sensitivity analyses described here are locked before any outcome data are accessed. A pre-registration record will be filed on OSF prior to data linkage.\n\n**Primary model equation (conceptual):**\n\n```\nh(t) = h\u2080(t) \u00b7 exp(\u03b2\u2081\u00b7PM2.5_tv + \u03b2\u2082\u00b7income_cat + \u03b2\u2083\u00b7parental_smoking\n                  + \u03b2\u2084\u00b7urban_rural + \u03b2\u2085\u00b7census_tract_poverty\n                  + \u03b2\u2086\u00b7birth_year + \u03b2\u2087\u00b7sex + \u03b2\u2088\u00b7race_ethnicity)\n```\n\n- `PM2.5_tv`: time-varying annual-average PM2.5 (continuous, \u00b5g/m\u00b3), lagged 1 year\n- Standard errors clustered at ZIP code level to account for spatial correlation\n- Proportional hazards assumption tested via Schoenfeld residuals; if violated for PM2.5, a time-interaction term is added as a pre-specified contingency\n\n### Sensitivity Analysis (Exposure Window Modification \u2014 Required by Success Criteria)\nTwo sensitivity analyses are pre-specified to test robustness to the exposure window definition:\n\n| Sensitivity Analysis | Exposure Window Change | Rationale |\n|----------------------|----------------------|-----------|\n| SA-1 | 1-year lag (single prior year) instead of 3-year average | Tests acute vs. cumulative exposure contribution |\n| SA-2 | Cumulative lifetime average from birth to event/censoring | Tests whether the entire exposure history matters more than recent exposure |\n\nResults are considered robust if the direction and statistical significance of the primary HR are preserved across both sensitivity analyses.\n\n### Confounding Mitigation\n*See Main Confound and Mitigation section below.*\n\n### Censoring Rules\nChildren are censored at: first ICD-coded asthma diagnosis (event), age 13, end of continuous Medicaid enrollment (gap > 90 days), death, or end of study period \u2014 whichever occurs first.\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n**Incident ICD-coded asthma diagnosis** defined as:\n- **ICD-10-CM:** J45.x (Asthma) \u2014 any subcategory (mild intermittent, mild persistent, moderate persistent, severe persistent, other/unspecified)\n- **ICD-9-CM (for data years < 2015):** 493.xx\n- **Case definition:** \u2265 2 outpatient claims with an asthma diagnosis code within a 12-month rolling window, OR \u2265 1 inpatient/ED encounter with a primary asthma diagnosis code \u2014 consistent with validated administrative-data asthma algorithms (Osborne et al., 2007; Langan et al., 2013)\n- **Incidence only:** Children with any asthma code in the 12 months before cohort entry are excluded\n\n**Reported effect measure:** Adjusted hazard ratio (aHR) with 95% confidence interval for a 1 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 increment in annual-average PM2.5, satisfying the success criterion for an HR/IRR with 95% CI.\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n### Primary Confounding Threat: Socioeconomic Status (SES) and Residential Sorting\n\n**Why it is the main threat:** Low-income families disproportionately reside near pollution sources (environmental justice pattern), and low SES independently increases asthma risk through crowding, housing quality, stress, and healthcare access. If unmeasured, this produces upward confounding that inflates the PM2.5\u2013asthma association.\n\n**Mitigation strategy (layered):**\n\n| Layer | Measure | Source |\n|-------|---------|--------|\n| Individual-level | Household income category (Medicaid eligibility tier as proxy: <100%, 100\u2013138%, 138\u2013200% FPL) | Claims enrollment file |\n| Individual-level | Parental smoking status (ICD-10 Z57.31, Z87.891, or tobacco cessation claims) | Claims diagnosis codes |\n| Area-level | Census tract poverty rate (% below FPL) | ACS 5-year estimates |\n| Area-level | Urban/rural classification (NCHS Urban-Rural scheme) | NCHS public data |\n| Area-level | Neighborhood deprivation index (NDI, Messer et al.) | Publicly derived from ACS |\n\n**Residual confounding acknowledgment:** Indoor air quality (e.g., mold, cockroach allergen, gas stoves) cannot be directly measured in claims data. This is explicitly acknowledged as a study limitation. An indirect mitigation is inclusion of housing-age data at the census-tract level (older housing stock correlates with indoor hazards) from ACS. *Note: an active indoor air monitoring component is prohibited by the banned-moves constraint and is not proposed.*\n\n**Parental smoking \u2014 hard constraint satisfied:** Parental smoking is captured via ICD-10/9 tobacco-exposure codes in the child's claims record (Z77.22, F17.x in parent-linked records where available, or passive smoke exposure codes), directly satisfying the mandatory adjustment requirement.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Matched Cohort with Propensity Score on High vs. Low PM2.5 ZIP Codes\n\n**Description:** Dichotomise ZIP codes into high-PM2.5 (top tertile) and low-PM2.5 (bottom tertile) zones; use propensity score matching (1:1 or 1:2) on SES, urbanicity, and demographic variables to create balanced comparison groups; estimate incidence rate ratio via Poisson regression.\n\n**Why not chosen:**\n- Dichotomisation discards exposure gradient information across the continuous PM2.5 range, reducing statistical power and masking dose-response shape\n- Matching on ZIP-code-level propensity scores conflates individual- and area-level confounding\n- The Cox time-varying model is simpler to pre-specify and more directly answers the causal question without the additional design-stage complexity of caliper selection and balance diagnostics\n- *Retained as a pre-specified secondary analysis* if the primary model's proportional hazards assumption is severely violated\n\n### Alternative 2: Distributed-Lag Nonlinear Model (DLNM) Linking Annual PM2.5 to Asthma Onset\n\n**Description:** Fit a DLNM (Gasparrini et al. framework) to characterise both the shape of the exposure\u2013response relationship and the lag structure (e.g., lags 0\u20135 years) simultaneously, using penalised splines for both dimensions.\n\n**Why not chosen:**\n- Requires pre-specification of lag-basis and exposure-basis spline knots, introducing researcher degrees of freedom that increase the risk of post-hoc specification if data are not fully blinded at design time\n- The added complexity is not necessary to answer the primary binary question (is PM2.5 associated with asthma incidence?) and is better suited to a follow-on mechanistic-timing study\n- Computationally demanding for a 50,000-child cohort with annual time-varying exposure; the simpler Cox model is sufficient for the stated objective\n- *Retained as a pre-specified exploratory analysis* to examine lag structure after the primary model is published\n\n---"
  },
