      "evaluate in open or outdoor environments rather than cluttered indoor spaces"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Core Hypothesis\nAugmenting a reinforcement-learning (RL) policy with human demonstrations via Behavioral Cloning (BC) seeds the agent with the demonstrator's \"cautious spatial routing manifold\" (a wider minimum clearance from obstacles). This inherited safety margin prevents the RL policy from converging on riskier, wall-hugging policies, directly causing a reduction in the zero-shot collision rate in unseen cluttered indoor environments compared to an RL policy trained from scratch.\n\n### Minimal Viable Design\n**Platform & Sensors:** A simulated differential-drive mobile base equipped strictly with a 2D LiDAR and an RGB-D camera. Navigation is entirely reactive; no prior maps are provided, and no occupancy grids are built during evaluation. State space includes downsampled LiDAR, RGB-D features, and a relative goal vector. Action space is continuous linear and angular velocity. \n\n**Environment Split:**\n*   **Training Layouts:** Randomized indoor rooms used strictly for demonstration collection and RL training.\n*   **Evaluation Layouts:** 5 completely distinct 5m x 5m rooms (25 square meters each) that the agent has never seen. Each contains exactly 15 movable obstacles (e.g., chairs, boxes) arranged to create narrow corridors.\n\n**Conditions (Using identical network architectures, PPO algorithms, and reward functions):**\n*   **Condition A (Baseline Pure RL):** Network weights are randomly initialized. Trained from scratch using PPO in the training layouts.\n*   **Condition B (BC-Augmented RL):** Exactly 50 point-to-point human teleoperation demonstrations are collected in the training layouts. The policy is pre-trained via Behavioral Cloning ($s_t \\rightarrow a_t$) on these 50 trajectories, then fine-tuned using the exact same PPO setup in the training layouts.\n*   **Shared Reward:** +10 (goal reached), -10 (collision/termination), +0.1 (decreasing Euclidean distance to goal), -0.01 (step penalty).\n\n**Protocol:** 100 point-to-point evaluation trials (20 per unseen evaluation layout). Maximum 120 seconds per trial. Both timeouts and collisions immediately terminate the trial as a failure.\n\n### Primary Outcome\n1.  **Core Metrics:** Report Mean \u00b1 Standard Error for **collision rate (%)** and **success rate (%)** across all 100 evaluation trials. \n2.  **Efficiency Metric:** Report mean **time-to-goal** strictly for successful trials, analyzed via an independent samples t-test between conditions.\n3.  **Learning Dynamics:** Plot a learning curve showing zero-shot evaluation collision and success rates (y-axis) vs. PPO environment steps (x-axis) for both conditions.\n4.  **Causal Mechanism Check:** Extract the **Mean Minimum Obstacle Clearance** (the closest distance to any obstacle per trial via 2D LiDAR). Compare clearance distributions between the Human Demos, Condition A, and Condition B to statistically prove Condition B inherited the human's safer spatial margins.\n\n### Main Confound and Mitigation\n**Confound:** *Room Memorization.* Reviewers could argue that the pre-trained policy (Condition B) simply memorized the specific spatial layouts of the training rooms faster than Condition A, meaning any observed reduction in collision rate is an artifact of overfitting rather than a generalized improvement in reactive obstacle avoidance.\n**Mitigation:** *Strict Train/Eval Spatial Split.* By collecting demonstrations and executing all PPO training in one set of rooms, but conducting the 100 evaluation trials strictly in 5 completely *unseen* layouts, we guarantee that the policy cannot rely on memorized maps. Any reduction in evaluation collision rate is definitively causal proof of generalized, reactive safety behaviors. \n\n### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Offline-to-Online RL using Implicit Q-Learning (IQL):** Using the 50 demos to seed an IQL replay buffer is a valid way to bypass policy collapse. However, end-to-end offline RL from high-dimensional visual inputs (RGB-D) is notoriously difficult to stabilize and requires high complexity. BC+PPO is the simpler, minimal viable mechanism to satisfy the objective.\n2.  **Inverse Dynamics Representation Pre-training:** We could have used the demonstrations to train an inverse dynamics model ($s_t, s_{t+1} \\rightarrow a_t$) to initialize the visual feature extractor. This guarantees the network *sees* the obstacles but does not causally guarantee the policy will inherit the human's *behavior* (avoiding them with wide margins) as strongly as direct Behavioral Cloning. \n\n***"
  },
