    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nProviding **written instructor feedback three times per week** on identical weekly problem sets, rather than **once per week**, will improve **end-of-term final exam performance** in an introductory university statistics course because the higher-frequency schedule increases the **speed and likelihood of feedback uptake** before subsequent learning tasks.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Design:** Quasi-experimental comparison of **two concurrent sections** of the same introductory university statistics course\n- **Instructor:** Same instructor teaches both sections\n- **Sample size:** At least **50 students per section**\n- **Intervention:**  \n  - Section A: written formative feedback **three times per week**  \n  - Section B: written formative feedback **once per week**\n- **Materials:** Same weekly problem sets, same lectures, same deadlines, same course content\n- **Baseline measure:** Short **week-1 pre-test** of prerequisite quantitative/statistics ability\n- **Mechanism measure:** Proportion of students who **access feedback within 48 hours**\n- **Duration:** Exactly **one academic term** (10\u201315 weeks)\n- **No extras:** No tutoring or supplementary instruction in either section\n- **Final exam:** Identical across sections and graded by a **blinded marker**\n- **Analysis:** Pre-registered **linear model / ANCOVA** predicting final exam score from condition while controlling for baseline pre-test score\n- **Effect size:** Report **Cohen\u2019s d** with confidence interval\n\n## Primary outcome\n**Final exam score** on the identical blinded-marked end-of-term exam, analyzed with a pre-registered linear model controlling for baseline ability.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n### Main confound\nBecause the design is quasi-experimental, the biggest threat is **baseline section differences** in prior ability or motivation.\n\n### Mitigation\n- Administer a **baseline pre-test** in week 1 and use it as the primary covariate\n- Keep **problem sets, lectures, deadlines, and final exam identical**\n- Standardize feedback using a **fixed rubric/template** so the only meaningful difference is **feedback frequency/timing**\n- Track **feedback uptake within 48 hours** to support the proposed mechanism\n- Use a **blinded marker** for the final exam to prevent outcome assessment bias\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Same section across two consecutive semesters using the prior semester as control**  \n   Not chosen because semester-to-semester changes in cohort composition, course context, and instructor drift would make the causal comparison less clean than concurrent sections.\n\n2. **Two concurrent sections with propensity score matching on prior GPA**  \n   Not chosen because GPA is a weaker baseline control than a direct pre-test of course-relevant ability, and matching would add complexity without improving the core mechanism story as much as the pre-test-adjusted ANCOVA."
