    "run_id": "c9b3bb4fb517",
    "brief_id": "cogsci_02",
    "domain": "cognitive psychology",
    "objective": "Test whether dual-task interference on a primary visual working memory task is larger when the concurrent secondary task is visual rather than auditory, holding secondary-task difficulty constant.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "within-subjects design with exactly 3 conditions (single-task baseline, visual dual-task, auditory dual-task)",
      "sample size between 40 and 80 participants",
      "secondary tasks must be matched on standalone accuracy within 5 percentage points via pilot calibration",
      "primary task must use a change-detection paradigm with set size 4",
      "no neuroimaging or physiological measures",
      "experiment must be completable in a single session under 90 minutes"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a cross-modal (audiovisual) secondary task condition",
      "vary the set size of the primary task across blocks",
      "include an individual-differences analysis correlating working memory capacity with interference magnitude"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Research Proposal**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**  \nDual-task interference on a primary visual working memory task is greater when the secondary task is visual rather than auditory\u2014**not due to general task difficulty or executive load**, but because the visual secondary task **competes for spatial attentional resources during the maintenance phase**, particularly when attentional demands **temporally overlap** with the need to maintain and refresh visual representations. This interference is **mechanistically tied to attentional competition**, as evidenced by:  \n- Larger d\u2032 reduction in the visual dual-task condition,  \n- A significant reduction in this effect when secondary-task onset is delayed (asynchronous trials), and  \n- Selective increases in attentional lapses (ex-Gaussian \u03bc) only under temporally overlapping visual load.\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**  \nA within-subjects, counterbalanced design with **three conditions**:  \n1. **Single-task**: participants perform a visual change-detection task alone.  \n2. **Visual dual-task**: participants perform the same primary task concurrently with a visual rapid serial search task containing spatially interfering distractors.  \n3. **Auditory dual-task**: participants perform the primary task concurrently with an auditory rapid deviant-detection task matched in difficulty but lacking spatial attentional demands.  \n\nEach condition includes **60 trials**. In the dual-task blocks, **80% of trials are synchronous** (secondary task begins 300 ms before primary task onset), and **20% are asynchronous** (secondary task begins 600 ms after primary array offset, i.e., during late retention). Trial types are intermixed and randomized.  \n\nParticipants: **N = 60**, within-subjects, tested in a single session.  \nAll tasks implemented in PsychoPy or equivalent; responses collected via keyboard.\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**  \n- **Change-detection sensitivity (d\u2032)** in the primary visual working memory task, computed separately for:  \n  - Each of the three main conditions (single, visual dual, auditory dual)  \n  - Synchronous vs. asynchronous trial types within dual-task conditions  \n- **Planned contrast**:  \n  - *Visual dual-task (synchronous) \u2013 auditory dual-task (synchronous)* interference difference  \n- Secondary outcomes:  \n  - ex-Gaussian parameters (\u03bc, \u03c3, \u03c4) from primary task RTs  \n  - NASA-TLX ratings (per block)  \n  - Secondary task accuracy and RT (to confirm matching)\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**  \n\n| **Confound** | **Risk** | **Mitigation Strategy** |\n|--------------|--------|--------------------------|\n| **Differences in perceived effort or executive load** | Could explain greater interference in visual condition, even if accuracy is matched | **NASA-TLX ratings** collected after each block to confirm subjective load is equivalent across dual-task conditions |\n| **General task difficulty mismatch** | Visual task may be inherently harder, biasing results | **Pilot calibration** ensures standalone accuracy within \u00b15 pp; parameters adjusted as needed |\n| **Temporal overlap confounded with encoding vs. maintenance** | Interference may reflect encoding competition, not maintenance | **Asynchronous trials** delay secondary task into retention phase; comparison isolates timing-specific effects |\n| **Attentional capture due to peripheral distractors (not task demands)** | Flankers may distract independently of task goals | Distractors are integral to target identification; asynchronous trials control for mere presence |\n| **Motor or response interference** | Dual responses may interfere | All secondary tasks require single keypress; primary task response is binary and separate in timing |\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**  \n\n1. **Storage-based secondary task (e.g., visual spatial memory span)**  \n   - *Why plausible*: Strong theoretical link to visuospatial sketchpad competition.  \n   - *Why rejected*: Hard to match difficulty with an auditory memory task without increasing cognitive load or set size (which would violate constraints). Risk of conflating memory load with attentional competition, weakening mechanistic clarity.\n\n2. **Sustained-attention secondary task (e.g., flicker detection in peripheral stream)**  \n   - *Why plausible*: Engages vigilance, a domain-general resource; could test attentional depletion.  \n   - *Why rejected*: Too passive; difficult to match in executive engagement and response structure. Risk of floor effects or habituation. Less precise control over attentional timing than rapid serial processing tasks.\n\n> **Chosen design wins** by isolating **spatial attentional competition** with **high temporal precision**, **matched executive demands**, and **embedded causal probes**, all within hard constraints.\n\n---"
  },
