    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a seeding or active replanting treatment to accelerate native recovery",
      "expand monitoring to include soil microbiome or nutrient cycling outcomes",
      "include a herbicide-treatment arm for comparison with mechanical removal"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Proposal:**\n\n**Core Hypothesis:**\nThe mechanical removal of a dominant invasive plant species will increase native plant percent cover by reducing competition for resources such as water, nutrients, and light, thereby creating a more conducive environment for native plant growth and survival.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design:**\nA paired treatment-control site design with at least 8 pairs of sites, where each pair consists of a treatment site with mechanical removal of the invasive species and a control site with no removal. Baseline data on native plant percent cover and resource availability will be collected before removal, and follow-up measurements will be taken at regular intervals over a 3-year period.\n\n**Primary Outcome:**\nThe primary outcome of interest is the change in native plant percent cover over time, measured as the difference in percent cover between treatment and control sites.\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation:**\nThe main confound identified is the potential for differences in site characteristics (e.g., soil type, topography) to influence the response of native plant communities to invasive species removal. To mitigate this confound, sites will be paired based on similar characteristics, and statistical models will control for any remaining differences.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen:**\n1. **Bayesian Change-Point Model:** This approach was considered but not chosen because it would require additional data and computational resources, and may not provide a clear advantage over the selected design in terms of understanding the treatment effect.\n2. **Permutation-Based Test:** This method was also considered but not chosen because it may not provide a robust test of the hypothesis, particularly if the data do not meet the assumptions of the test."
