    "domain": "computational social science",
    "objective": "Test whether exposure to algorithmically curated ideologically homogeneous content feeds on social media increases users' affective polarization scores over a 6-week period compared to exposure to ideologically diverse feeds.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "randomized controlled experiment with exactly 2 conditions (homogeneous feed vs diverse feed)",
      "sample size between 800 and 2000 adult U.S. social media users recruited via a platform partnership or browser extension",
      "affective polarization measured using the feeling thermometer difference score (in-party minus out-party warmth) administered pre and post",
      "intervention period must last exactly 6 weeks with compliance verified by feed exposure logs",
      "participants must not be informed of which condition they are assigned to during the study",
      "single platform only, no cross-platform analysis",
      "no deception beyond standard randomized assignment; study must receive IRB approval before data collection"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a survey-based measure of issue position extremity as a primary outcome alongside affective polarization",
      "include a no-intervention control group that receives their unmodified organic feed",
      "analyze behavioral outcomes such as sharing, commenting, or content creation during the study",
      "extend the study to non-U.S. populations or multiple countries"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Final Proposal\n\n**Core Hypothesis**\nOver a 6-week period, adult U.S. social media users exposed to an algorithmically curated, ideologically homogeneous feed will exhibit a significantly greater increase in affective polarization (measured via pre/post feeling thermometer difference scores) compared to users exposed to an ideologically diverse feed. \n\n**Minimal Viable Design**\n*   **Recruitment:** A quota-sampled online panel of 1,500 adult U.S. social media users (750 Democrats/leaners, 750 Republicans/leaners) recruited to install a \"Social Media Layout\" browser extension for the Bluesky web client. They are compensated weekly for maintaining extension uptime.\n*   **Intervention Strategy (Global Firehose):** To perfectly isolate the algorithm's causal effect, the extension suppresses the user\u2019s organic following network. Instead, it populates the timeline from a single, standardized real-time firehose of political posts (validated via AllSides domain ratings).\n*   **Conditions:** Participants are randomized into exactly two 6-week conditions, blinded as a layout test. \n    *   *Homogeneous Feed:* The algorithm filters the firehose to serve 100% in-party content.\n    *   *Diverse Feed:* The algorithm filters the firehose to strictly alternate 50/50 in-party and out-party content.\n*   **Compliance Verification:** The extension uses an `IntersectionObserver` to log \"meaningful dwell counts\"\u2014recording a compliance event only when a target post remains in the active, tab-focused viewport for 1.5 to 15 seconds.\n\n**Primary Outcome**\n*   **Measurement:** Affective polarization, administered at Week 0 and Week 6, strictly calculated as the feeling thermometer difference score (in-party warmth minus out-party warmth, each on a 0\u2013100 scale).\n*   **Main Effect Analysis:** An OLS regression predicting Week 6 difference scores based on treatment assignment (controlling for Week 0 baseline), reporting the between-condition difference in change with 95% confidence intervals.\n*   **CACE Estimation:** Two-Stage Least Squares (2SLS) estimating the Complier Average Causal Effect. Random assignment is the instrumental variable; the endogenous variable is the strictly logged *proportion of out-party posts meaningfully viewed*.\n*   **Heterogeneity Analysis:** An interaction model testing treatment assignment \u00d7 baseline affective polarization (Week 0) to evaluate backfire effects among highly polarized individuals.\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation**\n*   *Confound (The Organic Network Confound):* In traditional algorithmic experiments, merely re-ranking a user's organic timeline means the base pool of content varies wildly depending on who the user follows, making it impossible to separate the effect of the *algorithmic rule* from the *baseline network structure*. A secondary confound is differential attrition, where users assigned to the Diverse feed might drop out at higher rates due to psychological discomfort.\n*   *Mitigation:* Drawing from a centralized **global firehose** holds the baseline content universe mathematically constant for all 1,500 users; the ideological filter is the *only* varying parameter. To mitigate differential attrition without violating constraints or adding participant burden, we will calculate **Lee extreme-value bounds** to provide a worst-case true causal interval if attrition differs by >5% between conditions.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n1.  *Formal Platform Partnership:* Partnering with a tech company to randomize the diversity parameter of their core algorithm server-side. *Rejection justification:* High risk of corporate veto, restrictive NDAs, and limited access to millisecond-level granular viewport dwell logs required to prove strict cognitive exposure.\n2.  *DOM-Scraping Legacy Organic Feeds:* A browser extension that re-ranks existing timelines on legacy platforms (like Meta or Twitter/X) using HTML/CSS injection. *Rejection justification:* This fails to resolve the organic network confound, and frequent unauthorized platform UI updates consistently break DOM-scraping extensions, leading to severe, study-destroying attrition over a 6-week timeframe.\n\n---"
  },
