    "run_id": "ced199799b51",
    "brief_id": "nlp_01",
    "domain": "natural language processing",
    "objective": "Does few-shot in-context learning (5-shot) with a frozen 7B-parameter LLM achieve higher macro-F1 than task-specific fine-tuning of a 300M-parameter encoder model on text classification for languages with fewer than 10,000 labeled training examples?",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "Few-shot model must be a single 7B-parameter decoder-only LLM with no gradient updates",
      "Fine-tuned model must be a pre-trained multilingual encoder (e.g., XLM-R base, 270-300M parameters)",
      "Evaluation languages must have fewer than 10,000 labeled training examples in the chosen dataset",
      "Minimum 3 low-resource languages evaluated, each from a different language family",
      "Primary metric is macro-F1 on a held-out test set of at least 500 examples per language",
      "Few-shot examples selected randomly with a fixed seed; no manual curation or chain-of-thought"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "Using chain-of-thought, scratchpad, or multi-step reasoning in the few-shot prompt",
      "Fine-tuning the 7B LLM (LoRA, adapters, or full) instead of keeping it frozen",
      "Evaluating only on high-resource languages (more than 10,000 labeled examples)",
      "Ensembling multiple models or combining few-shot and fine-tuned predictions",
      "Translating test data into English before classification"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nIn low-resource multilingual topic classification, a **frozen 7B decoder-only LLM using 5-shot in-context learning** will perform comparatively well when **label semantics are available**, because it can exploit semantic alignment between the input text and the label names. A **fine-tuned multilingual encoder (~300M parameters, e.g. XLM-R base)** should improve more steadily as labeled data increase, because it learns a task-specific decision boundary from supervision.  \n\nThe causal prediction is that the frozen LLM\u2019s advantage, if present, should **shrink when label semantics are removed** and should be most visible in the **lowest-data regime**.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal viable design\n### Dataset\nUse a **single multilingual topic-classification benchmark**, preferably **SIB-200**.\n\n### Languages\nEvaluate **3 low-resource languages**, each:\n- with **fewer than 10,000 labeled training examples**\n- with **at least 500 held-out test examples**\n- from **different language families**\n\nA feasible set is:\n- **Yoruba**\n- **Tagalog**\n- **Burmese**\n\n### Models\n1. **Frozen few-shot model**\n   - one **7B decoder-only LLM**\n   - **5-shot** in-context learning\n   - **no gradient updates**\n   - few-shot examples selected **randomly with a fixed seed**\n   - no chain-of-thought, no scratchpad, no manual curation\n\n2. **Fine-tuned baseline**\n   - one **pre-trained multilingual encoder** such as **XLM-R base**\n   - standard supervised fine-tuning\n   - repeat with **3 random seeds** for initialization/training order\n\n### Protocol\nRun three conditions:\n- **Frozen LLM with meaningful labels**\n- **Frozen LLM with anonymized labels** as a causal control\n- **Fine-tuned encoder**\n\nFor the fine-tuned encoder, optionally include a small learning-curve subsample analysis:\n- 100\n- 300\n- 1,000\n- full available training data\n\nThis is the simplest way to show whether the comparison is driven by data scarcity.\n\n### Inference\n- Primary significance test: **paired bootstrap with 10,000 resamples**\n- Report **confidence intervals** for macro-F1 differences **for each language individually**\n- Assess reproducibility across **3 seeds** for both few-shot selection and fine-tuning\n\n---\n\n## Primary outcome\nThe primary outcome is **macro-F1 on the held-out test set** for each language.\n\nReport:\n- macro-F1 for frozen 7B ICL with meaningful labels\n- macro-F1 for frozen 7B ICL with anonymized labels\n- macro-F1 for fine-tuned encoder\n- per-language macro-F1 differences with confidence intervals\n- paired comparison across languages with bootstrap p-value\n\nThe main comparison is:\n- **frozen 7B meaningful-label ICL vs fine-tuned encoder**\n\nThe causal check is:\n- whether performance drops when labels are anonymized\n\n---\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n### Main confound\nA reviewer may argue that any advantage of the frozen LLM is due to **label wording / semantic priors**, not true few-shot learning or better multilingual understanding.\n\n### Mitigation\nUse a **prompt-level label anonymization control**:\n- keep the task, data, and evaluation fixed\n- only replace semantic label names with neutral IDs or arbitrary symbols in the frozen-LLM prompt\n\nIf performance declines materially under anonymized labels, that supports the mechanism that the frozen model relies on **semantic alignment** rather than a generic prompting artifact.\n\nThe fine-tuned encoder serves as the supervised baseline that is less dependent on label wording.\n\n---\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n### 1) Multi-benchmark design\nUse languages from two benchmarks, such as combining SIB-200 with another multilingual classification dataset.\n\n**Why not chosen:**  \nIt increases external validity, but it weakens causal clarity by introducing benchmark-specific differences in label structure, annotation style, and task difficulty.\n\n### 2) Varying the number of few-shot examples as the main analysis\nCompare 1-shot, 3-shot, and 5-shot prompting across languages.\n\n**Why not chosen:**  \nUseful as a secondary sensitivity analysis, but it does not sharpen the causal mechanism as directly as label anonymization. It also adds complexity without cleanly isolating why the frozen model succeeds.\n\n---"
  },
  {
    "item_number": 17,
    "run_id": "66aed500e122",
    "brief_id": "hci_01",
    "domain": "human-computer interaction",
    "objective": "Test whether delayed AI responses improve human research-question generation quality.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "human participants only",
      "budget under 25000 GBP",
      "no more than 2 experimental conditions",
      "must measure question quality with a predefined rubric",
      "no eye tracking or neuroimaging"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a third experimental condition",
      "add a think-aloud protocol or cognitive load measure",
      "expand to longitudinal deployment beyond a single session"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Research Proposal**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**\n\nArtificially delaying AI responses \u2014 when paired with an expectation-setting prompt \u2014 creates a reflective gap that increases self-generated anticipation, leading to deeper cognitive processing of information and, ultimately, higher-quality human-generated research questions. Specifically, we hypothesize that a 3-second delay in AI response, following a prompt to predict the answer, will result in research questions that go beyond the provided content compared to immediate responses, even when all other elements of the interaction are held constant.\n\nThis is not a test of \u201cslower AI is better\u201d but of **delay as a cognitive nudge**: a minimal intervention that shifts users from passive information consumers to active sense-makers.\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**\n\nA **between-subjects, single-session experiment** with **two conditions**:\n\n- **Condition 1 (Immediate):** After a 3-second window to enter an expected answer, the AI response appears immediately.  \n- **Condition 2 (Delayed):** After the same 3-second window, the AI response appears **3 seconds later** (i.e., a silent gap follows user input).\n\n**Participants:**  \n- N = 120 (60 per condition), recruited via Prolific (UK-based, screened for English fluency and education background if needed)  \n- One 45-minute session, compensated at \u00a311.25\n\n**Task:**  \nParticipants explore the topic **\u201cUrban Heat Islands and Public Health\u201d** through **6 structured inquiry rounds**. At each round:\n1. They choose one question from **3 pre-approved options** (e.g., \u201cWhat causes urban heat islands?\u201d)  \n2. They see:  \n   > \u201cThe AI is preparing a response. In the meantime, jot down what you *expect* the answer might be.\u201d  \n   (Text box open for 3 seconds)  \n3. The AI response appears \u2014 timing differs by condition\n\nAll participants receive **identical AI content** in the same sequence, depending only on their question choice. The interface is a simple web-based chat (React + Firebase), with no real-time AI generation (responses are pre-scripted).\n\nAt the end, participants generate **one original research question** they would investigate next.\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**\n\n**Research question quality**, assessed using a **5-point anchor-anchored rubric** that evaluates how far the final question goes beyond the information provided:\n\n| Level | Criteria |\n|-------|--------|\n| 1 | Repeats or rephrases AI content (minimal inference) |\n| 2 | Combines two ideas, but not testable |\n| 3 | Proposes a testable contrast or mechanism |\n| 4 | Integrates social and physical factors |\n| 5 | Novel, feasible, high-impact synthesis |\n\n- **Scoring process:**  \n  - Two **blinded raters** score all questions  \n  - Raters receive:  \n    - Final question  \n    - Full list of AI responses the participant saw  \n    - Rubric with predefined benchmark examples (Level 1, 3, 5)  \n  - Inter-rater reliability assessed (target ICC > 0.8)  \n- **Primary analysis:** Independent samples t-test on mean rubric score (Delayed vs. Immediate)\n\nThis outcome directly reflects the **cognitive added value** of the interaction, relative to controlled input.\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**\n\n- **Confound:** *Perceived responsiveness* \u2014 participants in the Delayed condition may view the AI as slower or less efficient, which could reduce engagement or motivation, independently of any cognitive benefit.  \n- **Mitigation:**  \n  - Measure perceived responsiveness post-task using a **3-item Likert scale** (e.g., \u201cThe AI responded quickly\u201d, 1\u20137)  \n  - Include score as a **covariate in ANCOVA**  \n  - Report correlation with primary outcome to assess confounding strength  \n  - Conduct sensitivity analysis excluding low-responsiveness raters\n\nThis ensures that any quality improvement is not attributable to perceived system performance.\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n\n1. **Immediate AI vs. No-AI Control**  \n   - Would test whether AI presence affects question quality, but **does not isolate the delay effect**.  \n   - Risk: conflates AI support with timing manipulation; fails to test the core hypothesis about reflective gaps.  \n   - Rejected to preserve focus on *delay* as the causal lever.\n\n2. **Short Delay (1s) vs. Long Delay (5s)**  \n   - Could test a dose-response relationship in delay duration.  \n   - Risk: reframes the study as about *optimal latency* rather than *mechanism of reflection*, weakening the theoretical contribution.  \n   - Also increases risk of interpreting results as preference-based rather than cognition-based.  \n   - Rejected to maintain a clean causal contrast and avoid implying a broader optimization agenda.\n\n---"
  },
