    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\n\nAt restoration sites within a single ecoregion, mechanical removal of one named dominant invasive plant species will reduce that species\u2019 percent cover and, within 3 years, increase native plant percent ground cover relative to untreated paired control sites. The causal story is that removal reduces invasive dominance first, creating release from space/structural suppression; native cover should then rise, while reinvasion should weaken that response.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n\n- **Focal species:** one named invasive plant species only\n- **Setting:** all sites within the same ecoregion\n- **Design:** paired before-after-control-impact design\n- **Replication:** at least 8 treatment-control site pairs; preferably 8\u201312 if feasible\n- **Pairing criteria:** match sites on baseline native cover, baseline focal invasive cover, management history, and major habitat features relevant to the ecoregion\n- **Pair retention rule:** retain only pairs where baseline native cover differs by no more than 10 percentage points between treatment and control\n- **Treatment:** mechanical removal only at treatment sites\n- **Control:** untreated paired sites\n- **No added treatments:** no herbicide, no seeding, no replanting\n\n### Sampling protocol\n- Establish permanent fixed quadrats at all sites before removal begins\n- Use the same quadrat number and placement logic within both sites of each pair\n- Measure in every quadrat at every time point:\n  - native plant percent ground cover\n  - focal invasive species percent cover\n\n### Timing\n- **T0:** baseline pre-removal\n- **T1:** early post-removal in the same growing season\n- **T2:** end of first growing season\n- **T3:** end of second growing season\n- **T4:** end of third growing season\n\nThis timing is the minimal addition needed to make the temporal sequence visible: invasive cover should drop before native cover increases.\n\n### Analysis\nUse a linear mixed-effects BACI model for native percent cover:\n- fixed effects: treatment, time, treatment \u00d7 time\n- random effect: site pair\n- repeated measure: time within site\n\nReport the treatment effect with a confidence interval, focusing on the treatment \u00d7 time interaction.\n\nUse a second mixed-effects model for invasive percent cover with the same structure to show whether treatment reduced invasive cover and whether reinvasion occurred over time.\n\n## Primary outcome\n\n**Native plant percent ground cover in fixed quadrats**, measured repeatedly from baseline through year 3.\n\nPrimary inferential target:\n- the difference in native-cover change over time between treated and untreated sites, estimated from the treatment \u00d7 time term in the mixed-effects model, with confidence interval\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n\n**Main confound:** pre-existing differences between treatment and control sites that could explain later native-cover differences independent of removal.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- paired design within one ecoregion\n- baseline data collected before removal\n- explicit matching on baseline native cover, invasive cover, management history, and relevant habitat features\n- pair retention only if baseline native cover differs by \u226410 percentage points\n- same fixed-quadrat approach and repeated schedule across both sites in each pair\n\nThis directly addresses the strongest causal criticism: that treated sites may have been more likely to recover even without intervention.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n\n### 1. Bayesian change-point model estimating lag to recovery at each site independently\n**Why plausible:** It could estimate when native cover begins to recover after removal and might be attractive for a novelty-focused paper.\n\n**Why not chosen:** It adds complexity and shifts emphasis away from the clearest required comparison: treatment versus paired control over time. It is less aligned with the success criterion requiring a treatment effect with confidence interval from a repeated-measures or mixed-effects model.\n\n### 2. Permutation-based test using site-level slopes of native cover over time\n**Why plausible:** It is robust and simple at the site level, especially with modest sample sizes.\n\n**Why not chosen:** It compresses the repeated-measures structure into a single slope per site and weakens the temporal causal story. It also uses less of the available information than a mixed-effects BACI model and is less effective for showing that invasive decline precedes native recovery."
