      "experiment must be completable in a single session under 90 minutes"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a cross-modal (audiovisual) secondary task condition",
      "vary the set size of the primary task across blocks",
      "include an individual-differences analysis correlating working memory capacity with interference magnitude"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\n\nDual-task interference on a primary visual working memory change-detection task will be greater when the concurrent secondary task is visual than when it is auditory, even when the two secondary tasks are calibrated to have equivalent standalone accuracy. Specifically, primary-task sensitivity (d\u2032) will be lowest in the visual dual-task condition, intermediate in the auditory dual-task condition, and highest in the single-task baseline.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n\n### Participants\n- **Target sample:** **60 adults**\n- **Allowed range satisfied:** 40\u201380\n- **Design:** within-subjects; every participant completes all 3 conditions\n\n### Conditions\nExactly 3 conditions:\n1. **Single-task baseline:** visual working memory change detection only\n2. **Visual dual-task:** primary task + visual secondary task\n3. **Auditory dual-task:** primary task + auditory secondary task\n\n### Primary task\n- **Paradigm:** visual change detection\n- **Set size:** exactly **4** items on every trial\n- **Stimuli:** for simplicity, 4 colored squares presented briefly at distinct locations\n- **Trial sequence:**\n  - fixation\n  - memory array of 4 colored squares\n  - retention interval\n  - test array\n  - same/different response\n- **Reason for choice:** this directly satisfies the required primary-task format while keeping the design minimal.\n\n### Secondary tasks\nTo preserve the main causal test while minimizing complexity, use **matched speeded discrimination tasks** in different modalities.\n\n#### Visual secondary task\n- During the retention interval, present a brief stream or single target at fixation or parafoveally requiring a speeded **visual discrimination** response, such as identifying whether a shape is one of two target categories.\n- The task should be demanding enough to consume visual-attentional resources but short enough to fit within the retention interval.\n\n#### Auditory secondary task\n- During the same retention interval, present a brief **auditory discrimination** requiring a speeded response, such as high vs low tone pattern classification.\n- Timing and response demands mirror the visual secondary task.\n\n### Pilot calibration\nA separate pilot is used to tune secondary-task parameters so that **standalone accuracy differs by no more than 5 percentage points** between visual and auditory tasks. Calibration can adjust:\n- stimulus duration\n- discriminability\n- response deadline\n\nThis is the simplest way to satisfy the matching constraint without changing the main experiment\u2019s structure.\n\n### Procedure\n- Single session, under 90 minutes\n- Participants complete practice first\n- Main task is organized into blocks by condition, with **counterbalanced order** across participants\n- Equal trial counts per condition\n\nA workable structure:\n- 3 blocks total, one per condition\n- ~60 trials per condition = 180 total trials\n- plus practice and short breaks\n\nThis should fit comfortably within 90 minutes.\n\n### Exclusion criterion\nExclude participants who perform **below chance in any single condition** on the primary task. This satisfies the success criterion directly. A simple operationalization is performance significantly below 50% correct or negative d\u2032 indicating systematic reversal; the exact rule should be prespecified.\n\n## Primary outcome\n\n### Main dependent variable\n- **Primary-task d\u2032** from the change-detection task, computed separately for:\n  - single-task baseline\n  - visual dual-task\n  - auditory dual-task\n\n### Main planned test\nUse a within-subject analysis comparing d\u2032 across the three conditions.\n\n### Planned contrast\nThe key planned contrast is the **interference difference**:\n- \\[(baseline d\u2032 \u2212 visual-dual d\u2032) \u2212 (baseline d\u2032 \u2212 auditory-dual d\u2032)\\]\n\nThis is algebraically equivalent to:\n- **auditory-dual d\u2032 \u2212 visual-dual d\u2032**\n\nA positive value supports the hypothesis that visual secondary-task interference is larger than auditory secondary-task interference.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n\n### Main confound\nThe biggest confound is that any visual secondary task may impair primary performance not because it draws on visual working memory resources per se, but because it causes **perceptual overlap or response competition** with the visual primary task.\n\n### Mitigation\nUse the **retention interval** for the secondary task so it does not overlap with encoding or probe display. Also:\n- keep the visual secondary stimuli spatially distinct from the memory array locations\n- use the same response format and timing demands across visual and auditory secondary tasks as much as possible\n- calibrate standalone accuracy to within 5 percentage points\n\nThis keeps the central comparison focused on modality-specific interference during maintenance rather than simple sensory masking.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n\n### 1. Storage-demanding visual secondary task\nA strong alternative would be a **visual spatial array memorization** task during the retention interval, paired with an auditory memory task. This could target storage-resource competition more directly.\n\n**Why not chosen:** it adds complexity because both secondary tasks would require their own memory maintenance and likely longer trial timing, making single-session feasibility and close difficulty matching harder. The simpler discrimination-based dual tasks are sufficient for the stated objective.\n\n### 2. Sustained-attention visual secondary task\nAnother option is a **continuous peripheral flicker monitoring** task during retention, paired with an auditory vigilance task.\n\n**Why not chosen:** vigilance tasks can introduce variability in engagement and are harder to equate tightly on standalone accuracy in a brief laboratory session. They also risk measuring lapses of sustained attention rather than dual-task interference per se."
  },
