    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nDual-task interference on visual working memory will be larger when the concurrent secondary task is visual than when it is auditory, even when the secondary tasks are equated for standalone difficulty. Specifically, visual secondary-task demands should reduce change-detection sensitivity more than auditory secondary-task demands because they compete more directly with visual maintenance and/or visual attentional resources.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n**Design:** Single-session, within-subjects experiment with exactly **3 conditions**:\n1. **Single-task baseline**: primary visual change-detection only  \n2. **Visual dual-task**: primary change-detection + visual secondary task  \n3. **Auditory dual-task**: primary change-detection + auditory secondary task  \n\n**Participants:** 40\u201380 healthy adults; target a practical sample of about **48\u201360** to balance power and session feasibility.\n\n**Primary task:**  \n- Standard **change-detection paradigm**  \n- **Set size fixed at 4** on every trial, across all conditions  \n- Measure accuracy sufficient to compute **d-prime**\n\n**Secondary tasks:**  \nUse two secondary tasks that are **matched in standalone accuracy within 5 percentage points via pilot calibration**:\n- **Visual secondary task:** a simple visual task that is clearly visual but not so complex that it changes the primary task structure. The cleanest option is a brief visual discrimination/search task with fixed difficulty.\n- **Auditory secondary task:** a matched auditory discrimination or monitoring task with equivalent response demands and timing.\n\nTo keep the design minimal and aligned with the brief, the secondary tasks should be calibrated in pilot testing until their standalone accuracies differ by no more than 5 percentage points.\n\n**Procedure:**  \n- Each participant completes all three conditions in counterbalanced order.\n- The entire session fits within **90 minutes** by using short blocks and brief instructions/practice.\n- Because the primary task is the same across conditions, the only manipulated factor is the modality of the concurrent secondary task.\n\n**Exclusion rule:**  \nExclude participants who perform **below chance on any single condition**. For change detection, this should be operationalized using the relevant accuracy threshold for the task scoring convention; the exclusion rule should be applied separately to each condition.\n\n## Primary outcome\nThe primary outcome is **change-detection sensitivity (d-prime)** computed separately for:\n- baseline\n- visual dual-task\n- auditory dual-task\n\nThe planned inferential focus is:\n1. Overall condition effect on d-prime across the three conditions\n2. A **planned contrast** testing whether **visual-dual minus baseline interference exceeds auditory-dual minus baseline interference**  \n   - equivalently, whether the decrement in d-prime is larger in the visual dual-task than in the auditory dual-task\n\nThis directly tests the target claim while preserving the required three-condition within-subjects structure.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n**Main confound:** The visual and auditory secondary tasks may differ in difficulty, making any modality effect ambiguous. If the visual task is harder, larger interference could reflect difficulty rather than modality-specific competition.\n\n**Mitigation:**  \n- Use **pilot calibration** to match standalone secondary-task accuracy within **5 percentage points** before the main study.\n- Keep response format, timing, and trial structure as similar as possible across modalities.\n- Use the same number of secondary-task trials and comparable pacing in both dual-task conditions.\n- Verify in the main study that secondary-task performance remains approximately matched; if it drifts, report it as a limitation rather than altering the design.\n\nThis is the critical control needed to support a modality-specific interpretation.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Storage-demanding visual secondary task**  \n   - Example: brief spatial array memorization  \n   - Why not chosen: it is a plausible visual load, but it risks being too specifically tied to visual working memory storage rather than general visual-vs-auditory interference. That makes the interpretation less clean if the goal is modality comparison at matched difficulty.\n\n2. **Processing-demanding visual secondary task**  \n   - Example: rapid visual search with response selection  \n   - Why not chosen: it may better tax executive control, but it also introduces stronger strategic and decisional demands that could make the visual task harder to match to the auditory task within the 5-point accuracy constraint.\n\nA sustained-attention visual monitoring task or a dual-component visual task are also plausible, but the simplest defensible choice for this brief is a single calibrated visual secondary task paired with a calibrated auditory counterpart."
