    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nMechanical removal of a single dominant invasive plant species will increase native plant percent cover within 3 years, relative to untreated paired controls, because removal reduces invasive occupancy and frees space for native recovery.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Design:** paired before-after-control-impact (BACI) field study\n- **Sites:** at least **8 treatment-control site pairs**\n- **Ecoregion:** all sites within the same ecoregion\n- **Target:** one **named invasive plant species**\n- **Treatment:** **mechanical removal only**\n- **Control:** no removal\n- **Baseline:** measure before removal begins\n- **Monitoring:** repeated measurements over 3 years in **fixed quadrats**\n- **Variables measured at every time point:**\n  - native plant percent ground cover\n  - invasive plant percent cover\n\n## Primary outcome\nChange in **native plant percent ground cover** over time, estimated with a **mixed-effects or repeated-measures model** that reports a **treatment effect with confidence interval**.\n\nRecommended primary model:\n- response: native percent cover\n- fixed effects: treatment, time, treatment \u00d7 time\n- random effect: site pair\n- repeated measure: year\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n**Main confound:** baseline differences between treatment and control sites in native cover or site quality.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- pair sites within the same ecoregion\n- collect baseline data before removal\n- verify that baseline native cover differs by **no more than 10 percentage points**\n- use site pair as a random effect in the model\n- track invasive cover at every time point to distinguish treatment effects from reinvasion\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Bayesian change-point model**  \n   Could estimate when native recovery begins after removal, but it is less direct than the BACI mixed model for the main causal question.\n\n2. **Permutation-based test of site-level slopes**  \n   Could compare native-cover trajectories nonparametrically, but it is less flexible for repeated measures and baseline adjustment."
