    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a third method or hybrid that combines domain randomization and real-world fine-tuning",
      "use a learned grasp quality estimator (e.g., GQ-CNN) as the base policy architecture",
      "expand the test set to include deformable or articulated objects",
      "collect more than 500 real-world grasps for the fine-tuning condition"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Core Hypothesis\nThe core hypothesis of this research is that sim-to-real transfer using domain randomization will achieve a higher grasp success rate on novel household objects compared to fine-tuning a simulation-pretrained policy on a limited number of real-world grasps (500 or fewer). This hypothesis is grounded in the idea that domain randomization can enhance the robustness and generalizability of grasping policies by exposing them to a wide range of simulated environments and conditions.\n\n### Minimal Viable Design\nThe minimal viable design to test this hypothesis involves:\n1. **Base Policy Architecture and Simulation-Pretrained Weights**: Both methods (domain randomization and fine-tuning) will start from the same base policy architecture and simulation-pretrained weights to ensure a fair comparison.\n2. **Domain Randomization**: Utilize Isaac Gym for domain randomization, varying at least texture, lighting, object mass, and friction parameters. This approach allows for efficient and automatic domain parameter sampling.\n3. **Fine-Tuning**: Fine-tune the simulation-pretrained policy on real-world grasp data, with a budget cap of 500 grasp attempts.\n4. **Robot Hardware**: Employ a single 6-DOF or 7-DOF arm with a parallel-jaw gripper for both methods.\n5. **Evaluation**: Evaluate both methods on exactly 30 previously unseen household objects, with each object tested with at least 10 grasp attempts per method.\n6. **Success Criteria**: Define grasp success as lifting the object at least 10 cm above the table and holding for 3 seconds.\n\n### Primary Outcome\nThe primary outcome of this study will be the comparison of per-method grasp success rates with 95% confidence intervals across the 30 test objects, along with a breakdown of success rates by object difficulty category (small, medium, large) to provide insights into how method performance varies with object size.\n\n### Main Confound and Mitigation\nA main confound in this study could be the difference in adaptation to real-world conditions between the domain randomization method and the fine-tuning method. To mitigate this, ensuring that both methods start from the same base policy and are evaluated under the same conditions (e.g., same robot, same test objects) is crucial. Additionally, using a robust evaluation metric (e.g., grasp success rate with confidence intervals) helps to minimize the impact of potential confounds.\n\n### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1. **NVIDIA Omniverse for Photorealistic Rendering-Based Domain Randomization**: While this approach could offer more realistic visual randomization, it might not significantly impact grasp success rates, which are more dependent on physical parameters like friction and mass.\n2. **Dynamics Randomization in MuJoCo with DAgger Fine-Tuning**: This method focuses solely on dynamics without visual randomization and uses a different fine-tuning approach. It's an interesting alternative but might not fully capture the benefits of comprehensive domain randomization."
