    "domain": "social psychology",
    "objective": "Test whether structured intergroup contact with outgroup members reduces implicit racial bias as measured by the Implicit Association Test.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "randomized controlled trial with at least 2 arms",
      "sample size of at least 200 participants per arm",
      "must use the standard race IAT hosted on Project Implicit infrastructure",
      "intervention must be a single session lasting no more than 90 minutes",
      "no deception beyond standard IAT instructions",
      "follow-up measurement at exactly 2 weeks post-intervention"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add an explicit bias measure such as a feeling thermometer or social distance scale",
      "extend the intervention to multiple sessions or a longitudinal program",
      "include a neuroimaging or physiological arousal component"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Final Research Proposal: The Cooperative Dyad Effect\n\n**Core Hypothesis**\nA single 90-minute session of structured, interdependent cooperative problem-solving with an outgroup partner will produce a statistically significant reduction in implicit racial bias (as measured by the Race IAT) at a 14-day follow-up, compared to a solo task control, with a minimum effect size of Cohen\u2019s $d = 0.20$.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design**\nThe study is a two-arm, parallel-group Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT) with $N=900$ (450 per arm). \n*   **Experimental Arm:** Participants engage in a 45-minute \"Information Exchange\" task requiring mandatory cooperation with an outgroup partner to solve a logistical puzzle.\n*   **Control Arm:** Participants complete the same puzzle independently.\n*   **Procedure:** Baseline IAT $\\rightarrow$ Randomized Task (45 min) $\\rightarrow$ Manipulation Check $\\rightarrow$ Follow-up IAT (14 days exactly).\n\n**Primary Outcome**\nThe primary outcome is the difference in the **Race IAT $D_{600}$ score** between baseline and the 14-day follow-up. Analysis will be conducted via **ANCOVA**, using the baseline $D_{600}$ score as a covariate to increase precision and account for the IAT\u2019s low test-retest reliability.\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation**\n*   **Confound:** The \"Novelty/Attention\" effect, where the mere presence of a new interpersonal interaction (regardless of content) temporarily lowers bias scores, conflating general social arousal with intergroup contact effects.\n*   **Mitigation:** By keeping the task structure identical across arms (cooperative vs. solo) and specifically measuring the perceived \"cooperative dependency\" in the manipulation check, we isolate the variance attributable to the *nature* of the intergroup contact rather than the mere presence of a social partner.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n1.  **Virtual Reality (VR) Shared Experience:** Rejected due to excessive technical variance and potential \"novelty effects\" from hardware use, which could introduce uncontrolled artifacts into the implicit bias measurement.\n2.  **Structured Perspective-Taking Conversation:** Rejected because open-ended conversation, even when structured, is prone to uncontrollable variability in quality and content between participants, threatening the internal validity of the \"cooperative\" condition compared to a rigid puzzle-solving task."
  },
