    "item_number": 25,
    "run_id": "0c81e1f56d8b",
    "brief_id": "edu_01",
    "domain": "education",
    "objective": "Test whether providing written formative feedback three times per week instead of once per week improves end-of-term exam scores in an introductory university statistics course.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "quasi-experimental design comparing two sections of the same course taught by the same instructor",
      "minimum 50 students per section",
      "feedback must be written comments on weekly problem sets, not grades or scores alone",
      "final exam must be identical across both sections and graded by a blinded marker",
      "study duration is exactly one academic term (10 to 15 weeks)",
      "no additional tutoring or supplementary instruction offered to either group"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a third section receiving peer feedback instead of instructor feedback",
      "measure student satisfaction or perceived learning as a co-primary outcome",
      "vary the content or difficulty of the problem sets between sections",
      "use automated AI-generated feedback instead of instructor-written feedback"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "# Final Research Proposal\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nWritten formative feedback delivered three times per week produces higher end-of-term exam scores than written formative feedback delivered once per week in an introductory university statistics course. The effect is hypothesised to operate through error-consolidation prevention: shorter intervals between committing an error and receiving corrective written feedback reduce the number of occasions on which an incorrect procedure is practised and reinforced before correction, producing a faster within-term error-elimination trajectory that compounds into a measurable exam score advantage. Feedback volume \u2014 total written comment length across the term \u2014 is held constant, so any observed difference is attributable to temporal distribution, not amount.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Structure\nTwo concurrent sections of the same introductory statistics course, taught by the same instructor in the same term. Before the term begins, a coin flip assigns one section to the control condition and one to the treatment condition. Target enrolment is 60 students per section (minimum 50). The term runs for 13 weeks.\n\n### Manipulation\nThe sole difference between conditions is how problem-set work is batched and how often written feedback is returned.\n\n| Feature | Control \u2014 Massed (1\u00d7/week) | Treatment \u2014 Spaced (3\u00d7/week) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Submissions per week | 1 (Friday) | 3 (Mon, Wed, Fri) |\n| Problems per submission | 9 | 3 |\n| Total problems per week | 9 | 9 |\n| Total problems across term | 99 | 99 |\n| Feedback turnaround | \u226448 hours | \u226412 hours |\n| Written comments provided | Yes | Yes |\n| Grades or scores provided | No | No |\n| Content and difficulty | Identical | Identical |\n\nThe manipulation is temporal structure only. Problem content, total volume, difficulty, and instructor identity are invariant across conditions.\n\n### Baseline Measure\nA 20-item validated quantitative reasoning pre-test is administered in Week 1, before any problem sets are assigned. It serves as the primary covariate in all confirmatory models and as a proxy for prior statistical aptitude.\n\n### Fidelity Monitoring\nSix fidelity checks run continuously across the term, derived from existing data streams with no new student burden:\n\n| Check | What It Rules Out | Threshold |\n|---|---|---|\n| Feedback word count (LMS metadata) | Volume differences between conditions | Mean \u00b1 20% across conditions |\n| Feedback turnaround time (LMS timestamps) | Differential promptness beyond manipulation | Control \u226448 hrs; Treatment \u226412 hrs |\n| Problem content equivalence (independent rater) | Content or difficulty variation | 100% learning-objective coverage parity |\n| Instructor time investment (self-logged hours) | Differential instructor effort | Reported as sensitivity covariate in all models |\n| Error taxonomy coverage | Incomplete mechanism measurement | \u226585% of feedback comments mappable to pre-registered taxonomy |\n| Submission completion rate equivalence (LMS logs) | Differential within-term effort between conditions | Mann-Whitney U reported; added to all models if unequal |\n\n### Pre-Registration\nAll confirmatory models, the error taxonomy, the causal DAG, the equivalence bounds, and the sampling procedure for the feedback quality audit are lodged on OSF before the term begins and before any outcome data are observed.\n\n### Contamination Control\nSections are scheduled at non-overlapping times. An end-of-term disclosure item asks students whether they shared or received feedback comments from a student in the other section. Confirmed contamination cases are flagged; the primary analysis is intention-to-treat; a sensitivity analysis excludes confirmed cases.\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n**Final examination score (0\u2013100)**, administered simultaneously to both sections in Week 13.\n\n- Exam is identical across sections, drawn from a pre-existing validated item bank to prevent instructor construction bias.\n- Scripts are anonymised immediately after collection, with section identifiers removed.\n- A blinded external marker grades all scripts without knowledge of condition assignment.\n- Inter-rater reliability is checked on a 20% random sample of scripts; target Cohen's \u03ba \u2265 0.80.\n\n### Confirmatory Analytical Plan\n\n**Model 1 \u2014 ANCOVA Superiority Test (primary)**\n```\nFinalExamScore_i = \u03b20 + \u03b21\u00b7Condition_i + \u03b22\u00b7PreTestScore_i + \u03b5_i\n```\n`Condition_i` = 1 (treatment), 0 (control); `PreTestScore_i` mean-centred. Standard errors reported both conventionally and clustered at the section level, with explicit acknowledgement of the two-cluster limitation. Primary inferential target is \u03b21. Effect size reported as Cohen's *d* with 95% CI via non-central *t* distribution.\n\n**Model 2 \u2014 Equivalence Test (co-primary)**\nThe 90% CI for Cohen's *d* is tested against pre-registered equivalence bounds [\u22120.20, +0.20]. If the CI falls entirely within these bounds, the null result is declared interpretable \u2014 feedback frequency produces no educationally meaningful difference. This is pre-registered as a co-equal primary analysis, making the study publishable regardless of direction.\n\n**Model 3 \u2014 FQI-Adjusted Sensitivity Model (pre-registered robustness check)**\n```\nFinalExamScore_i = \u03b20 + \u03b21\u00b7Condition_i + \u03b22\u00b7PreTestScore_i \n                   + \u03b23\u00b7MeanFQI_i + \u03b5_i\n```\n`MeanFQI_i` is each student's mean Feedback Quality Index score across a 30% stratified random sample of their received feedback comments, rated by two blinded external raters (ICC target \u2265 0.75) using a validated four-dimension rubric (specificity, actionability, elaboration, tone; scored 0\u201311). Models 1 and 3 are reported side by side in a single table. If \u03b21 is stable across both models, the frequency interpretation stands. If \u03b21 attenuates substantially, the manuscript reports this transparently and reframes the finding as a quality-adjusted frequency effect.\n\n**Model 4 \u2014 Effort-Adjusted Error-Elimination Mediation (pre-registered secondary)**\n\nGrounded in a pre-registered causal DAG with two identified backdoor paths \u2014 prior ability (blocked by pre-test covariate) and within-term effort (blocked by submission completion rate) \u2014 and an explicit written assumption audit stating that no further unmeasured common causes are assumed.\n\n```\nStage 1:\nErrorEliminationRate_i = \u03b10 + \u03b11\u00b7Condition_i \n                          + \u03b12\u00b7PreTestScore_i \n                          + \u03b13\u00b7CompletionRate_i + \u03b6_i\n\nStage 2:\nFinalExamScore_i = \u03b20 + \u03b21\u00b7Condition_i \n                   + \u03b22\u00b7ErrorEliminationRate_i\n                   + \u03b23\u00b7PreTestScore_i \n                   + \u03b24\u00b7CompletionRate_i + \u03b5_i\n```\n\n`ErrorEliminationRate_i` = proportion of previously flagged error types (from a pre-registered 12\u201315 item taxonomy) that do not recur in subsequent submissions, averaged across the term, coded by a blinded research assistant. `CompletionRate_i` = proportion of assigned problem sets submitted, derived from LMS logs.\n\nBootstrapped indirect effect: 5,000 iterations, bias-corrected 95% CI.\n\n**Model 5 \u2014 Temporal Segmentation Check (pre-registered secondary)**\n```\nFinalExamScore_i = \u03b20 + \u03b21\u00b7EarlyEliminationRate_i \n                   + \u03b22\u00b7LateEliminationRate_i\n                   + \u03b23\u00b7PreTestScore_i \n                   + \u03b24\u00b7CompletionRate_i + \u03b5_i\n```\nEarly = Weeks 2\u20136; Late = Weeks 7\u201312. If \u03b21 > 0 and significant after controlling for \u03b22, early error elimination predicts exam scores independently of late-term performance \u2014 consistent with a cumulative causal mechanism rather than a concurrent ability proxy. If \u03b21 \u2248 0, the manuscript reports this as evidence against the temporal mechanism claim.\n\n**Model 6 \u2014 Uptake Latency Comparison (pre-registered secondary)**\nMean hours between feedback release and first student LMS access, per student, compared between conditions via Mann-Whitney U. Reported as a process descriptor characterising the feedback loop. Satisfies the success criterion for a feedback uptake measure.\n\n**Model 7 \u2014 Moderation by Prior Ability (exploratory, supplementary only)**\n`Condition \u00d7 PreTestScore` interaction added to Model 1. Hypothesis-generating; reported in one supplementary paragraph with no main-text discussion beyond a single locating sentence.\n\n### Results Section Structure\n\n| Section | Content | Models |\n|---|---|---|\n| 3.1 | Fidelity, effort equivalence, quality audit | Descriptive + FQI Mann-Whitney |\n| 3.2 | Primary outcome | Models 1\u20132 |\n| 3.3 | Robustness to quality differences | Model 3 alongside Model 1 |\n| 3.4 | Causal mechanism (DAG \u2192 mediation \u2192 temporal check) | Models 4\u20135 |\n| 3.5 | Process outcomes | Model 6 |\n| S1 | Prior ability moderation | Model 7 |\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n### The Confound\nThe instructor knows which section each student belongs to. When writing feedback more frequently for the treatment section, the instructor may \u2014 without awareness \u2014 produce qualitatively better comments: more diagnostic, more specific, more actionable. This would occur because more frequent contact with each student's work creates a richer model of that student's error profile. If this happens, the treatment section receives both higher-frequency *and* higher-quality feedback, and any exam score advantage cannot be attributed to frequency alone.\n\nThis confound is not resolved by word-count parity. A comment of identical length can vary substantially in diagnostic quality. It is not resolved by instructor time logging. More time does not guarantee quality differences, nor does equal time guarantee quality equivalence. It is the most serious remaining threat to the internal validity of the frequency interpretation, and it is the one threat that cannot be eliminated by design \u2014 only measured and adjusted for.\n\n### The Mitigation: Blinded Feedback Quality Audit\n\n**Sampling:** After the term ends and before any outcome data are analysed, a 30% stratified random sample of all feedback instances is drawn, stratified by week (early, mid, late term) and by student pre-test quartile. With 60 students per section and 11 active feedback weeks, this yields approximately 200 sampled feedback instances per section (400 total).\n\n**Blinding:** All identifying information \u2014 student name, section label, submission date, week number \u2014 is stripped from feedback comments. Comments are presented to raters in randomised order, not grouped by student or section. Raters are graduate students in education or psychology with no connection to the course, told only that they are rating written feedback comments, with no knowledge that a frequency manipulation exists.\n\n**Instrument:** The Feedback Quality Index (FQI; Winstone et al., 2019, adapted), a validated four-dimension rubric:\n\n| Dimension | What It Captures | Scale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Specificity | Precise identification of error location and nature | 0\u20133 |\n| Actionability | Clear instruction on what to do differently | 0\u20133 |\n| Elaboration | Conceptual explanation of why the error matters | 0\u20133 |\n| Tone | Constructive rather than evaluative framing | 0\u20132 |\n\nTotal FQI per comment: 0\u201311. Two raters score all 400 comments independently; disagreements resolved by discussion; final score is the mean of both ratings. Target ICC \u2265 0.75.\n\n**Analysis:** Mann-Whitney U test comparing mean FQI scores between conditions. If the 95% CI for the condition difference includes zero, quality equivalence is supported. The FQI-adjusted sensitivity model (Model 3) then tests whether the exam score effect survives quality control. If it does, the frequency interpretation is substantially strengthened. If it does not, the result is reported honestly as a quality-adjusted frequency effect \u2014 which is itself a theoretically meaningful finding about what makes feedback work.\n\n**The mitigation converts the confound from a fatal flaw into a reported finding.** A reviewer who raises the quality concern is answered by a pre-registered analysis, not a post-hoc defence.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Consecutive-Semester Design (Prior Semester as Control)\nThe same section of the course is taught in two consecutive semesters. The first semester serves as the control (1\u00d7/week feedback); the second serves as the treatment (3\u00d7/week feedback). All other features are held constant.\n\n**Why it was not chosen:** Cohort differences between semesters are uncontrolled and uncontrollable. Students who enrol in the same course in consecutive semesters differ systematically in prior GPA, course load, and academic standing. Seasonal and curricular drift \u2014 changes in the broader course sequence, institutional calendar, or instructor familiarity with the manipulation \u2014 are confounded with the treatment. A pre-test covariate partially addresses ability differences but cannot address the structural non-equivalence of the cohorts. The concurrent two-section design, despite its two-cluster limitation, is strictly preferable because both cohorts are exposed to the same external conditions simultaneously.\n\n### Alternative 2: Propensity Score Matching on Prior GPA Without a Pre-Test\nTwo concurrent sections are used, but instead of administering a quantitative reasoning pre-test, students are matched across sections on institutional prior GPA using propensity score matching. The matched sample is then analysed with a simple between-groups *t*-test.\n\n**Why it was not chosen:** Propensity score matching on a single administrative variable (GPA) is a weaker adjustment than ANCOVA on a domain-specific pre-test for two reasons. First, GPA is a broad composite that does not capture the specific quantitative reasoning ability most relevant to introductory statistics performance; the pre-test provides a more precise and theoretically relevant covariate. Second, matching discards unmatched students, reducing effective sample size below the 50-per-section minimum in a worst-case scenario and reducing statistical power in all scenarios. ANCOVA with a continuous pre-test covariate retains all students, uses the full variance in baseline ability, and is more efficient when the covariate\u2013outcome correlation is strong \u2014 which it is expected to be in a quantitative course. Propensity matching would be the preferred approach only if no pre-test were feasible, which is not the case here.\n\n---"
  },
  {
