    "objective": "Does augmenting training data with back-translation (English to pivot language and back) improve macro-F1 for sentiment analysis when the test domain differs from the training domain by more than 5 points of baseline F1 drop?",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "Back-translation uses a single pivot language; no multi-pivot or paraphrase models",
      "Source training domain and target test domain must be explicitly different (e.g., electronics reviews vs restaurant reviews)",
      "Baseline model is a fine-tuned encoder of 110-130M parameters (e.g., BERT-base or equivalent)",
      "Augmented data must not exceed 2x the original training set size",
      "Domain shift confirmed by at least a 5-point macro-F1 drop when the baseline trained on source is evaluated on target",
      "Minimum 3 domain-shift pairs evaluated"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "Using generative LLM paraphrasing (e.g., GPT-based rewriting) instead of back-translation",
      "Including any target-domain labeled data in training",
      "Applying domain-adaptive pre-training (DAPT) on unlabeled target-domain text",
      "Filtering or curating back-translated samples by quality score"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Proposal**\n\n**Core Hypothesis**\nThe core hypothesis of this study is that back-translation using a pivot language with distinct typological characteristics (e.g., German and Chinese) will improve sentiment analysis performance across domain shifts, and that the effectiveness of back-translation will be influenced by the pivot language typology.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design**\nThe minimal viable design for this study consists of:\n\n1. Selecting two pivot languages (German and Chinese) with distinct typological characteristics\n2. Using a single dataset (multi-domain Amazon reviews) to create three domain-shift pairs with a confirmed baseline F1 drop of at least 5 points\n3. Fine-tuning a pre-trained BERT-base model (110M parameters) on the source domain for each pair, using a domain-adversarial training objective\n4. Translating the source domain training data to the two pivot languages and back to English, creating augmented data that does not exceed 2x the original training set size\n5. Evaluating the baseline and augmented models on the target domain for each pair, using macro-F1 as the primary metric\n6. Conducting a mediation analysis to examine the relationship between the pivot language typology, back-translation quality, and sentiment analysis performance\n7. Repeating the fine-tuning process three times for each condition (baseline and augmented) with different random seeds\n8. Conducting a human evaluation study to assess the quality of the back-translated data and the sentiment analysis performance of the models\n\n**Primary Outcome**\nThe primary outcome of this study is the improvement in macro-F1 score for sentiment analysis across domain shifts, measured using paired bootstrap testing to determine statistical significance (p < 0.05).\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation**\nThe main confound in this study is the potential for differences in back-translation quality between the two pivot languages, which could influence the effectiveness of back-translation. To mitigate this confound, we will:\n\n* Use a single machine translation model for both pivot languages to minimize differences in translation quality\n* Evaluate the back-translation quality using metrics such as syntax and semantics preservation, lexical and grammatical complexity\n* Conduct a mediation analysis to examine the relationship between the pivot language typology, back-translation quality, and sentiment analysis performance\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\nTwo plausible alternative designs that were not chosen are:\n\n1. Using a multi-pivot language approach, where multiple pivot languages are used to create a more diverse set of back-translated data. This approach was not chosen because it would increase the complexity of the study and make it more difficult to interpret the results.\n2. Using a different machine learning model, such as a transformer-based model, to evaluate the effectiveness of back-translation. This approach was not chosen because the BERT-base model is a well-established and widely-used model for sentiment analysis, and using a different model would introduce additional variability and make it more difficult to compare the results to previous studies."
