    "domain": "computational social science",
    "objective": "Test whether exposure to algorithmically curated ideologically homogeneous content feeds on social media increases users' affective polarization scores over a 6-week period compared to exposure to ideologically diverse feeds.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "randomized controlled experiment with exactly 2 conditions (homogeneous feed vs diverse feed)",
      "sample size between 800 and 2000 adult U.S. social media users recruited via a platform partnership or browser extension",
      "affective polarization measured using the feeling thermometer difference score (in-party minus out-party warmth) administered pre and post",
      "intervention period must last exactly 6 weeks with compliance verified by feed exposure logs",
      "participants must not be informed of which condition they are assigned to during the study",
      "single platform only, no cross-platform analysis",
      "no deception beyond standard randomized assignment; study must receive IRB approval before data collection"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a survey-based measure of issue position extremity as a primary outcome alongside affective polarization",
      "include a no-intervention control group that receives their unmodified organic feed",
      "analyze behavioral outcomes such as sharing, commenting, or content creation during the study",
      "extend the study to non-U.S. populations or multiple countries"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Final Research Proposal\n\n#### Core Hypothesis\nAffective polarization is driven by heuristic, identity-based rejection of out-group content. I hypothesize that exposure to ideologically diverse content\u2014when mediated by **Value-Framing** that explicitly identifies the moral-political values underlying out-group arguments\u2014will significantly decrease affective polarization compared to ideologically homogeneous feeds. I further hypothesize that this effect is causally mediated by an increase in \"Perspective-Taking Accuracy\" (measured via weekly probes).\n\n#### Minimal Viable Design\n*   **Platform:** Twitter/X (via browser extension).\n*   **Sample:** 1,600 U.S. adults (stratified by party affiliation).\n*   **Procedure:** 6-week intervention.\n    *   **Condition A (Homogeneous Control):** Extension suppresses cross-cutting content, enforcing a partisan \"echo chamber.\"\n    *   **Condition B (Value-Framed Diversity):** Extension enforces ideological diversity and injects a standardized, neutral \"Value-Frame\" tag to cross-cutting content.\n*   **Mechanism Probe:** Weekly, one-time interaction where participants categorize the \"underlying value\" of a recently viewed post. This serves as a proxy for cognitive processing (mediator) and ensures compliance (log data).\n\n#### Primary Outcome\nThe change in **Affective Polarization (Thermometer Score)** from baseline to 6 weeks.\n*   *Difference-in-Differences (DiD)* estimation comparing the pre-post gap between Condition A and Condition B.\n*   *CACE Analysis* using the randomized assignment as an instrument to account for non-compliance (low feed usage).\n\n#### Main Confound and Mitigation\n*   **Confound:** \"Self-Selection/Platform Fatigue.\" Users may abandon the extension if their feed feels alien, leading to attrition that is non-random and biased toward the homogeneous group.\n*   **Mitigation:** The extension UI will prioritize \"usability\" (minimal design) and will not block content\u2014it only filters or labels. We will track \"Days Active\" as a covariate and use a *Heckman selection model* or inverse probability weighting (IPW) to adjust for differential attrition between conditions.\n\n#### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Simulated Feed App:** Rejected because it lacks the \"ecological validity\" of real-world Twitter/X interactions and creates a high barrier to entry (users must migrate their social consumption to a new app).\n2.  **Platform Partnership (API Access):** Rejected due to feasibility. Accessing granular, real-time feed randomization parameters via Twitter/X API is currently cost-prohibitive and technically unstable given platform volatility."
  },
  {
    "item_number": 28,
    "run_id": "730d21b838ba",
    "brief_id": "soccomp_02",
    "domain": "computational social science",
    "objective": "Test whether algorithmic content curation on social media platforms reduces the diversity of news sources that users engage with compared to reverse-chronological feeds.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "observational study only, no platform-side A/B test access",
      "must use publicly available or researcher-accessible API data",
      "sample must include at least 5000 unique user accounts",
      "analysis window must not exceed 6 months",
      "must operationalize source diversity using Shannon entropy or equivalent information-theoretic metric",
      "no survey or self-report data"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add sentiment analysis or toxicity scoring of consumed content",
      "expand scope to include non-news content such as entertainment or lifestyle posts",
      "introduce a content-level topic model to characterize article similarity"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Research Proposal**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**\n\nWhen social media platforms switch users from reverse-chronological to algorithmic feed curation by default, users are exposed to more already-popular content, which systematically reduces the diversity of news sources they engage with.  \nWe hypothesize that:  \n> **News source diversity (measured by Shannon entropy) will decline after a platform-wide switch to algorithmic curation, but only among users whose exposure to high-engagement content increases \u2014 and not among those insulated from the algorithmic feedback loop.**\n\nThis hypothesis links platform mechanism to user behavior through a testable causal pathway:  \n**Feed switch \u2192 \u2191 algorithmic exposure \u2192 \u2193 news source diversity**\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**\n\nA **mechanism-conditional natural experiment** leveraging a known platform-wide default feed switch (e.g., Twitter/X\u2019s April 15, 2023, activation of \u201cFor You\u201d as default).\n\n- **Design Type**: Regression discontinuity in time (RDD), with treatment effect conditioned on behavioral evidence of algorithmic exposure.\n- **Unit of Analysis**: Unique user accounts (\u22655,000) active in the 90 days before and after the switch.\n- **Time Window**: 180 days total (90 pre, 90 post), satisfying the 6-month maximum.\n- **Identification Strategy**:  \n  1. Estimate discontinuity in news source diversity at the switch date.  \n  2. Show the effect is **present only among users whose algorithmic exposure increases**, as measured by engagement velocity of consumed content.  \n  3. Validate counterfactual trends using a synthetic control of chronological-feed-only users.\n\n- **Key Behavioral Proxy**:  \n  - **Algorithmic Exposure Intensity (AEI)** = median engagement velocity (likes + retweets / age in hours) of posts a user engages with.  \n  - **\u0394AEI** = post-switch AEI minus pre-switch AEI (split at median).\n\n- **Analysis Plan**:  \n  - Compute per-user Shannon entropy of news domains in pre- and post-switch periods.  \n  - Fit local linear regression (\u00b130 days from switch) with user fixed effects.  \n  - Run model separately for high- and low-\u0394AEI users.  \n  - Primary test: Significant drop in entropy only in high-\u0394AEI group.\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**\n\n- **News source diversity**, operationalized as **Shannon entropy of news domains engaged with** per user:  \n  $$\n  H_u = -\\sum_{d \\in D_u} p(d|u) \\log p(d|u)\n  $$\n  where $ p(d|u) $ is the proportion of user $ u $\u2019s engagements with news domain $ d $.  \n- **News domains** defined via pre-registered list (e.g., Google News sitemap + Media Bias/Fact Check), excluding non-news and hyperpartisan outliers.  \n- **Engagements**: Retweets, likes, and replies to posts containing news URLs.  \n- **Metric finalized before analysis begins**.\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**\n\n- **Main Confound**: Time-varying external factors (e.g., breaking news, elections, platform-wide attention shifts) could reduce news source diversity independently of the feed algorithm.\n\n- **Mitigation Strategy**:  \n  1. **Mechanism conditioning**: Restrict causal claim to users whose *exposure to algorithmically amplified content increases*. If diversity drops only where AEI rises, it is unlikely due to broad temporal trends.  \n  2. **Synthetic control**: Construct a counterfactual trend using users who consume only chronological feeds (e.g., TweetDeck users). If the treatment group diverges post-switch while the synthetic control does not, the effect is attributable to the feed change.  \n  3. **Falsification chain**:  \n     - No effect on non-news content diversity.  \n     - No discontinuity at placebo switch date (6 months prior).  \n     - No divergence in synthetic control on non-news entropy.\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n\n1. **Propensity Score Matching (PSM) of feed opt-in behavior**  \n   - *Why not chosen*: Opt-in status (chronological vs. algorithmic) is often unobservable via API; inferred behavior may be noisy. PSM also cannot fully address unmeasured confounding (e.g., motivation, ideology). Our design uses a sharper exogenous shock.\n\n2. **Regression Kink Design (RKD) on engagement thresholds**  \n   - *Why not chosen*: Requires precise identification of unobserved algorithmic thresholds (e.g., \u201cboost if >3 likes/post\u201d), which risks model dependence and weak instruments. Our design anchors on a known event, making identification more credible.\n\n---"
  },
