    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Proposal**\n\n**Core Hypothesis**\nMandatory ESG disclosure requirements reduce the cost of equity capital for affected firms by reducing information asymmetry between investors and firms.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design**\nThe study will employ a staggered difference-in-differences (DiD) design, using the implementation of the EU Non-Financial Reporting Directive (NFRD) as a natural experiment. The sample will consist of at least 200 non-financial sector firms listed on stock exchanges in EU member states that adopted the NFRD. The treatment group will consist of firms that were required to disclose non-financial information under the NFRD, while the control group will consist of firms that were not required to disclose such information.\n\n**Primary Outcome**\nThe primary outcome variable will be the implied cost of capital, estimated using a model such as the Gebhardt et al. (2001) or Easton (2004) model. The implied cost of capital will be calculated using publicly available stock market and filing data.\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation**\nThe main confound is the potential for concurrent regulatory changes to affect the cost of equity capital. To mitigate this confound, the study will control for changes in macroeconomic conditions, industry trends, and firm-specific characteristics using the Callaway-Sant'Anna (2020) estimator. Additionally, the study will include a falsification test using bond market data to check for the absence of an effect on the cost of debt capital.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\nTwo plausible alternatives not chosen are:\n\n1. An event study around the SEC climate disclosure rule using size-based compliance thresholds. This design was not chosen because it may not provide a clear causal story, as the SEC rule may have been anticipated by market participants.\n2. A difference-in-differences design around the implementation of a national ESG disclosure mandate in a country with a large and developed stock market. This design was not chosen because it may be subject to concerns about the generalizability of the results to other countries and regulatory environments."
