    "item_number": 30,
    "run_id": "76d5deb1f489",
    "brief_id": "legal_02",
    "domain": "criminal justice policy",
    "objective": "Test whether jurisdiction-level bail reform policies that eliminate cash bail for misdemeanors reduce the Black-white gap in pretrial detention rates without increasing failure-to-appear rates.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "quasi-experimental design using staggered policy adoption across jurisdictions, no randomization",
      "treatment defined as statutory or administrative elimination of cash bail for all misdemeanor charges, not partial reforms or judicial discretion changes",
      "pretrial detention measured from official jail booking records, not survey data",
      "racial disparity must be operationalized as the Black-white ratio of pretrial detention rates, not raw counts",
      "must include at least 4 reform-adopting jurisdictions and at least 4 comparison jurisdictions",
      "analysis must span at least 2 years pre-reform and 2 years post-reform",
      "failure-to-appear rate must be measured from court administrative records within the same jurisdictions"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a qualitative interview component with judges or defendants",
      "expand the outcome to include felony charges alongside misdemeanors",
      "incorporate recidivism or re-arrest as an outcome measure",
      "use individual-level risk assessment scores as a control variable"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "# Final Research Proposal\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nStatutory elimination of cash bail for misdemeanor charges removes a financial barrier to pretrial release that bound Black defendants more tightly than white defendants \u2014 because Black defendants are disproportionately concentrated at wealth levels where even modest bail amounts are unaffordable. Removing this barrier should therefore reduce the Black-white pretrial detention rate ratio. The reduction should operate primarily through the conditional detention channel (equal treatment within the system) rather than through changes in who is charged, and should not be offset by substitution into non-financial detention mechanisms. Failure-to-appear rates should remain within an acceptable margin because the policy changes the payment condition for release, not the defendant's underlying incentive or ability to appear.\n\nThree links in this chain are empirically testable and are tested in sequence:\n\n| Link | Claim | Test |\n|---|---|---|\n| **L1** | Pre-reform cash bail bound Black defendants more tightly than white defendants at identical bail amounts | Pre-reform racial detention gap as a function of bail amount; predicted to peak within the interquartile range of the bail amount distribution |\n| **L2** | The BW-Ratio reduction post-reform is driven by elimination of financial holds, not charge composition shifts | Detention-basis decomposition and Channel A/B decomposition within the DiD framework |\n| **L3** | Jurisdictions did not substitute non-financial detention for cash bail in a racially patterned way | DiD on non-financial detention counts post-reform, separately by race |\n\nIf any link fails, the paper reports this honestly and revises the causal interpretation accordingly. The primary policy estimands \u2014 the ATT on BW-Ratio and the FTA non-inferiority test \u2014 are reported regardless of the mechanism findings.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Identification Strategy\n\n**Callaway-Sant'Anna staggered difference-in-differences** across counties within states that enabled but did not mandate county-level misdemeanor cash bail elimination. Groups are defined by adoption cohort (year-quarter of policy effective date). Time is indexed at county-month. The estimator is doubly robust, combining outcome regression with inverse probability weighting. Standard errors are clustered at the county level with a 999-iteration bootstrap.\n\nThis is the minimal sufficient estimator for the staggered adoption setting. It handles treatment effect heterogeneity across cohorts without the negative weighting problems of two-way fixed effects, and it produces event-study coefficients that directly test the parallel trends assumption in the pre-period.\n\n### Sample\n\n| Role | Minimum | Target | Selection criterion |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Reform-adopting counties | 4 | 8\u201312 | Full statutory or administrative elimination of cash bail for all misdemeanor charges, verified against policy text and operational implementation date |\n| Comparison counties | 4 | 12\u201320 | Same state(s) as adopting counties; never adopted or adopted outside the study window |\n\nCounties where reform adoption is ambiguous, where implementation was suspended, or where the reform covered only a subset of misdemeanor charge types are excluded from the primary analysis.\n\n### Study Window\n\nMinimum 24 months pre-reform and 24 months post-reform for each county, indexed to that county's own effective date. Counties with fewer than 24 months of post-reform data at the time of data extraction are excluded from the primary analysis and included in a sensitivity run.\n\n### Treatment Definition\n\nTreatment is coded as a binary indicator equal to 1 from the month of the statutory or administrative effective date onward, for counties where the policy:\n- Eliminates cash bail (not reduces, not caps)\n- Applies to all misdemeanor charges without exception\n- Is implemented by statute or binding administrative order, not judicial guideline\n- Was operationally in effect (verified by court administrator confirmation)\n\nPartial reforms, discretion-based changes, and pilot programs are not coded as treatment.\n\n### Covariates\n\nEntered via the outcome regression component of the doubly robust estimator:\n- County unemployment rate (ACS 5-year)\n- County violent crime rate (UCR/NIBRS, lagged 1 year)\n- Log county adult population (ACS)\n- Share of county adult population that is Black (ACS)\n- Pre-reform jail capacity utilization rate (BJS Census of Jails)\n\nIndividual-level risk assessment scores are not used as controls.\n\n### Mechanism Tests\n\nConducted within the same data and estimation framework, in sequence:\n\n**L1 test:** Local linear regression of pre-reform detention probability on bail amount, estimated separately for Black and white defendants. Pre-registered prediction: the racial gap peaks within the interquartile range of the pre-reform bail amount distribution. Estimated using pre-reform booking records only; no post-treatment data involved.\n\n**L2 test \u2014 Detention-basis decomposition:** Post-reform DiD estimated separately for financial-hold detentions and non-financial-hold detentions, using the detention basis code field in booking records. Conditional on that field being present and consistently coded in \u2265 90% of pre-reform misdemeanor bookings in a jurisdiction. Pre-registered prediction: the BW-Ratio reduction is concentrated in financial-hold detentions.\n\n**L2 test \u2014 Channel A/B decomposition:** Kitagawa-Oaxaca-Blinder decomposition of the BW-Ratio change into charge-composition (Channel A) and conditional-detention (Channel B) components, using NIBRS offense codes to define charge cells. Pre-registered prediction: Channel B accounts for the majority of the BW-Ratio change.\n\n**L3 test:** DiD ATT on non-financial pretrial detention counts, estimated separately for Black and white defendants. Pre-registered prediction: the ATT on non-financial detention is not significantly positive for Black defendants (one-sided test, \u03b1 = 0.05), indicating no racially patterned substitution.\n\n**Cross-jurisdiction scaling:** County-level ATT estimates on BW-Ratio regressed on the pre-reform Black/white median household income ratio (ACS), weighted by inverse first-stage variance. Pre-registered prediction: jurisdictions with lower Black/white income ratios show larger BW-Ratio reductions.\n\n### Identification Validation\n\n**Difference-in-discontinuities design**, conditional on identifying a statutory eligibility threshold (county population, jail size, or court caseload volume) in at least one study state with \u2265 6 counties within the optimal bandwidth. Combines a regression discontinuity in eligibility with the pre/post DiD structure. Produces a local ATT that is immune to the selection-on-trends critique. If the threshold does not exist, a synthetic control for the largest single adopting jurisdiction is substituted as identification validation.\n\nPre-registered predictions: the pre-period RD estimate on BW-Ratio is indistinguishable from zero; the Diff-in-Disc point estimate falls within the 95% CI of the primary DiD ATT for the same subsample.\n\n### Robustness Checks\n\n| Check | Purpose | Required? |\n|---|---|---|\n| R1: Exclude jurisdictions with simultaneous criminal justice reforms | Clean treatment estimate | \u2705 Required |\n| R2: TWFE comparator | Document heterogeneity bias | Recommended |\n| R3: Placebo adoption dates (\u221224 months) | Pre-trend falsification | Recommended |\n| R4: Propensity-score-matched comparison set | Covariate balance | Recommended |\n| R5: Alternative FTA definition (any missed appearance) | Measurement sensitivity | Recommended |\n| R6: Alternative charge-cell definitions for decomposition | Decomposition sensitivity | Recommended |\n| R7: Jackknife over adopting jurisdictions | Influence check | Recommended |\n| R8: Bail-amount tier cutoffs at quartiles instead of terciles | Tier definition sensitivity | Recommended |\n| R9: Racial poverty gap as alternative Step 3 moderator | Wealth measure sensitivity | Recommended |\n| R10: Exclude jurisdictions with significant post-reform non-financial detention increase | Substitution contamination | Recommended |\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n### Outcome 1: Black-White Pretrial Detention Rate Ratio\n\n$$\\text{BW-Ratio}_{jt} = \\frac{\\text{Misdemeanor pretrial detention rate, Black adults}_{jt}}{\\text{Misdemeanor pretrial detention rate, white adults}_{jt}}$$\n\nRates are detained individuals per 100,000 adult (18+) residents of each racial group in county *j*, month *t*, using ACS 5-year population estimates as denominators. Detention is measured from official jail booking records. The estimand is the ATT on BW-Ratio across all adopting jurisdictions and post-reform periods, reported with a 95% confidence interval.\n\n### Outcome 2: Failure-to-Appear Rate\n\n$$\\text{FTA rate}_{jt} = \\frac{\\text{Bench warrants issued for misdemeanor non-appearance}_{jt}}{\\text{Misdemeanor cases with a scheduled court appearance}_{jt}}$$\n\nMeasured from court administrative records (clerk of court case management system) within the same jurisdictions. Restricted to misdemeanor cases originating after the reform effective date for post-reform measurement. The estimand is the ATT on FTA rate, tested against a **pre-specified non-inferiority margin of +2.0 percentage points** above the pre-reform baseline FTA rate in adopting jurisdictions. This margin is locked in the pre-registration document before any outcome data are accessed. Reform is declared non-inferior if the upper bound of the 95% CI for the ATT does not exceed +2.0 pp.\n\n### Data Sources\n\n| Element | Source | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pretrial detention, bail amounts, detention basis codes | County jail booking records (sheriff / jail administrator) | Detention basis field required for mechanism tests; feasibility verified at site selection |\n| FTA rate | Clerk of court case management system | Same jurisdictions as booking records |\n| Population denominators | ACS 5-year estimates | CV < 30% for racial subgroup estimates required |\n| Reform adoption dates | Statutory and administrative records | Verified against policy text and court administrator confirmation |\n| Covariates | ACS, UCR/NIBRS, BJS Census of Jails | Publicly available |\n| Eligibility threshold (if applicable) | State enabling legislation | Verified against statutory text |\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n### The Confound: Selection-on-Trends With Substitution\n\nThe design faces two related threats that, taken together, constitute the main confound:\n\n**Threat A \u2014 Selection-on-trends:** Jurisdictions that adopted bail reform may have done so because racial detention disparities were already worsening, meaning post-reform improvement partially reflects mean reversion rather than a policy effect. Standard pre-trend tests rule out linear divergence but cannot rule out non-linear trajectories that would have reversed without the policy.\n\n**Threat B \u2014 Substitution:** Even if the policy reduced cash bail detention, jurisdictions may have simultaneously expanded non-financial detention mechanisms (preventive detention orders, public safety holds) in ways that offset the racial equity benefit and are correlated with the adoption decision. This would cause the primary DiD to understate the true financial barrier effect while overstating the net policy benefit if substitution was racially neutral, or to produce a misleading BW-Ratio reduction if substitution was racially patterned.\n\nThese two threats interact: jurisdictions that adopted reform in response to worsening disparities may also be jurisdictions most likely to have expanded non-financial holds to manage the political risk of appearing soft on public safety.\n\n### Mitigation\n\n**Against Threat A:** The Diff-in-Disc design uses statutory eligibility thresholds to generate as-good-as-random variation in eligibility near the cutoff, producing a local ATT that is immune to selection-on-trends by construction. Consistency between the DiD and Diff-in-Disc estimates is the primary validation. Secondary mitigation: placebo adoption dates (R3) and the pre-period event-study coefficients test for pre-existing trends.\n\n**Against Threat B:** The L3 substitution test directly estimates whether non-financial detention increased post-reform in a racially patterned way, using the detention basis code field in booking records. R10 re-estimates the primary DiD excluding jurisdictions where significant substitution is detected, providing a clean-treatment estimate. R1 excludes jurisdictions that simultaneously expanded preventive detention provisions alongside bail reform, addressing the correlated policy change version of the threat.\n\n**Against the interaction:** The combination of R1 (simultaneous reform exclusion) and the Diff-in-Disc (selection-on-trends correction) jointly addresses the scenario where adoption decision, outcome trajectory, and substitution behavior are all correlated. If the R1 subsample and the Diff-in-Disc estimate are both consistent with the primary DiD, the confound is credibly mitigated.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Interrupted Time Series With Propensity-Score-Matched Comparison Counties\n\n**Design:** For each adopting county, identify 2\u20133 comparison counties matched on pre-reform BW-Ratio trend, crime rates, population, and racial composition. Estimate an interrupted time series model with the matched comparison group as the counterfactual, using county-month observations and a segmented regression around the reform effective date.\n\n**Why it was not chosen:** ITS with matched controls handles the \u22654/\u22654 constraint and is more transparent to policy and criminology audiences. However, it is less rigorous than Callaway-Sant'Anna under staggered adoption because it does not account for treatment effect heterogeneity across cohorts, and the segmented regression functional form imposes assumptions about the shape of the post-reform trend that are not required by the DiD framework. The matching also does not resolve the selection-on-trends threat \u2014 matched counties may still be on different latent trajectories. It remains available as a robustness check (R4 uses propensity-score matching within the DiD framework) but is not the primary estimator.\n\n**When it would be preferred:** If the adopting jurisdiction count is at the minimum (4) and the goal is a policy brief rather than a journal article, ITS with matched controls is more accessible and sufficient for the primary policy question.\n\n### Alternative 2: Synthetic Control for a Single Large Jurisdiction\n\n**Design:** Select one large adopting jurisdiction (e.g., a state-level adopter such as New Jersey or Illinois) and construct a synthetic counterfactual as a weighted combination of non-adopting jurisdictions that best matches the pre-reform BW-Ratio and FTA trajectory. Estimate the post-reform gap between the treated jurisdiction and its synthetic control.\n\n**Why it was not chosen:** The synthetic control produces a visually compelling and highly credible estimate for a single jurisdiction but cannot satisfy the \u22654 adopting jurisdiction hard constraint as a standalone design. It also cannot support the mechanism chain (the bail-amount tier and detention-basis analyses require within-jurisdiction variation across many defendants, which is available in the DiD setting but produces a single aggregate estimate in the synthetic control). It is retained as a conditional substitute for the Diff-in-Disc if no eligibility threshold is found, and as a supplementary analysis for the largest adopting jurisdiction.\n\n**When it would be preferred:** If the research question were narrowed to a single high-profile jurisdiction with a well-documented reform date and a large donor pool of comparable non-adopting jurisdictions, the synthetic control would be the most credible primary design.\n\n---"
  },
  {
