    "run_id": "421b5e8d2d86",
    "brief_id": "edu_01",
    "domain": "education",
    "objective": "Test whether providing written formative feedback three times per week instead of once per week improves end-of-term exam scores in an introductory university statistics course.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "quasi-experimental design comparing two sections of the same course taught by the same instructor",
      "minimum 50 students per section",
      "feedback must be written comments on weekly problem sets, not grades or scores alone",
      "final exam must be identical across both sections and graded by a blinded marker",
      "study duration is exactly one academic term (10 to 15 weeks)",
      "no additional tutoring or supplementary instruction offered to either group"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a third section receiving peer feedback instead of instructor feedback",
      "measure student satisfaction or perceived learning as a co-primary outcome",
      "vary the content or difficulty of the problem sets between sections",
      "use automated AI-generated feedback instead of instructor-written feedback"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\n\nStudents in an introductory university statistics course who receive **written formative feedback on weekly problem sets three times per week** will achieve **higher end-of-term final exam scores** than students who receive the same type of written formative feedback **once per week**, when comparing two sections of the same course taught by the same instructor over a single academic term.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n\n**Design type:** Quasi-experimental comparison of **two sections of the same course**, taught by the **same instructor**, during **one academic term**.\n\n**Groups**\n- **Section A:** written formative feedback provided **three times per week**\n- **Section B:** written formative feedback provided **once per week**\n\n**Sample**\n- At least **50 students per section**\n\n**Term length**\n- Exactly **one academic term**, within the allowed **10\u201315 week** range\n\n**Instructional equivalence**\n- Same instructor\n- Same syllabus\n- Same weekly problem sets\n- Same class materials\n- Same pacing and assessments\n- No additional tutoring or supplementary instruction for either section\n\n**Feedback intervention**\n- Feedback is delivered as **written comments on weekly problem sets**\n- No use of grades/scores alone as the intervention\n- No AI-generated feedback\n- Problem set content and difficulty remain identical across sections\n\n**Baseline ability measure**\n- Administer a **statistics pre-test at the start of term** as the baseline ability covariate for the pre-registered linear model\n\n**Feedback uptake measure**\n- Track the **proportion of students accessing posted written feedback within 48 hours** using the course learning platform log data\n\n**Outcome assessment**\n- Both sections sit the **same final exam**\n- Exam scripts are graded by a **blinded marker** unaware of section assignment\n\n**Analysis**\n- Pre-register a **linear model**:\n  - outcome: final exam score\n  - predictor: feedback frequency condition\n  - covariate: baseline ability pre-test score\n- Report the treatment effect and **Cohen\u2019s d with confidence interval**\n\nThis is the simplest design that satisfies the brief while directly identifying the target claim.\n\n## Primary outcome\n\n**Primary outcome:** end-of-term **final exam score**\n\n**Primary analysis:** pre-registered linear model controlling for **baseline ability** measured by the start-of-term pre-test\n\n**Effect size reporting:** **Cohen\u2019s d** with confidence interval\n\n**Process measure required by the brief:** proportion of students in each section who **access feedback within 48 hours**\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n\n**Main confound:** baseline differences between the two sections due to **non-random student selection into sections**\n\nBecause the design must be quasi-experimental, section membership may reflect scheduling preferences, prior preparation, or motivation.\n\n**Mitigation**\n- Use **concurrent sections in the same semester** to reduce historical and curricular differences\n- Keep **same instructor**, materials, problem sets, and assessments across sections\n- Measure baseline ability with a **pre-test**\n- Use the pre-registered linear model to **control for baseline ability**\n\nThis mitigation is preferable to a cross-semester comparison because it avoids term-to-term drift in student cohorts, course delivery, and institutional context.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n\n### 1. Two concurrent sections with propensity score matching on prior GPA\n**Why plausible:** It addresses selection differences between sections.\n\n**Why not chosen:** It adds complexity beyond what is necessary. The brief\u2019s success criterion already specifies a **pre-registered linear model controlling for baseline ability**, and a direct pre-test measure is more closely aligned with course-specific preparedness than prior GPA alone.\n\n### 2. Same section across two consecutive semesters, using the earlier semester as control\n**Why plausible:** It avoids student self-selection between concurrent sections.\n\n**Why not chosen:** It introduces stronger historical confounding from semester-to-semester changes in cohort composition, calendar timing, institutional conditions, and instructor adaptation. A **concurrent two-section comparison** is the cleaner minimal design under the hard constraints."
  },
  {
    "item_number": 32,
    "run_id": "0b7829664cdc",
    "brief_id": "nlp_02",
    "domain": "natural language processing",
    "objective": "Does augmenting training data with back-translation (English to pivot language and back) improve macro-F1 for sentiment analysis when the test domain differs from the training domain by more than 5 points of baseline F1 drop?",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "Back-translation uses a single pivot language; no multi-pivot or paraphrase models",
      "Source training domain and target test domain must be explicitly different (e.g., electronics reviews vs restaurant reviews)",
      "Baseline model is a fine-tuned encoder of 110-130M parameters (e.g., BERT-base or equivalent)",
      "Augmented data must not exceed 2x the original training set size",
      "Domain shift confirmed by at least a 5-point macro-F1 drop when the baseline trained on source is evaluated on target",
      "Minimum 3 domain-shift pairs evaluated"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "Using generative LLM paraphrasing (e.g., GPT-based rewriting) instead of back-translation",
      "Including any target-domain labeled data in training",
      "Applying domain-adaptive pre-training (DAPT) on unlabeled target-domain text",
      "Filtering or curating back-translated samples by quality score"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nSingle-pivot back-translation improves cross-domain sentiment classification macro-F1 when the target domain differs from the source domain enough to cause a baseline cross-domain drop of more than 5 macro-F1 points.\n\nMore concretely:\n- Train a BERT-base sentiment classifier on labeled source-domain reviews\n- Augment the source training set with one English\u2192German\u2192English back-translated version of each source example\n- Evaluate on a distinct target review domain\n- Expect higher target-domain macro-F1 than the non-augmented baseline on at least 2 of 3 eligible domain-shift pairs\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Task:** sentiment analysis\n- **Model:** BERT-base or equivalent 110\u2013130M parameter encoder\n- **Augmentation:** single-pivot back-translation using **German only**\n- **Augmentation ratio:** 1.0x, meaning one back-translated copy per original source training example\n  - Total training size becomes 2x original, which is the maximum allowed but still compliant\n- **Domains:** use a multi-domain Amazon reviews dataset with explicitly different domains\n- **Pair selection:**\n  1. Screen candidate source\u2192target pairs from different domains\n  2. Train baseline on source only\n  3. Measure source in-domain macro-F1 and target cross-domain macro-F1\n  4. Retain the first 3 pairs in a predeclared order whose baseline drop exceeds 5 points\n- **Conditions per retained pair:**\n  - Baseline: source training data only\n  - Back-translation: source training data + one German back-translation per source example\n- **Seeds:** 3 random fine-tuning seeds per condition\n- **Analysis:** paired bootstrap significance test on target-domain predictions, p < 0.05\n\nThis yields the smallest complete study that answers the question:\n- 3 domain pairs\n- 2 conditions\n- 3 seeds\n- 18 main fine-tuning runs, plus baseline screening runs\n\n## Primary outcome\nThe primary outcome is:\n\n- **Target-domain macro-F1 difference** between:\n  - baseline source-only training\n  - source training plus German back-translation augmentation\n\nSuccess is defined exactly by the brief:\n- statistically significant improvement in macro-F1 on at least 2 of 3 domain pairs using paired bootstrap, p < 0.05\n- average macro-F1 gain of at least 1.5 points across all 3 tested domain pairs\n- results observed across 3 random seeds per condition\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n### Main confound\nThe main confound is that augmentation changes both:\n- the linguistic surface form of training examples\n- and the effective training set size\n\nSo any improvement could reflect either:\n- beneficial paraphrastic variation from back-translation\n- or simply having more training examples\n\n### Mitigation\nFor the initial study, do **not** add extra control conditions, because that would expand the aim beyond the brief.\n\nInstead, mitigate by:\n- keeping the augmentation procedure fixed and minimal\n- using the same 1.0x ratio for all pairs\n- keeping all training hyperparameters identical across baseline and augmented conditions\n- interpreting the result narrowly as the effect of **back-translation augmentation as a practical intervention**, not as a pure mechanism test\n\nThis is the simplest valid mitigation consistent with the objective.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n### 1) Compare two pivot languages on the same 3 domain pairs\nExample: German vs Chinese\n\nWhy plausible:\n- directly tests whether pivot language matters\n\nWhy not chosen:\n- adds a second research question beyond the main objective\n- increases complexity without improving identification of the core claim\n- unnecessary for the initial test of whether single-pivot back-translation helps at all\n\n### 2) Vary augmentation ratio as a secondary factor\nExample: 0.5x vs 1.0x vs 2.0x with one pivot language\n\nWhy plausible:\n- could reveal whether gains depend on augmentation intensity\n\nWhy not chosen:\n- adds another factor not needed for the primary claim\n- 1.0x already reaches the allowed total-size cap exactly\n- a ratio sweep is better reserved for follow-up after establishing the core effect"
  },
