    "final_proposal": "**Final Research Proposal: Demonstrations as Contextual Priors in Reactive Robot Navigation**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**\n\n> **The reduction in collision rate from demonstration-augmented reinforcement learning in cluttered indoor navigation is causally driven by the incorporation of human-learned, context-sensitive obstacle negotiation strategies \u2014 not by generic regularization, data volume, or low-level action smoothing.**\n\nThis hypothesis asserts that **meaningful sensorimotor contingencies** in human demonstrations \u2014 such as slowing before tight turns or lateral shifting to pass furniture \u2014 are the active ingredient in performance improvement. If demonstrations lack this functional alignment (even if they match in form), no benefit should arise.\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**\n\nWe test the hypothesis using a **three-condition counterfactual design** under a shared PPO backbone:\n\n1. **RL-only (Control):**  \n   - Trained from scratch with no demonstrations.  \n   - Isolates baseline RL performance.\n\n2. **PA-PPO (Human):**  \n   - Uses 50 human teleoperation demonstrations.  \n   - Segments them into local obstacle interaction windows (\u22641.5 m proximity).  \n   - Clusters action sequences (via DTW + K-means) into 6 reusable **behavioral primitives** (e.g., \u201cslow advance\u201d, \u201clateral dodge\u201d).  \n   - Trains a frozen primitive classifier and injects its output as a KL regularization term during PPO:  \n     $ \\mathcal{L} = \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{PPO}} + \\lambda D_{\\text{KL}}(\\pi_{\\text{primitive}} \\| \\pi_{\\text{RL}}) $  \n   - At test time, only the trained RL policy acts (reactive, no memory, no map).\n\n3. **PA-PPO (Synthetic-Context-Matched):**  \n   - **Identical architecture and training** to human condition.  \n   - Demonstrations generated via **Obstacle-Phase-Randomized Playback (OPRP)**:  \n     - Original human actions are replayed from **randomly shifted starting poses** relative to obstacles.  \n     - Preserves action distributions, trajectory statistics, and sensor diversity.  \n     - **Destroys functional alignment** between observations and actions.  \n   - Primitives are extracted and used identically \u2014 but now represent **non-functional, misaligned behaviors**.\n\nAll conditions use the same:\n- Network architecture (LiDAR + RGB-D encoders, shared latent space, actor-critic MLPs)\n- Reward function (sparse: +1 on goal, \u22120.01 per step)\n- Training steps (2M), evaluation frequency (every 10k steps)\n- Robot platform and sensor suite\n\n**Evaluation:**  \n- 100 point-to-point trials across 5 distinct cluttered indoor layouts (\u226515 movable obstacles per 25 m\u00b2)  \n- Max 120 seconds per trial; timeout = failure  \n- No map input or construction during evaluation  \n- Start/goal positions randomized (\u22653 m apart), obstacles re-randomized per trial within density constraints\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**\n\n- **Main metric:** **Collision rate** (proportion of trials with \u22651 collision), reported with bootstrapped standard errors.\n- **Statistical test:** One-way ANOVA across the three conditions, with **Tukey HSD post-hoc comparisons**.\n- **Expected result:**  \n  - PA-PPO (Human) < RL-only \u2248 PA-PPO (Synthetic)  \n  - Significant difference only between human and synthetic/RL-only conditions.\n\nThis outcome would confirm that **only demonstrations with intact human behavioral structure** reduce collisions \u2014 supporting the causal role of context-sensitive strategies.\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**\n\n- **Confound:** *Demonstration augmentation improves performance due to regularization, not meaningful behavior.*  \n  For example, any demonstration-derived prior might stabilize training or constrain action space, regardless of content.\n\n- **Mitigation:**  \n  The **synthetic demonstration control (OPRP)** matches human data in all statistical properties (action norms, velocity distributions, trajectory length, sensor coverage) but **breaks the sensorimotor contingency**.  \n  Because both human and synthetic conditions use **identical architectures, training procedures, and KL regularization**, any performance difference must stem from the **functional content** of the demonstrations \u2014 not the form or regularization mechanism.\n\nThis design isolates **meaningful behavioral structure** as the sole differing factor.\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n\n1. **Behavioral Cloning + PPO (BC+PPO):**  \n   - *Why plausible:* Well-established, simple, and often effective.  \n   - *Why rejected:* Confounds initialization with mechanism. Improvement could stem from better starting weights rather than incorporation of reusable strategies. Does not allow clean isolation of *what* about demonstrations helps.\n\n2. **GAIL (Generative Adversarial Imitation Learning):**  \n   - *Why plausible:* Learns reward functions from demonstrations; widely used.  \n   - *Why rejected:* Introduces adversarial dynamics that complicate interpretation. Hard to distinguish whether improvement comes from imitation or discriminator-induced exploration. Less stable with only 50 demos. Obscures the mechanistic link between demonstrations and collision reduction.\n\nOur design prioritizes **causal clarity over popularity**, choosing a path that makes the mechanism **explicit, testable, and falsifiable**.\n\n---"
  },
