    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nMechanical removal of one dominant invasive plant species will increase **native plant percent ground cover** within 3 years at restoration sites, relative to untreated controls, because removal reduces the invasive species\u2019 percent cover and thereby releases native vegetation from dominance.\n\n## Minimal viable design\nUse a **paired before-after-control-impact design** within a single ecoregion.\n\n- Target **one named invasive species only**\n- Enroll **at least 8 matched treatment-control site pairs**; 10 pairs preferred if feasible\n- Collect **baseline data before any removal**\n- At each site, establish **permanent fixed quadrats**\n- Measure in each quadrat at every time point:\n  - **native plant percent ground cover**\n  - **focal invasive species percent cover**\n- Sampling schedule:\n  - baseline pre-removal\n  - early post-removal in the same growing season\n  - end of year 1\n  - end of year 2\n  - end of year 3\n- Apply **mechanical removal only** at treatment sites using a standardized protocol\n- Leave control sites untreated\n- If operationally feasible, **randomly assign** treatment vs control within each matched pair after baseline measurement\n\nAnalysis:\n- Fit a **linear mixed-effects repeated-measures model** for native percent cover with treatment, time, and treatment \u00d7 time as fixed effects and site pair as a random effect\n- Report the treatment effect with **confidence interval**\n- Confirm baseline native cover difference between treatment and control within pairs is **no more than 10 percentage points**\n- Report invasive cover at every time point to document suppression and reinvasion\n\n## Primary outcome\n**Native plant percent ground cover** measured in permanent fixed quadrats.\n\nThe primary estimand is the **difference in native cover trajectory**, especially the treatment-control difference by **year 3**, from the mixed-effects repeated-measures model with confidence interval.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n**Main confound:** pre-existing differences between treatment and control sites that could explain later differences in native cover.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- match sites into pairs within the same ecoregion\n- require baseline native cover difference to be **\u226410 percentage points**\n- collect baseline data before removal begins\n- if feasible, randomly assign treatment within pairs\n- use site pair as a random effect in the repeated-measures mixed model\n- standardize mechanical removal timing and intensity across treatment sites\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Simpler annual-sampling BACI design without early post-removal measurement**  \n   Not chosen because it gives weaker evidence for temporal ordering between invasive suppression and native recovery.\n\n2. **Permutation-based analysis using site-level slopes of native cover over time**  \n   Not chosen because it is less directly aligned with the stated success criterion requiring a treatment effect with confidence interval from a repeated-measures or mixed-effects model."
