    "final_proposal": "**Final Research Proposal**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**\n\nA brief, intentional delay in AI responses \u2014 signaled by a \u201cThinking\u2026\u201d indicator \u2014 improves the quality of human-generated research questions **by prompting users to engage in self-initiated reflection during the pause**. We hypothesize that this effect is *mediated* by real-time reflection, not explained by perceived AI competence or novelty. The delay functions not as a passive wait, but as a **behavioral invitation to think**, aligning with social pacing and reflective cognition principles in human-AI interaction.\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**\n\nA between-subjects, single-session experiment with **two conditions**:\n\n- **Condition 1 (Immediate AI):** After each user input, the AI responds instantly with a generic, high-quality prompt.\n- **Condition 2 (Delayed AI):** After each user input, the AI displays \u201cThinking\u2026\u201d for **3 seconds**, then delivers the **identical** response as in Condition 1.\n\nAll content, interface, instructions, and response timing (outside the delay) are matched. The AI is **fully scripted** (no live model) to eliminate variability in response quality.\n\n**Participants (N = 120, 60 per condition):**  \nRecruited online (e.g., Prolific), compensated \u00a315 for ~20 minutes.\n\n**Task Flow:**  \n1. Read a primer on a novel scientific topic (e.g., programmable bacteria).  \n2. Engage in 4 rounds of interaction:  \n   - Type an idea or curiosity  \n   - Receive AI response (immediate or delayed)  \n3. **After Round 2**, answer:  \n   > \u201cWhile waiting for the AI\u2019s response, how much did you use that time to think further about your ideas?\u201d  \n   > (Not at all \u2192 A lot; 4-point scale)  \n4. After Round 4, generate **2\u20133 original research questions** on the topic.  \n5. Complete post-task survey:  \n   - Perceived AI deliberation (2 items)  \n   - Perceived AI competence (2 items)  \n   - User agency (2 items)  \n   - Baseline interest in topic (1 item, pre-task)\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**\n\n**Mean quality score** of participant-generated research questions, assessed using a **predefined rubric** with four criteria (0\u20133 each):\n\n| Criterion       | Focus |\n|----------------|-------|\n| Specificity     | Clear variables and scope |\n| Feasibility     | Empirically testable |\n| Originality     | Novel insight or combination |\n| Depth           | Explores mechanisms or implications |\n\n- **Scoring:** Double-blind, two independent raters (target \u03ba > 0.7; third rater resolves disagreements).  \n- **Pilot:** Rubric validated on external sample (n=20) prior to main study.\n\n**Analysis:**  \nPre-specified mediation model (Hayes\u2019 PROCESS Model 4):  \n- **X**: Condition (0 = Immediate, 1 = Delayed)  \n- **M**: Real-time reflection (after Round 2)  \n- **Y**: Mean question quality  \n- **Covariates:** Baseline interest, perceived competence, user agency\n\nPrimary inference: **Indirect effect** of condition on quality via real-time reflection.\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**\n\n**Confound:**  \n*The delay is interpreted as system incompetence or slowness, not as a signal of deliberation \u2014 suppressing user confidence and question quality.*\n\n**Mitigation:**  \n1. **Reframe the delay** with a neutral \u201cThinking\u2026\u201d indicator to signal intentional processing, not technical lag.  \n2. **Measure perceived competence separately** (2-item scale) and include it as a covariate in the mediation model.  \n3. **Compare perceived deliberation vs. competence**: If deliberation increases *without* a drop in competence, the cue is working as intended.  \n4. **Include user agency items** to rule out passivity (e.g., \u201cI was the main driver of this interaction\u201d).\n\nThis ensures that any improvement in quality is not due to perceived AI ability *per se*, but to the **behavioral invitation to reflect**.\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n\n1. **Delayed AI vs. No-AI Control**  \n   - *Why considered:* Would test whether *any* AI interaction aids question generation.  \n   - *Why rejected:* Confounds **delay** with **AI presence**; cannot isolate the effect of timing. Violates objective to test *delay*, not *AI utility*. Would also require redefining the mechanism, increasing complexity.\n\n2. **Varying Delay Duration (e.g., 1s vs 3s)**  \n   - *Why considered:* Could test a dose-response relationship, strengthening causal inference.  \n   - *Why rejected:* Exceeds minimal sufficiency. A binary test (delay vs. no delay) is adequate to establish the effect and mechanism. Adding duration levels risks diluting power or introducing nonlinear interpretations without clear theoretical gain. Stays within two-condition constraint.\n\n---"
  },
