    "final_proposal": "**Core Hypothesis**:\nThe core hypothesis of this study is that the use of adaptive demonstration forgetting in a reinforcement-learning navigation policy will lead to improved navigation performance in cluttered indoor environments, as measured by a reduction in collision rate and improvement in success rate, due to the policy's ability to adaptively focus on the most relevant demonstrations and forget less useful ones.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design**:\nThe minimal viable design for this study consists of the following elements:\n* A reinforcement-learning navigation policy trained with adaptive demonstration forgetting, using 50 human teleoperation demonstrations.\n* A control condition where the same reinforcement-learning navigation policy is trained without adaptive demonstration forgetting, using the same 50 human teleoperation demonstrations.\n* A comprehensive evaluation protocol, including at least 100 point-to-point navigation trials across at least 5 distinct room layouts, with a maximum episode length of 120 seconds per trial.\n* A human evaluation and validation component, where a separate group of human evaluators assess the policy's performance in a series of simulated and real-world scenarios.\n\n**Primary Outcome**:\nThe primary outcome of this study will be the comparison of the collision rate and success rate between the treatment and control conditions, as well as the comprehensive human evaluation and validation component.\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation**:\nThe main confound in this study is the potential for differences in the quality of the human teleoperation demonstrations between the treatment and control conditions. To mitigate this confound, the study will use a randomized design, where the demonstrations are randomly assigned to either the treatment or control condition. Additionally, the study will use a blinded evaluation protocol, where the human evaluators are blinded to the condition to which the robot is assigned.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**:\nTwo plausible alternatives that were not chosen for this study are:\n* Using a classical planning approach, such as RRT or A\\*, as a baseline for comparison. This approach was not chosen because it would not provide a fair comparison to the reinforcement-learning navigation policy, as classical planning approaches are not designed to handle the complexity and uncertainty of cluttered indoor environments.\n* Using a larger number of human teleoperation demonstrations, such as 100 or 200 demonstrations. This approach was not chosen because it would increase the complexity and cost of the study, and may not provide significant additional benefits in terms of navigation performance."
