    "objective": "Quantify whether increasing habitat fragmentation, measured as decreasing mean patch size, reduces wild bee species richness in temperate agricultural landscapes.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "field sampling must occur in a single geographic region spanning no more than 200 km diameter",
      "fragmentation metric is mean patch area of semi-natural habitat within 1 km radius of each sampling site",
      "must sample at least 30 sites across a fragmentation gradient",
      "bee identification must be to species level, not morphospecies",
      "sampling protocol must use pan traps or netting, not both combined",
      "no sites within protected nature reserves"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a pollen-transport or pollination-service experiment to link diversity to function",
      "expand taxonomic scope to include hoverflies or butterflies as additional pollinator groups",
      "incorporate eDNA metabarcoding as a detection method"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Core Hypothesis\nIncreasing habitat fragmentation\u2014specifically measured as decreasing mean patch area of semi-natural habitat within a 1 km radius\u2014mechanistically reduces wild bee species richness in temperate agricultural landscapes. This effect operates independently of total habitat loss, but its magnitude is confounded or buffered by the spatial configuration of landscape-level crop diversity.\n\n### Minimal Viable Design\n**1. Site Selection (Orthogonal Landscape Design)**\nWe will use a geospatial algorithm to select 45 independent field margins within a single 150 km diameter temperate agricultural region. To break the natural collinearity of landscape variables, the algorithm will select a mathematically orthogonal matrix of sites where our focal metric (**mean patch area**) is completely de-correlated ($r \\approx 0$) from **total semi-natural area** and **crop diversity** (Shannon index). Local registries will be cross-referenced to guarantee zero sites fall within protected nature reserves.\n\n**2. Sampling Protocol**\nField sampling will exclusively utilize **active sweep netting** along standardized 150 m transects for fixed time intervals. Sampling will be temporally stratified across three phenological windows (pre-bloom, peak-bloom, post-bloom) to capture the full community. All collected wild bees will be expertly pinned and identified strictly to the species level. \n\n**3. Analytical Framework**\nVariable netting yields across the 45 sites will be standardized using coverage-based extrapolation (`iNEXT` package in R) to generate an asymptotic species richness estimate for each site. We will then fit a Spatially Explicit Structural Equation Model (Spatial SEM) guided by an *a priori* Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) to isolate the independent effects of mean patch area, total habitat amount, and crop diversity.\n\n### Primary Outcome\nThe study will report the standardized path coefficient (effect size) and 95% confidence interval for the direct regression of **mean patch area (1 km radius)** on **coverage-estimated species richness**. Because of the orthogonal design and spatial controls, this metric will represent a robust, causal species-fragmentation relationship.\n\n### Main Confound and Mitigation\n**Confound:** Observational fragmentation studies are inherently plagued by collinearity (shrinking patches almost always covary with total habitat loss and intensive crop monocultures), spatial autocorrelation (SAC), and the \"floral dilution effect\" (where passive traps catch fewer bees in resource-rich landscapes).\n**Mitigation:** \n1. *Collinearity:* Eliminated *a priori* via the orthogonal landscape site-selection algorithm.\n2. *Floral Dilution:* Eliminated by utilizing active sweep netting rather than passive pan traps.\n3. *Spatial Autocorrelation:* Eliminated by incorporating Moran's Eigenvector Maps (MEMs) into the SEM, which mathematically partials out unmeasured spatial clustering, guaranteeing unbiased confidence intervals. We will also explicitly model an interaction term (Mean Patch Area $\\times$ Crop Diversity) to test if crop diversity statistically confounds or ecologically buffers the fragmentation effect.\n\n### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1. **Hierarchical distance sampling (HDS) to jointly estimate detection and richness.** \n   *Reason for rejection:* HDS requires complex, stationary point-count protocols where researchers must accurately estimate the radial distance to fast-moving bees prior to netting. Using standardized temporal netting combined with coverage-based rarefaction fulfills the effort-standardization constraint with drastically lower field complexity, perfectly satisfying the minimal sufficient complexity rule.\n2. **Space-for-time substitution using GLMs with sites binned by patch size quartiles.**\n   *Reason for rejection:* Binning continuous spatial metrics into quartiles artificially reduces statistical power and destroys the continuous variance required to run our orthogonal site-selection algorithm. Retaining continuous mean patch area is strictly necessary to break the collinearity between fragmentation and habitat loss.\n\n---"
  },
