    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nDecreasing mean patch area of semi-natural habitat within 1 km of agricultural sites reduces wild bee species richness, and part of this effect operates through lower floral resource availability and reduced temporal stability of bee communities in more fragmented landscapes.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Study type:** repeated-measures field survey in a single temperate agricultural region\n- **Geography:** one region with a diameter of **\u2264200 km**\n- **Sites:** **36\u201348 sites** spanning a gradient of **mean patch area** of semi-natural habitat within a **1 km radius**\n- **Exclusions:** no sites inside protected nature reserves\n- **Bee sampling:** **pan traps only** at every site\n- **Taxonomy:** identify all bees to **species level**\n- **Temporal replication:** sample each site **twice in the same season** using the same protocol and effort\n- **Mechanism measurement:** at each visit, record a simple standardized measure of **floral resource availability** (e.g., flowering cover or flower abundance)\n- **Landscape covariates:** quantify **crop diversity** within the same 1 km buffer; optionally also record total semi-natural habitat area for interpretation\n\n### Analysis\n1. Standardize richness using **coverage-based estimation** or rarefaction.\n2. Fit a **mixed-effects regression** with:\n   - response: standardized bee species richness\n   - focal predictor: mean patch area\n   - covariates: crop diversity, floral resource availability, visit timing\n   - random effect: site\n3. Test whether the mean patch area effect is reduced after adding floral resource availability.\n4. Test whether the fragmentation effect is consistent across visits via a **mean patch area \u00d7 visit** interaction.\n5. Report **effect size and confidence interval** for the fragmentation effect.\n\n## Primary outcome\nA **species-fragmentation regression** estimating how bee species richness changes with mean patch area, reported with an effect size and confidence interval after accounting for sampling completeness and crop diversity.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n**Main confound:** landscape-level **crop diversity**, which could influence bee richness independently of fragmentation and also covary with patch size.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- measure crop diversity in the same **1 km buffer**\n- include crop diversity as a covariate in the main model\n- keep the study within one region and exclude protected reserves to reduce broad environmental heterogeneity\n- use repeated sampling and coverage-based richness estimation to reduce noise from temporal variation and unequal effort\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Hierarchical distance sampling**\n   - Advantage: explicitly models detection probability\n   - Not chosen because it is more complex to implement cleanly with a single bee sampling method and is not necessary for the core fragmentation question\n\n2. **Multi-scale buffer analysis**\n   - Advantage: could test whether 500 m, 1 km, or 2 km best predicts richness\n   - Not chosen because the brief already fixes the fragmentation metric at **1 km**, so adding extra scales would increase complexity without directly improving the target claim"
