    "final_proposal": "# Final Research Proposal\n\n## Long-Term Ambient PM2.5 Exposure and Childhood Asthma Incidence: A Multi-Identification Causal Cohort Study\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nLong-term ambient PM2.5 exposure causes incident asthma in children aged 0\u201312, with the effect concentrated in the alveolarisation window (ages 0\u20132 at time of exposure), mediated by oxidative-stress-driven lung development impairment, and of greater magnitude in low-income children due to biological vulnerability rather than differential exposure misclassification. The association is not explained by unmeasured neighbourhood-level confounders correlated with residential location choice.\n\nThis hypothesis has three components, each falsifiable:\n\n| Component | Falsification Criterion |\n|---|---|\n| PM2.5 causes asthma incidence | IV estimate IRR includes 1.0 across all instrument construction choices |\n| Effect concentrated in alveolarisation window (ages 0\u20132) | Constrained DLNM fits substantially worse (\u0394AIC \u2265 2) than unconstrained model, or lag-2\u20136 cumulative IRR does not exceed lag-0\u20131 IRR |\n| Larger effect in low-income children reflects biological vulnerability, not measurement error | Income \u00d7 PM2.5 interaction attenuates \u226515% when restricted to residentially stable children |\n\nAll three falsification criteria are pre-registered before any outcome data are analysed.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Overall Structure\nRetrospective cohort study using linked electronic health records (EHR) and Medicaid/CHIP administrative claims from California, Texas, and Pennsylvania (2005\u20132022), with PM2.5 exposure assigned from publicly available EPA and NASA surfaces geocoded to residential address. Three independent identification strategies are embedded within a single cohort and organised around a pre-specified DAG and estimand hierarchy.\n\n### Directed Acyclic Graph\n\n```\n                    Wind direction &\n                    emission sources\n                          \u2502\n                          \u2502 (instrument)\n                          \u25bc\nResidential         \u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510     Lung development     Incident\nlocation \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u25ba\u2502   PM2.5     \u2502\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u25ba impairment (0\u20132y) \u2500\u2500\u25ba Asthma\nchoice              \u2502   exposure  \u2502                            (ICD J45.x)\n                    \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n                          \u25b2                     \u25b2\n                          \u2502                     \u2502\n              \u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2534\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510          \u2502\n              \u2502                      \u2502          \u2502\n         Urbanicity            Household   Parental\n         (census)              income      smoking \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u25ba\u2518\n              \u2502                      \u2502\n              \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n                         \u2502\n                  Unmeasured neighbourhood\n                  factors (housing quality,\n                  stress, green space)\n                         \u2502\n                         \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u25ba Asthma\n```\n\nEvery modelling decision is derived from this DAG. Physician density is excluded from the primary model because it is a potential collider on the path from healthcare access to diagnosis; it appears only in a supplementary detection-bias check.\n\n### Cohort and Follow-Up\n\n| Parameter | Specification |\n|---|---|\n| Source | EHR + Medicaid/CHIP claims, CA + TX + PA |\n| Entry criterion | First clinical encounter; no prior ICD asthma code; 12-month look-back |\n| Age at entry | 0\u201312 years |\n| Follow-up end | First asthma diagnosis, age 13, death, disenrollment, or 31 December 2022 |\n| Minimum cohort size | 5,000 asthma-na\u00efve children (hard constraint floor) |\n| Target enrolment | \u226515,000 to ensure adequate power after exclusions |\n| Birth cohort enrichment | Oversample children born 2005\u20132010 to ensure \u22655 years follow-up for lag estimation |\n\n### Exposure Assignment\n**Primary:** Annual-average PM2.5 (\u00b5g/m\u00b3) from the EPA Downscaler Fused Air Quality Surface (~12 km resolution), supplemented by NASA SEDAC Global Annual PM2.5 Grids (~1 km) where Fused Surface coverage is incomplete. Both are publicly available. Assigned annually by geocoding residential address and extracting the grid cell value. Updated each calendar year (time-varying).\n\n**Instrument:** Upwind industrial source exposure (USE) score, constructed annually per child from EPA National Emissions Inventory point-source locations and NOAA Integrated Surface Database wind direction data:\n\n```\nUSE_it = \u03a3\u2c7c [E\u2c7c \u00d7 I(source j upwind of child i in year t) \u00d7 (1/d\u1d62\u2c7c\u00b2)]\n\nWhere:\n  E\u2c7c   = annual PM2.5-relevant emissions (SO\u2082 + NO\u2093 + direct PM2.5)\n           from NEI point source j\n  I(\u00b7) = 1 if \u226540% of daily wind observations place source j upwind\n           of child i (within \u00b130\u00b0 of prevailing direction) in year t\n  d\u1d62\u2c7c\u00b2 = squared distance, child i to source j\n```\n\nWind direction drives variation in USE independently of neighbourhood socioeconomic characteristics. The instrument is direction-based, not proximity-based, which separates meteorological PM2.5 variation from the economic effects of industrial facility proximity.\n\n### Three Identification Strategies and Their Estimands\n\n| Strategy | Estimand | Primary Use in Argument |\n|---|---|---|\n| Covariate-adjusted constrained DLNM | ATE conditional on measured covariates | Describes exposure-response shape and lag structure |\n| DiD exploiting 2012 NAAQS tightening | ATT in non-attainment counties | Translates finding into policy-relevant terms |\n| Wind-based IV (2SLS, Poisson second stage) | LATE for wind-exposed compliers | Primary causal identification; least vulnerable to neighbourhood confounding |\n\n**Pre-specified reconciliation hierarchy:**\n1. All three strategies must show IRR > 1 for the causal hypothesis to be supported. Any strategy yielding IRR < 1 with CI excluding 1.0 is a pre-specified falsification.\n2. Expected magnitude ordering: IV (LATE) \u2265 DLNM (ATE) \u2265 DiD (ATT), based on estimand theory. Deviations are reported and interpreted explicitly.\n3. The IV estimate is the primary causal estimate reported in the abstract. The DLNM estimate is the primary descriptive estimate. The DiD estimate is the primary policy estimate. These roles are stated in the pre-registration.\n\n### Primary Model\nBiologically constrained DLNM in a Poisson person-year framework:\n\n```\nlog[E(Y\u1d62\u209c)] = log(PT\u1d62\u209c) + \u03b1 + cb(PM2.5, lag=1:6, w(\u2113)=exp(-\u03bb\u2113), \u03bb>0)\n               + \u03b2\u00b7income + \u03b2\u00b7smoking + \u03b2\u00b7sex + \u03b2\u00b7race\n               + \u03b2\u00b7urbanicity + \u03b2\u00b7gestage + \u03b2\u00b7insurance\n               + \u03b3_state + \u03b4_year\n\nWhere:\n  w(\u2113) = exp(-\u03bb\u2113)  constrains lag weights to monotonic decay\n  \u03bb     is estimated from data with constraint \u03bb > 0\n  lag 1\u20136 corresponds to exposure 1\u20136 years prior to diagnosis,\n  targeting the alveolarisation window for children diagnosed\n  at ages 4\u20138 (the modal diagnosis age in the literature)\n```\n\nThe constraint is falsifiable: if the unconstrained model fits substantially better (\u0394AIC \u2265 2), the monotonic-decay biological hypothesis is rejected and the unconstrained estimate is reported as primary.\n\n### Sensitivity Analyses\n\n| # | Analysis | Causal Function |\n|---|---|---|\n| SA-1 | Constrained vs. unconstrained DLNM (\u0394AIC) | Tests biological lag constraint against data |\n| SA-2 | 3-year rolling average exposure window | **Hard constraint: exposure window modification** |\n| SA-3 | Residentially stable sub-cohort (\u22641 address change) | Reduces misclassification; enables EJ mechanism test |\n| SA-4 | Cox model, single-year lagged PM2.5 | Literature comparability; outputs aHR |\n| SA-5 | ALRI positive control outcome | Validates exposure assignment and pipeline |\n| SA-6 | Otitis media negative control outcome | Rules out healthcare-access confounding |\n| SA-7 | DiD around 2012 NAAQS change | Policy-relevant ATT estimate |\n| SA-8 | IV excluding co-pollutant (NO\u2082, O\u2083) adjustment | Tests exclusion restriction sensitivity |\n| SA-9 | IV using SO\u2082 emissions only | Tests instrument construction sensitivity |\n| SA-10 | EC vs. crustal material constituent models | Specificity argument against generic urban confounding |\n| SA-11 | EJ interaction in stable sub-cohort | Distinguishes biological vulnerability from measurement error |\n| SA-12 | E-value for IV primary estimate | Quantifies residual unmeasured confounding robustness |\n\n### Analysis Sequence and Pre-Registration\n```\n1. Pre-register DAG, primary model, falsification criteria,\n   reconciliation hierarchy, and all SA definitions on OSF\n   \u2190 hard stop: no outcome data accessed before this step\n\n2. Obtain IRB approval and data use agreements\n\n3. Geocode addresses; assign PM2.5 and USE scores\n\n4. Apply inclusion/exclusion criteria; document in CONSORT flow\n\n5. Run first-stage IV regression; report F-statistic and partial R\u00b2\n   \u2190 if F < 10, instrument is weak; pre-specified response:\n     report IV as exploratory only, elevate DiD to primary causal estimate\n\n6. Run primary constrained DLNM; compare to unconstrained (\u0394AIC)\n\n7. Run DiD; test parallel pre-trends formally (F-test of pre-period\n   interaction) and visually\n\n8. Run IV second stage; compute bootstrapped CIs (1,000 iterations,\n   clustered on census tract)\n\n9. Apply reconciliation hierarchy; report all three estimates with\n   explicit estimand labels\n\n10. Run SA-1 through SA-12 in pre-specified order\n\n11. Run EJ effect modification models; apply stable sub-cohort test\n\n12. Label any unplanned analyses as post-hoc in manuscript\n```\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n**Incident asthma**, defined as the first occurrence of either:\n- \u22652 outpatient ICD-10 J45.x (or ICD-9 493.x) codes on separate dates within any 12-month window, or\n- \u22651 inpatient or emergency department ICD-10 J45.x code\n\nChildren with any asthma-related ICD code in the 12-month look-back period before cohort entry are excluded. This validated algorithm (adapted from Schatz et al. 2010; Osborne et al. 2007) reduces single-encounter miscoding while capturing severe presentations through the inpatient criterion.\n\n**Reported metric:** Incidence rate ratio (IRR) per 1 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 increase in annual-average PM2.5, with 95% confidence interval, from the primary constrained DLNM. The Cox model (SA-4) additionally reports an adjusted hazard ratio (aHR) for meta-analytic comparability with prior literature.\n\n**Validity checks on outcome definition:**\n- ALRI (ICD-10 J20\u2013J22) as positive control: expected IRR > 1, confirming the exposure pipeline detects known PM2.5-sensitive outcomes in the same cohort\n- Otitis media (ICD-10 H65\u2013H66) as negative control: expected IRR \u2248 1, ruling out healthcare-access confounding as a driver of the asthma result\n- If the otitis media IRR exceeds 1.10 with CI excluding 1.0, this is a pre-specified signal of unresolved detection bias; the physician density supplementary analysis is elevated to the main text\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n### The Confound\n**Unmeasured neighbourhood-level factors** \u2014 housing quality, psychosocial stress, green space, traffic noise, food environment \u2014 are simultaneously correlated with residential PM2.5 levels (because pollution burden is geographically and socioeconomically patterned) and with childhood asthma risk (through multiple biological and social pathways). No set of measured covariates, however comprehensive, can fully adjust for this cluster of confounders because they are not systematically recorded in EHR or claims data.\n\nThis is the single threat that, if unaddressed, would allow a reviewer to attribute the entire observed association to residential self-selection rather than PM2.5 exposure.\n\n### The Mitigation: Three-Layer Defence\n\n**Layer 1 \u2014 Covariate adjustment (necessary but insufficient):**\nIncome, parental smoking, race/ethnicity, urbanicity, gestational age, insurance type, state fixed effects, and calendar-year fixed effects are included in all models. These absorb the measured component of neighbourhood confounding. Pre-cohort PM2.5 trend (2000\u20132004 mean at residential address) is added to control for long-standing pollution environments that may have selected residential location.\n\n**Layer 2 \u2014 DiD exploiting regulatory discontinuity:**\nThe 2012 NAAQS tightening produced differential PM2.5 reductions across counties based on pre-existing attainment status \u2014 a change driven by federal regulation, not by local neighbourhood characteristics. The DiD estimate compares asthma incidence trends in non-attainment counties (treated) versus attainment counties (control) before and after 2012. Confounders that are stable within counties over time are differenced out. The parallel pre-trends assumption is formally tested; violation is a pre-specified reason to report the DiD as inconclusive.\n\n**Layer 3 \u2014 Wind-based instrumental variable (primary causal identification):**\nThe USE instrument isolates variation in PM2.5 driven by meteorology \u2014 specifically, whether prevailing winds carry industrial emissions toward a child's home in a given year. This variation is:\n- Correlated with actual PM2.5 (relevance; tested by first-stage F-statistic)\n- Independent of neighbourhood socioeconomic characteristics (exogeneity; tested by regressing USE on all covariates; target R\u00b2 < 0.05)\n- Affecting asthma only through PM2.5, not through other pathways (exclusion restriction; partially tested by co-pollutant adjustment in SA-8; residual threat acknowledged and quantified via E-value in SA-12)\n\nThe direction-based design of the instrument (upwind vs. crosswind children near the same facility) separates meteorological exposure variation from the economic effects of industrial proximity, which is the primary threat to a simpler distance-to-source instrument.\n\n**Convergence criterion:** If all three layers produce IRR > 1 with CIs excluding 1.0, and the IV and DiD estimates are directionally consistent with the DLNM estimate, the unmeasured neighbourhood confounding explanation requires those confounders to bias all three identification strategies simultaneously in the same direction \u2014 a substantially harder argument for a reviewer to sustain than critiquing any single strategy.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Propensity-Score Matched Cohort Design\n\n**Description:** Children in high-PM2.5 ZIP codes are matched to children in low-PM2.5 ZIP codes on measured covariates (income, race, urbanicity, parental smoking, insurance type) using 1:1 nearest-neighbour propensity score matching. A Cox model is then run in the matched sample.\n\n**Why it was not chosen:**\nPropensity score matching addresses confounding by *measured* covariates only. It does not address unmeasured neighbourhood confounders, which are the primary threat identified in the DAG. In fact, matching on income and urbanicity may *worsen* residual confounding by unmeasured factors if those factors are correlated with the matched variables in complex ways \u2014 a phenomenon known as bias amplification. Additionally, matching discards unmatched children, reducing the effective sample size and power, and collapses the continuous exposure distribution into a binary high/low contrast, losing the dose-response information that the DLNM provides. The IV analysis supersedes propensity score matching for the purpose of addressing unmeasured confounding while retaining the full cohort and continuous exposure.\n\n**Retained as:** A supplementary analysis to bound the effect estimate under the assumption that measured covariates are sufficient \u2014 explicitly labelled with this assumption in the manuscript.\n\n### Alternative 2: Distributed-Lag Nonlinear Model Without Biological Constraint (Fully Flexible DLNM)\n\n**Description:** A DLNM with natural splines on both the exposure-response and lag dimensions (4 df each), making no prior assumptions about the shape of the lag-response function. The lag-response curve is estimated entirely from the data and interpreted post-hoc.\n\n**Why it was not"
  },
