    "item_number": 40,
    "run_id": "62f80e1090a4",
    "brief_id": "legal_02",
    "domain": "criminal justice policy",
    "objective": "Test whether jurisdiction-level bail reform policies that eliminate cash bail for misdemeanors reduce the Black-white gap in pretrial detention rates without increasing failure-to-appear rates.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "quasi-experimental design using staggered policy adoption across jurisdictions, no randomization",
      "treatment defined as statutory or administrative elimination of cash bail for all misdemeanor charges, not partial reforms or judicial discretion changes",
      "pretrial detention measured from official jail booking records, not survey data",
      "racial disparity must be operationalized as the Black-white ratio of pretrial detention rates, not raw counts",
      "must include at least 4 reform-adopting jurisdictions and at least 4 comparison jurisdictions",
      "analysis must span at least 2 years pre-reform and 2 years post-reform",
      "failure-to-appear rate must be measured from court administrative records within the same jurisdictions"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a qualitative interview component with judges or defendants",
      "expand the outcome to include felony charges alongside misdemeanors",
      "incorporate recidivism or re-arrest as an outcome measure",
      "use individual-level risk assessment scores as a control variable"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "# Final Research Proposal\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nFull statutory elimination of cash bail for misdemeanor charges reduces the Black-white pretrial detention rate ratio by constraining judges to make active, explicitly justified detention decisions rather than passively applying a cash bail default. Because racial bias operates more readily through passive defaults than through active, scrutinized choices, removing the default disproportionately benefits Black defendants who were detained under the prior regime not because of assessed flight risk but because the default was applied without individualized justification. The effect should be immediate in onset, stable in magnitude after onset, and specific to the misdemeanor charge class \u2014 the only class subject to the rule change. Failure-to-appear rates should not increase beyond a policy-relevant margin because the defendants released under the new regime are those for whom the prior detention was default-driven rather than risk-driven.\n\n**Null hypothesis:** Full misdemeanor cash bail elimination produces no change in the Black-white pretrial detention rate ratio.\n\n**Directional alternative:** Full misdemeanor cash bail elimination reduces the Black-white pretrial detention rate ratio, with the effect (a) appearing within one month of the reform effective date, (b) remaining stable rather than growing or decaying over the post-reform window, and (c) absent in the felony charge class within the same jurisdictions over the same period.\n\n**Non-inferiority hypothesis for FTA:** The post-reform change in misdemeanor failure-to-appear rate does not exceed +2 percentage points, pre-specified as the maximum acceptable increase before reform is considered harmful to court process integrity.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Design Class\nStaggered difference-in-differences with a within-jurisdiction charge-class placebo, implemented as a triple difference (DDD). The DDD is the minimal design that simultaneously satisfies the hard constraints and defends the causal identification assumption against the most damaging available critique \u2014 that adopting jurisdictions were on differential disparity trajectories for reasons unrelated to bail reform.\n\n### Why This Is the Minimum Necessary\nA simple two-way fixed effects DiD on the misdemeanor series alone would satisfy the hard constraints but would leave the parallel trends assumption entirely dependent on cross-jurisdiction comparability. Adding the felony placebo series and estimating the DDD converts the identifying assumption from \"treated and control jurisdictions would have had parallel misdemeanor disparity trends\" to \"any differential trend in treated jurisdictions affected misdemeanor and felony disparity proportionally\" \u2014 a strictly weaker and more defensible assumption that absorbs all jurisdiction-specific time-varying confounds that operate across charge classes. No additional design element is needed to defend the primary causal claim. Every other component either tests the causal mechanism or bounds a threat to the welfare interpretation, and each is retained only because it is derivable from the committed causal model without adding new data sources or analytical degrees of freedom.\n\n### Sample Requirements\n- \u22654 jurisdictions with full statutory misdemeanor cash bail elimination on a recorded effective date\n- \u22654 jurisdictions in the same states that did not adopt, serving as controls\n- Continuous jail booking records and court administrative records covering 24 months before and 24 months after each jurisdiction's adoption date\n- All jurisdictions must have felony booking records in the same system as misdemeanor records, enabling the within-jurisdiction charge-class comparison\n\n### Estimator\nPrimary: Callaway & Sant'Anna (2021) staggered DiD applied to the misdemeanor series, producing group-time average treatment effects aggregated to a single post-reform ATT with 95% simultaneous confidence intervals.\n\nIdentification test: Triple-difference specification stacking misdemeanor and felony series:\n\n$$\\ln(R_{jct}) = \\alpha_{jc} + \\gamma_{ct} + \\delta_{jt} + \\beta \\cdot Post_{jt} \\cdot Treat_j \\cdot Misd_c + X_{jt}'\\delta + \\varepsilon_{jct}$$\n\nWhere $\\alpha_{jc}$ absorbs time-invariant jurisdiction \u00d7 charge-class disparity levels, $\\gamma_{ct}$ absorbs national trends specific to each charge class, $\\delta_{jt}$ absorbs all jurisdiction-specific time-varying shocks regardless of source, and $\\beta$ identifies the misdemeanor-specific response to reform in treated jurisdictions relative to controls. Standard errors clustered at the jurisdiction level with wild cluster bootstrap if the cluster count falls below 30.\n\n### Sequential Analysis Gates\nThe analysis follows a pre-registered sequence with decision rules at each stage:\n\n**Gate 1 \u2014 Existence:** Does the primary DiD on $\\ln(R^{misd}_{jt})$ produce a negative and significant $\\widehat{ATT}$? If not, the paper reports a precise null and stops making causal claims about disparity reduction.\n\n**Gate 2 \u2014 Specificity:** Does the DDD produce a negative $\\hat{\\beta}$ while the felony post-reform coefficients are jointly indistinguishable from zero? If the felony series moves, a jurisdiction-level confound is present and the paper reframes as a descriptive policy evaluation with an explicitly unresolved identification threat.\n\n**Gate 3 \u2014 Timing:** Are the event-study coefficients consistent with immediacy (significant at $k=0$) and stability (flat post-reform path, joint Wald test fails to reject $\\beta_k = \\beta_{k+1}$ for $k \\geq 1$)? If the path is growing, the paper reframes the mechanism as learning-based rather than default-shift. If the path is declining, the paper investigates enforcement fidelity before drawing welfare conclusions.\n\n**Gate 4 \u2014 Offset bound:** Does the DiD on the misdemeanor filing rate ratio show a change smaller than 20% of the magnitude of the detention ratio effect? If the bound is exceeded, the welfare interpretation is revised to acknowledge partial prosecutorial offset of the disparity reduction.\n\n**Gate 5 \u2014 Non-inferiority:** Does the upper bound of the one-sided 95% CI for the FTA effect fall at or below +2 percentage points? Non-inferiority is declared only if this condition is met.\n\n### Pre-Registration\nAll five gates, the non-inferiority margin, the 20% prosecutorial offset bound, and the primary model specification are pre-registered on OSF before any data access. The pre-registration document specifies exactly what the paper will conclude under each possible combination of gate outcomes, eliminating post-hoc reframing.\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n**Black-white pretrial misdemeanor detention rate ratio**, computed monthly at the jurisdiction level:\n\n$$R^{misd}_{jt} = \\frac{D^{Black}_{jt} \\;/\\; A^{Black}_{jt}}{D^{White}_{jt} \\;/\\; A^{White}_{jt}}$$\n\nWhere $D$ = number of individuals detained pretrial on misdemeanor charges, $A$ = number of misdemeanor arrests, both from official jail booking records. The ratio is logged for regression: $\\ln(R^{misd}_{jt})$.\n\n**Denominator:** Misdemeanor arrests by race from NIBRS agency-level extracts, matched to jurisdictions by agency identifier. Where NIBRS coverage is incomplete, the denominator falls back to ACS jurisdiction-level racial population estimates with a sensitivity analysis comparing both denominators in the overlapping subsample.\n\n**Reported quantity:** The aggregated post-reform $\\widehat{ATT}$ from CS(2021), expressed as a percentage change in the Black-white detention ratio, with 95% simultaneous confidence intervals. The paper reports this quantity for the primary DiD and for the DDD, with the DDD estimate treated as the preferred causal estimate and the primary DiD as the reduced-form benchmark.\n\n**Secondary reported quantity:** The change in failure-to-appear rate $\\Delta \\widehat{FTA}$ with 95% CI and explicit comparison to the pre-specified +2 percentage point non-inferiority margin.\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n### The Confound\n**Differential jurisdiction trajectories in the Black-white misdemeanor detention ratio.** Jurisdictions that adopt full misdemeanor bail elimination are not randomly selected. They are likely to be jurisdictions that already had rising concern about racial disparities in pretrial detention, active reform advocacy, or political leadership sympathetic to decarceration. These same conditions may independently cause the Black-white misdemeanor detention ratio to decline \u2014 through changes in prosecutorial charging priorities, shifts in policing intensity in Black neighborhoods, or demographic and economic changes affecting who is arrested for misdemeanors. If these trends were underway before reform and accelerate around the reform date, the DiD estimate conflates the reform effect with the underlying trajectory, even if pre-trend tests appear to pass, because the acceleration itself is the confound.\n\nThis is the most damaging available critique because it is (a) institutionally plausible, (b) not fully addressed by pre-trend tests if the trend change is contemporaneous with adoption, and (c) not resolved by adding more control jurisdictions, since the confound is jurisdiction-specific.\n\n### The Mitigation\nThe DDD specification with the felony charge-class placebo directly addresses this confound. Any jurisdiction-specific shock \u2014 accelerating reform advocacy, policing intensity changes, demographic shifts, economic shocks, or simultaneous policy changes \u2014 that affects the overall pretrial detention environment will affect both the misdemeanor and felony disparity ratios. The $\\delta_{jt}$ term in the DDD absorbs these shocks entirely. The only remaining threat is a shock that specifically and exclusively affects the misdemeanor disparity ratio without affecting the felony disparity ratio, in treated jurisdictions, coinciding precisely with the reform effective date. This residual threat requires an implausibly specific confound: a simultaneous intervention that targets only misdemeanor arraignment decisions, only in adopting jurisdictions, only at the moment of adoption, without affecting felony arraignment decisions in the same courtrooms by the same judges. No such intervention is institutionally plausible in the U.S. criminal justice context.\n\nThe mitigation is further strengthened by three supporting elements:\n\n**Supporting element 1 \u2014 Pre-trend test on the charge-class differential.** The identifying assumption for the DDD is testable in the pre-period. Rather than testing parallel trends in the misdemeanor series alone, the pre-trend test examines whether the *difference* between misdemeanor and felony disparity ratios was trending differentially across treated and control jurisdictions before adoption. If the pre-period DDD coefficients are jointly zero, the assumption is supported.\n\n**Supporting element 2 \u2014 Robustness to simultaneous reform exclusion.** Jurisdictions that enacted any co-occurring criminal justice reform within \u00b112 months of bail reform adoption are dropped and the DDD is re-estimated. If the estimate is stable, the confound from simultaneous reforms is bounded. If it changes materially, the paper reports which co-occurring reforms drive the instability and interprets the primary estimate with appropriate caution.\n\n**Supporting element 3 \u2014 Prosecutorial filing rate test.** The DiD on the misdemeanor filing rate ratio (Black-white) directly tests whether the misdemeanor-specific trajectory changed for reasons other than the detention rule \u2014 specifically, whether prosecutors shifted the composition of misdemeanor cases filed by race around the time of reform. A null result on the filing rate ratio, combined with a significant result on the detention ratio, supports the interpretation that the detention-decision channel rather than case-composition change is driving the primary finding.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Regression Discontinuity Around the Legislative Effective Date\n\nA regression discontinuity design exploiting the sharp effective date of a single large jurisdiction's bail reform \u2014 treating calendar time as the running variable and the effective date as the cutoff \u2014 would provide clean local identification of the reform's immediate effect without requiring cross-jurisdiction comparability. The RD estimate would be interpreted as the average treatment effect for cases processed immediately around the effective date, where the only difference between the treatment and control observations is which side of the cutoff they fall on.\n\n**Why not chosen:** This design structurally cannot satisfy the hard constraint requiring \u22654 reform-adopting jurisdictions. An RD within a single jurisdiction identifies the reform effect for that jurisdiction only, and the estimate cannot be generalized to the policy question of whether bail reform as a class of interventions reduces racial disparities. Additionally, the RD estimate is local to the cutoff \u2014 it identifies the effect for defendants processed in the weeks immediately around the effective date, who may be systematically different from defendants processed months later as the new regime becomes routine. The default-shift mechanism specifically predicts that the most important behavioral changes occur as judges adapt to the new rule over the first several months, which the RD cannot capture. The staggered DiD with DDD recovers the full post-reform trajectory across multiple jurisdictions at the cost of a weaker identification assumption that is explicitly addressed by the charge-class placebo.\n\n### Alternative 2: Synthetic Control for a Single Large Reform Jurisdiction\n\nThe synthetic control method would construct a weighted combination of non-reforming jurisdictions whose pre-reform misdemeanor disparity ratio trajectory closely matches that of a single large adopting jurisdiction \u2014 for example, New Jersey's 2017 bail reform or New Mexico's county-level implementations. The synthetic control provides a transparent, data-driven counterfactual without imposing parametric assumptions, and the visual comparison between the treated jurisdiction and its synthetic counterpart is highly legible to non-technical audiences and policymakers.\n\n**Why not chosen:** Like the RD, this design structurally cannot satisfy the hard constraint requiring \u22654 reform-adopting jurisdictions, since the synthetic control is defined for a single treated unit. More fundamentally, the synthetic control does not resolve the main confound identified above \u2014 it addresses the parallel trends problem by matching on pre-reform trajectories, but it cannot absorb jurisdiction-specific shocks that are contemporaneous with the reform effective date, which is precisely the threat the DDD is designed to address. A synthetic control for New Jersey would be unable to distinguish the bail reform effect from simultaneous changes in New Jersey's prosecutorial practices, policing priorities, or demographic composition that happened to coincide with the 2017 reform. The staggered DiD with DDD is chosen over the synthetic control because it uses multiple adopting jurisdictions (satisfying the hard constraint), addresses the contemporaneous confound directly through the charge-class placebo, and produces a generalizable estimate rather than a jurisdiction-specific one.\n\n---"
  },
