    "final_proposal": "**Core hypothesis**  \nDual-task interference on a primary visual working memory task will be greater when the secondary task is visual compared to auditory, even when secondary-task difficulty is equated. This is predicted by the modality-specific competition hypothesis, which posits that interference is stronger within the same perceptual modality due to shared representational and maintenance resources in visual working memory.\n\n---\n\n**Minimal viable design**  \nA within-subjects design with 3 conditions administered in a counterbalanced order:  \n1. **Single-task baseline**: Participants perform only the primary visual working memory change-detection task.  \n2. **Visual dual-task**: Participants perform the primary task concurrently with a visual secondary task.  \n3. **Auditory dual-task**: Participants perform the primary task concurrently with an auditory secondary task.  \n\nAll tasks are implemented using a computer-based interface. Each condition consists of 48 trials, with intermixed trial types in dual-task blocks (i.e., primary and secondary task events temporally overlapped or closely spaced). The full session includes practice blocks for all tasks, calibration of secondary-task difficulty via pilot testing, and feedback to maintain engagement.\n\n**Primary task**: Change-detection with set size 4. On each trial, participants view a memory array of 4 colored squares for 500 ms, followed by a 900 ms retention interval, then a test array. They respond whether any item changed (yes/no) using keyboard responses. Distractors differ in color only; changes are non-matching colors.\n\n**Visual secondary task (chosen)**: *Rapid visual categorization with response selection*. During the retention interval of the primary task, participants view a stream of 4 briefly presented (100 ms each) Gabor patches in the periphery, with one target (e.g., vertical orientation) to be detected. They must indicate, via button press, whether a target was present after the test array. This task is processing-demanding and taxes executive control and attentional resources within the visual modality.\n\n**Auditory secondary task**: *Frequency discrimination with response selection*. During the retention interval, participants hear a sequence of 4 tones (100 ms each), with one deviant tone (higher pitch) embedded in standard tones. They respond after the test array whether a deviant was present. The task is matched in structure and response demands to the visual version.\n\nSecondary tasks are pilot-calibrated to ensure accuracy differs by no more than \u00b15 percentage points between modalities (e.g., both ~75\u201380% correct). Difficulty is adjusted pre-experiment via parametric manipulation (e.g., orientation contrast for Gabors, frequency separation for tones).\n\nParticipants: 60 adults (within 40\u201380 range), recruited from a university subject pool. Session duration: ~80 minutes (practice: 15 min; experimental blocks: 60 min; breaks: 5 min between blocks).\n\nCounterbalancing: Order of the three main conditions is balanced using a Latin square design. Practice blocks precede each condition.\n\n---\n\n**Primary outcome**  \nChange-detection sensitivity in the primary task, measured as **d-prime (d\u2032)**, calculated separately for each condition:  \n- *d\u2032 = z(Hit Rate) \u2212 z(False Alarm Rate)*  \n- Hits: correct \"change\" responses on change trials  \n- False alarms: \"change\" responses on no-change trials  \n\nA planned contrast will compare dual-task interference:  \n**(d\u2032_visual_dual \u2212 d\u2032_single)** minus **(d\u2032_auditory_dual \u2212 d\u2032_single)**  \nThis quantifies the *additional* interference from a visual vs. auditory secondary task.\n\n---\n\n**Main confound and mitigation**  \n**Confound**: Differential task-switching or response interference in dual-task blocks, unrelated to modality-specific resource competition.  \n\n**Mitigation**:  \n- **Temporal alignment**: Secondary task stimuli are presented only during the 900 ms retention interval of the primary task, minimizing overlap with encoding and response phases.  \n- **Response timing**: Secondary-task responses are delayed until after the primary-task response, preventing motor interference and allowing clean separation of decision processes.  \n- **Structural equivalence**: Both secondary tasks have identical trial structure (4-item sequence, 1 target, yes/no response), timing, and response mapping (e.g., same two keys, counterbalanced mapping).  \n- **Pilot calibration**: Ensures secondary tasks are matched on accuracy and perceived difficulty (via post-task ratings), reducing strategic differences.\n\n---\n\n**Two plausible alternatives not chosen**  \n\n1. **Spatial array memorization (storage-demanding visual secondary task)**  \n   - *Why not chosen*: While it directly competes for visual maintenance resources, it may induce stronger proactive interference or chunking strategies, increasing variance. It also risks being too similar to the primary task (both involve color/spatial memory), potentially inflating interference beyond typical executive control demands. The processing-demanding task provides a more generalizable test of visual-domain interference under concurrent cognitive load.\n\n2. **Continuous flicker monitoring (sustained-attention visual secondary task)**  \n   - *Why not chosen*: This taps vigilance rather than working memory or executive control, and may not engage the same transient, high-load processes as the primary task. It could lead to different time-on-task effects and drift in attention, complicating d\u2032 interpretation. The rapid categorization task better matches the temporal dynamics and cognitive demands of the primary task.\n\n---"
  },
