    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nDual-task interference on visual working memory will be larger when the concurrent secondary task is **visual** rather than **auditory**, even when the secondary tasks are matched for standalone difficulty. The causal claim is that **concurrent visual attentional selection** competes more strongly with the visual selection/maintenance operations needed for change detection than does matched auditory selection.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Design:** within-subjects, exactly 3 conditions  \n  1. **Single-task baseline:** visual change detection only  \n  2. **Visual dual-task:** visual change detection + visual secondary task  \n  3. **Auditory dual-task:** visual change detection + auditory secondary task  \n\n- **Primary task:**  \n  - Change-detection paradigm  \n  - **Set size fixed at 4** across all conditions\n\n- **Secondary tasks:**  \n  - **Visual task:** brief visual target detection / search / discrimination task  \n  - **Auditory task:** matched auditory target detection / discrimination task  \n  - Pilot-calibrated so standalone accuracy matches within **5 percentage points**\n\n- **Added rigor component:**  \n  - Brief **in-session verification block** to confirm the calibration still holds in the tested sample before the main dual-task blocks\n\n- **Session structure:**  \n  - Single session, comfortably under **90 minutes**\n  - Main condition order counterbalanced\n\n- **Sample size:**  \n  - Choose a value in the allowed range, ideally around **48\u201360** for a practical lab study\n\n## Primary outcome\n- **Change-detection sensitivity (d-prime)** for the primary task in each of the three conditions\n- Planned contrast:\n  - \\[(Baseline \u2212 Visual dual) \u2212 (Baseline \u2212 Auditory dual)\\]\n- This directly tests whether the **visual** secondary task produces greater interference than the **auditory** one\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n### Main confound\nThe visual secondary task could be criticized as simply being **harder** or more attentionally demanding than the auditory task, rather than specifically competing with visual working memory.\n\n### Mitigation\n- **Pilot calibration** to match standalone accuracy within 5 percentage points\n- **Brief in-session verification block** to confirm the match in the actual sample\n- Keep the secondary tasks:\n  - brief\n  - trial-based\n  - similar response format\n  - counterbalanced in order across participants\n\nThis makes it harder to argue that any interference difference is just a difficulty artifact.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Storage-demanding visual secondary task vs matched auditory storage/discrimination task**  \n   - This would support a maintenance-resource account  \n   - Not chosen because it is less mechanistically sharp for the specific causal story and may be harder to keep equally matched\n\n2. **Sustained-attention visual monitoring task vs matched auditory monitoring task**  \n   - This would emphasize vigilance/resource maintenance  \n   - Not chosen because it is more vulnerable to fatigue, timing drift, and calibration problems within a single <90-minute session"
