    "objective": "Does 36 hours of total sleep deprivation impair working memory updating accuracy on an N-back task (2-back and 3-back) relative to a rested control group in healthy adults aged 18-35?",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "Participants must be healthy adults aged 18-35 with no diagnosed sleep disorders",
      "Sleep deprivation condition is exactly 36 hours of continuous wakefulness verified by wrist actigraphy",
      "Control group sleeps 7-9 hours the night before testing, confirmed by actigraphy",
      "Primary outcome is d-prime on 2-back and 3-back conditions; reaction time is secondary only",
      "Minimum 20 participants per group (sleep-deprived vs rested)",
      "No caffeine, alcohol, or stimulant use permitted in the 24 hours before testing",
      "Testing session occurs between 08:00 and 10:00 to control circadian phase"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "Administering modafinil, caffeine, or any pharmacological countermeasure during deprivation",
      "Replacing the N-back task with a different working memory paradigm (e.g., Sternberg, change detection)",
      "Using self-reported sleep logs instead of actigraphy for sleep verification",
      "Adding emotional stimuli to the N-back to study affective modulation"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Research Proposal: Effects of 36-Hour Total Sleep Deprivation on Working Memory Updating Accuracy in Healthy Adults**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**  \nWe hypothesize that 36 hours of total sleep deprivation will significantly impair working memory updating accuracy, as measured by d-prime, on the 3-back condition of the N-back task, compared to a rested control group. We expect a medium-to-large effect size (Cohen\u2019s d > 0.5) in the 3-back condition, with smaller or non-significant effects in the 2-back condition.\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**  \nA **between-subjects design** with two groups:  \n- **Sleep-deprived group (n = 25)**: 36 hours of continuous wakefulness, verified by wrist actigraphy.  \n- **Rested control group (n = 25)**: 7\u20139 hours of self-reported habitual sleep the prior night, confirmed by actigraphy.  \n\nAll participants are healthy adults aged 18\u201335, free of diagnosed sleep disorders. Testing occurs between 08:00 and 10:00 to minimize circadian confounds. Participants abstain from caffeine, alcohol, and stimulants for 24 hours prior to testing.  \n\nEach participant completes a single testing session including 2-back and 3-back N-back tasks. D-prime (sensitivity index) is computed for each condition. Reaction time is recorded but not analyzed for primary inference.\n\nStatistical analysis: Independent samples t-test (or Mann-Whitney U if assumptions violated) comparing d-prime between groups for each N-back level (2-back and 3-back), with significance set at p < 0.05. Effect size (Cohen\u2019s d) is calculated for the 3-back comparison.\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**  \nD-prime (A') on the **2-back and 3-back N-back tasks**, calculated as:  \nd\u2019 = z(Hit Rate) \u2013 z(False Alarm Rate)  \nusing standard signal detection theory methods. This is analyzed separately for 2-back and 3-back conditions. The 3-back condition is the focus for effect size evaluation.\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**  \n**Confound:** Circadian rhythm effects on cognitive performance, particularly in the sleep-deprived group who are tested at the end of 36 hours awake (equivalent to 36+ hours since last sleep onset).  \n\n**Mitigation:**  \n- All testing occurs between **08:00 and 10:00**, aligning the rested group\u2019s morning testing with the sleep-deprived group\u2019s 36-hour mark, which typically begins at 08:00 post-baseline sleep.  \n- This ensures both groups are tested at the same clock time, reducing variability due to diurnal fluctuations.  \n- Actigraphy confirms compliance with sleep/wake schedules, and all participants maintain a regular sleep schedule (\u00b11 hour) in the week prior (screened via actigraphy baseline).  \n\nAdditionally, **practice effects** are avoided by using a between-subjects design\u2014no participant completes the task twice.\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**  \n\n1. **Within-subjects crossover design (n = 20)**:  \n   - *Why not chosen?* Although more statistically efficient and controlling for individual differences, it introduces **carryover effects** and **residual sleep debt** despite a 2-week washout. A single night of recovery sleep may not fully normalize neurocognitive function, especially in sensitive working memory circuits. Additionally, the emotional and physical burden of 36-hour deprivation may influence motivation or strategy in the second session. Given the hard constraint of no pharmacological countermeasures and the need for clean, interpretable between-group differences, the between-subjects design offers greater fidelity to the target comparison.\n\n2. **Three-group between-subjects design (adding 24-hour partial deprivation)**:  \n   - *Why not chosen?* While useful for dose-response inference, this exceeds the **minimal sufficient complexity** required to answer the binary question: *Does 36-hour deprivation impair performance relative to rested state?* Adding a third group increases sample size demands (n = 90 total) without improving precision on the primary contrast. The objective does not require modeling a gradient\u2014only a comparison of total deprivation vs. rest.\n\n---"
