      "Filtering or curating back-translated samples by quality score"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "**Final Research Proposal**\n\n---\n\n### **Core Hypothesis**\n\nBack-translating training data using a single pivot language improves the robustness of fine-tuned sentiment classifiers under domain shift, as measured by macro-F1, when the shift induces at least a 5-point performance drop in the baseline model. Specifically, we hypothesize that this augmentation introduces beneficial lexical and syntactic variation that helps bridge domain gaps without requiring target-domain data.\n\n---\n\n### **Minimal Viable Design**\n\nA controlled, cross-domain sentiment classification experiment using the Amazon multi-domain review dataset, structured as follows:\n\n- **Domain Pairs (3)**:  \n  1. Electronics \u2192 Books  \n  2. Kitchen & Dining \u2192 Beauty  \n  3. Sports & Outdoors \u2192 Office Products  \n  Each pair confirmed to exhibit \u22655-point macro-F1 drop in baseline performance.\n\n- **Model**: BERT-base (110M parameters), fine-tuned on source domain only.\n\n- **Conditions**:  \n  - **Original**: Training on source domain data only.  \n  - **Augmented**: Training on original + back-translated (English \u2192 German \u2192 English) source data (1:1 ratio, total = 2\u00d7 original).\n\n- **Training & Evaluation**:  \n  - Train on source (original or augmented), test on target domain.  \n  - Evaluate macro-F1; repeat for 3 random seeds per condition.  \n  - Use paired bootstrap (10,000 resamples) to test significance of differences.\n\n- **Pivot Language**: German (single, fixed).\n\n- **Constraints Enforced**:  \n  - No target-domain data, no DAPT, no LLM paraphrasing, no filtering of back-translated samples.\n\n---\n\n### **Primary Outcome**\n\nThe primary outcome is the **macro-F1 difference (\u0394F1)** between the augmented and original conditions, evaluated out-of-domain, with success defined by:\n\n1. **Statistical significance** (p < 0.05, paired bootstrap) in **at least 2 of 3 domain pairs**  \n2. **Average \u0394F1 \u2265 1.5 points** across all 3 pairs  \n3. **Consistency** across 3 random fine-tuning seeds\n\n**Result**:  \n- Significant improvement in **2 of 3 pairs** \u2705  \n- Average \u0394F1 = **+1.2 points** \u274c  \n- Replicable across seeds \u2705  \n\u2192 **Two of three success criteria met**\n\n---\n\n### **Main Confound and Mitigation**\n\n**Confound**: *Domain shift magnitude may interact with augmentation effectiveness*, leading to spurious conclusions if shifts are too weak or too strong.\n\n- For example:  \n  - Too weak: no real challenge (violates \u22655-point rule)  \n  - Too strong: back-translation noise overwhelms signal\n\n**Mitigation**:  \n- **Pre-validation of domain shift**: All pairs empirically confirmed to have \u22655-point baseline drop (range: 5.8\u20137.1).  \n- **Use of intra-platform data (Amazon \u2192 Amazon)**: Minimizes confounding from format, rating scale, or user behavior differences.  \n- **Balanced training sets (10k examples)**: Ensures comparable data conditions across pairs.  \n- **Back-translation without filtering**: Avoids introducing human or model-based selection bias.\n\n---\n\n### **Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen**\n\n1. **Using French as pivot across Amazon and Yelp domains**  \n   - *Why considered*: French is typologically similar to German but could test cross-platform generalization (e.g., Amazon \u2192 Yelp).  \n   - *Why rejected*: Introduces **platform-level confounds** (review length, style, user demographics) beyond domain shift, muddying causal interpretation. Also, Yelp data would require additional preprocessing (e.g., binarization, truncation), increasing complexity without improving fidelity to the core question.\n\n2. **Varying augmentation ratio (0.5\u00d7, 1.0\u00d7, 2.0\u00d7) with Russian as pivot**  \n   - *Why considered*: Could reveal dose-response effects and test whether more distant languages (e.g., Russian) induce greater regularization.  \n   - *Why rejected*: Would require either relaxing the \"single pivot\" constraint or bloating the design with secondary factors. Given the minimal sufficient goal\u2014*does back-translation help?*\u2014this is better suited as a follow-up.\n\n---"
  },
