    "final_proposal": "### Final Research Proposal: Fragmentation as a Functional Filter\n\n#### Core Hypothesis\nWild bee species richness decreases as mean semi-natural habitat patch size declines, specifically due to the loss of large-bodied, area-sensitive species. This effect is independent of total habitat amount, local floral resource density, and surrounding landscape-level crop diversity.\n\n#### Minimal Viable Design\n*   **Site Network:** 30 sites within a 200 km diameter region, stratified to vary mean patch size (1 km radius) while maintaining constant total semi-natural habitat area. \n*   **Protocol:** Pan-trap arrays (standardized grid) deployed at the center of semi-natural patches, serviced at fixed 72-hour intervals across the season.\n*   **Trait Analysis:** Assign body size (ITS) and nesting guild to all identified species to create a Community-Weighted Mean (CWM) for each site.\n*   **Statistical Analysis:** A GLMM using coverage-based rarefied species richness as the response variable. Include mean patch size, local floral richness, and landscape crop diversity as fixed effects, and a spatial autocorrelation structure (Mat\u00e9rn) to ensure independence.\n\n#### Primary Outcome\nA regression model reporting the effect size ($\\beta$) and 95% CI of mean patch size on bee richness, alongside a trait-interaction analysis demonstrating whether larger-bodied bees show a steeper decline in fragmented landscapes, confirming a demographic filter mechanism.\n\n#### Main Confound and Mitigation\n*   **Confound:** The \"Total Habitat Amount\" effect, where studies fail to distinguish between fragmentation per se and simple habitat loss. \n*   **Mitigation:** By selecting site landscapes with consistent total semi-natural habitat cover while varying mean patch size, we isolate the specific influence of patch configuration.\n\n#### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Threshold (Breakpoint) Modeling:** Deferring this because 30 sites provide insufficient statistical power to locate a robust \"tipping point\" without risking high Type II error.\n2.  **Structural Equation Modeling (SEM):** Deferring this as it requires more complex, unrequested inputs (like dispersal distances and isolation metrics) that move beyond the objective of quantifying the fragmentation-richness relationship."
