    "final_proposal": "**Final Proposal:**\n\n**Core Hypothesis:**\nSim-to-real transfer with domain randomization will achieve a higher grasp success rate on novel household objects than fine-tuning a simulation-pretrained policy on 500 or fewer real-world grasps.\n\n**Minimal Viable Design:**\nWe will use the Isaac Gym simulator to train a domain-randomized policy with automatic domain parameter sampling, varying at least texture, lighting, object mass, and friction parameters. The policy will be based on a simulation-pretrained architecture and weights, which will also serve as the starting point for the fine-tuning method. The domain-randomized policy will be deployed zero-shot to a Franka Panda arm, a 7-DOF robot with a parallel-jaw gripper. For the fine-tuning condition, we will collect up to 500 real-world grasps on the same Franka Panda arm, using the same base policy architecture and simulation-pretrained weights. We will then fine-tune this policy on the collected real-world data. Both methods will be evaluated on exactly 30 previously unseen household objects, divided into small, medium, and large object difficulty categories (with at least 8 objects per category).\n\n**Primary Outcome:**\nThe primary outcome will be the grasp success rate, defined as the percentage of successful grasps out of the total number of grasp attempts, with a success criterion of lifting the object at least 10 cm above the table and holding for 3 seconds. We will report per-method grasp success rates with 95% confidence intervals across the 30 test objects, as well as a breakdown of success rate by object difficulty category.\n\n**Main Confound and Mitigation:**\nA potential confound is the difference in the number of parameters and the complexity of the policies used for domain randomization and fine-tuning. To mitigate this, we will ensure that both methods start from the same base policy architecture and simulation-pretrained weights, and that the fine-tuning method uses a simple and efficient algorithm (e.g., DAgger) to adapt to the real-world environment.\n\n**Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen:**\n1. **NVIDIA Omniverse-based Domain Randomization:** We considered using NVIDIA Omniverse for photorealistic rendering-based domain randomization, but opted for Isaac Gym due to its ease of use, flexibility, and computational efficiency.\n2. **Dynamics Randomization-only Approach:** We also considered implementing dynamics randomization only (no visual randomization) in MuJoCo, but chose to use Isaac Gym's built-in domain randomization capabilities to vary both visual and dynamics parameters."
