      "evaluate in open or outdoor environments rather than cluttered indoor spaces"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "### Final Proposal: Value-Prior Guided Exploration (VPGE)\n\n#### Core Hypothesis\nInitializing a Reinforcement Learning (RL) agent\u2019s value function with 50 human teleoperation demonstrations\u2014via Implicit Q-Learning (IQL)\u2014provides a \"value-informed backbone\" that significantly accelerates the acquisition of safe navigation policies and reduces collision frequency in high-clutter environments compared to random-initialization PPO.\n\n#### Minimal Viable Design\n1.  **Preparation:** Collect exactly 50 teleoperation trials in the cluttered indoor environment.\n2.  **Phase I (Offline):** Train an IQL agent on the 50 demonstrations to compute the optimal value function $V_{expert}$ and policy $\\pi_{expert}$.\n3.  **Phase II (Training):** Initialize the PPO policy and critic weights using the weights derived from $V_{expert}$ and $\\pi_{expert}$. Continue training via PPO using identical hyper-parameters and reward functions for both conditions.\n4.  **Evaluation:** Conduct 100 trials (50 static clutter, 50 adversarial bottlenecked) across 5 room layouts. The agent must rely solely on onboard 2D LiDAR and RGB-D sensors.\n\n#### Primary Outcome\nThe **Collision-Rate Jump-Start Ratio**: The ratio of successful navigation trials in the first 10% of training steps between the experimental and baseline conditions. This quantifies the causal \"value-prior\" effect provided by the 50 demonstrations.\n\n#### Main Confound and Mitigation\n*   **Confound:** The observed improvement might be due to the policy simply memorizing demonstration paths (overfitting), rather than learning a generalized navigation logic.\n*   **Mitigation:** Inclusion of \"Adversarial Bottleneck\" test layouts (doorways/passages) that differ in geometry and obstacle configuration from the demonstration set. Success here provides empirical evidence of generalization.\n\n#### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **GAIL (Generative Adversarial Imitation Learning):** Rejected because it introduces a discriminator and an adversarial game, making the cause of performance gains (the demonstrations vs. the stability of the minimax game) ambiguous.\n2.  **Behavioral Cloning (BC) Pre-training:** Rejected because standard supervised learning (BC) ignores the environment's value landscape, leading to poor performance when the robot enters states not covered by the 50 demonstrations (distributional shift).\n\n***"
