    "final_proposal": "### Final Research Proposal: The Sim-to-Real Calibration Gap\n\n#### Core Hypothesis\nWe hypothesize that Domain Randomization (DR) acts as a high-entropy regularizer that achieves consistent performance across diverse objects by ignoring physical nuances, whereas Fine-Tuning (FT) utilizes real-world data to \"calibrate\" the pretrained policy toward the specific physical manifold of the test environment. We posit that FT will outperform DR only on objects whose physical properties fall outside the DR training distribution, at the cost of requiring real-world interaction data.\n\n#### Minimal Viable Design\n1.  **SysID Audit:** Measure mass and friction for all 30 objects; plot them against the DR training distribution to classify objects as \"In-Distribution\" (ID) or \"Out-of-Distribution\" (OOD).\n2.  **Base Policy:** A 7-DOF Franka Panda policy trained in Isaac Gym (Base weights $\\theta_0$).\n3.  **Method A:** Zero-shot deployment of $\\theta_0$ (DR policy).\n4.  **Method B:** Deployment of $\\theta_0$ followed by 500-grasp fine-tuning on a balanced sampling of objects. \n5.  **Metrics:** Success rate (10cm lift, 3s hold), Failure Mode analysis (Reach vs. Stability), and Weight-space Drift ($\\|\\theta_{final} - \\theta_0\\|_2$).\n\n#### Primary Outcome\nThe **Calibration Efficiency Curve**: A plot showing the success rate delta between FT and DR as a function of the real-world grasp count, segmented by object category (Small/Medium/Large) and ID/OOD status. This reveals the \"crossover point\" where real-world data investment provides a statistically significant advantage over simulated breadth.\n\n#### Main Confound and Mitigation\n*   **Confound:** The \"Evaluation Bias\"\u2014the risk that the 30 test objects inherently favor one method due to the chosen simulation parameters.\n*   **Mitigation:** We will report the \"Coverage Audit.\" By documenting the physical parameters of the test objects alongside the DR distribution, we provide a mathematical basis for interpreting the results, effectively normalizing for any systematic bias in the simulation setup.\n\n#### Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n1.  **Residual Policy Learning:** Adding a separate learned residual layer on top of the base policy. *Rejected:* Violates the \"base policy architecture\" constraints and complicates the interpretation of weight drift.\n2.  **Active Learning for Fine-Tuning:** Using an uncertainty-aware acquisition function to pick which objects to grasp during FT. *Rejected:* Introduces non-random sampling, which makes it harder to isolate the effect of \"number of grasps\" versus \"quality of data.\"\n\n***"
