    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\nProviding **written formative feedback three times per week** on weekly problem sets will produce **higher end-of-term final exam scores** than providing the same type of written feedback **once per week** in an introductory university statistics course.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n- **Design:** quasi-experimental comparison of **two concurrent sections** of the same course taught by the **same instructor**\n- **Sample:** at least **50 students per section**\n- **Intervention:** identical weekly problem sets in both sections; only the **frequency of written feedback** differs\n  - Section A: written comments **once per week**\n  - Section B: written comments **three times per week**\n- **Baseline control:** brief **pre-test of statistics ability** in week 1\n- **Duration:** exactly **one academic term** (10\u201315 weeks)\n- **No added support:** no tutoring or supplementary instruction for either section\n- **Outcome assessment:** identical final exam for both sections, graded by a **blinded marker**\n- **Process measure:** proportion of students who **access feedback within 48 hours**\n- **Analysis:** pre-registered **linear model / ANCOVA** predicting final exam score from feedback condition while controlling for baseline pre-test score\n\n## Primary outcome\n- **Final exam score**\n- Report the treatment effect as:\n  - adjusted mean difference\n  - **Cohen\u2019s d**\n  - confidence interval for Cohen\u2019s d\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n### Main confound\nBecause this is **quasi-experimental**, the biggest threat is **baseline differences between sections** in prior ability or motivation.\n\n### Mitigation\n- Administer a **baseline pre-test** at the start of the term\n- Include the pre-test score as a **covariate** in the pre-registered linear model\n- Keep the **same instructor, same problem sets, same term, same final exam, and same grading rubric**\n- Use a **blinded marker** for the final exam to reduce outcome assessment bias\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Compare the same section across two consecutive semesters using the prior semester as control**  \n   Not chosen because cohort and calendar differences would make it harder to isolate the effect of feedback frequency.\n\n2. **Compare two concurrent sections and use propensity score matching on prior GPA**  \n   Not chosen because matching may reduce sample size and is less direct than a baseline pre-test for controlling ability relevant to statistics performance."
