    "domain": "ecology",
    "objective": "Test whether active removal of a dominant invasive plant species increases native plant percent cover within 3 years at restoration sites compared to untreated control sites.",
    "hard_constraints": [
      "must target a single named invasive species, not multiple invaders simultaneously",
      "paired design with at least 8 treatment-control site pairs",
      "native cover must be measured as percent ground cover in fixed quadrats, not species counts",
      "all sites must be within the same ecoregion",
      "removal method must be mechanical only, no herbicide application",
      "baseline data must be collected before removal begins"
    ],
    "banned_moves": [
      "add a seeding or active replanting treatment to accelerate native recovery",
      "expand monitoring to include soil microbiome or nutrient cycling outcomes",
      "include a herbicide-treatment arm for comparison with mechanical removal"
    ],
    "final_proposal": "## Core hypothesis\n\nMechanical removal of **[single named invasive plant species]** at restoration sites will increase **native plant percent ground cover** within 3 years relative to untreated paired control sites in the same ecoregion.\n\nTightened causal story:\n- mechanical removal reduces cover of the focal invasive species,\n- reduced invasive cover lowers competitive suppression on native plants,\n- native percent cover increases,\n- and weaker native recovery is expected where reinvasion is stronger.\n\n## Minimal viable design\n\n- **Study system:** one named invasive plant species in a single ecoregion.\n- **Sites:** at least **8 matched treatment-control site pairs**; 10\u201312 pairs preferred if feasible.\n- **Pairing criteria:** similar habitat/restoration context, similar dominance by the focal invasive, and similar baseline native cover.\n- **Assignment:** collect baseline data first, then randomly assign one site per pair to treatment and the other to control if operationally feasible. If not feasible, retain matched pairing and document assignment basis.\n- **Baseline:** before removal begins, establish permanent fixed quadrats at all sites and measure:\n  - native plant percent ground cover\n  - focal invasive species percent cover\n- **Treatment:** mechanical removal only at treatment sites; no herbicide; control sites remain untreated.\n- **Follow-up:** sample the same fixed quadrats annually for 3 years in the same seasonal window.\n- **Measures at each annual time point:**\n  - native plant percent ground cover\n  - focal invasive species percent cover\n- **Added mechanism-strengthening component:** measure focal invasive cover once shortly after each annual removal window as a suppression/reinvasion check. This adds no new modality and directly supports the causal pathway.\n\n**Analysis**\n- Primary analysis: linear mixed-effects repeated-measures model for native cover with:\n  - fixed effects: treatment, year, treatment \u00d7 year\n  - random effect: site pair\n  - site-level repeated measures over time\n- Report treatment effect estimates with confidence intervals, especially by Year 3.\n- Secondary mechanism analysis: model invasive cover over time and test whether lower invasive cover predicts higher native cover.\n\n## Primary outcome\n\n**Native plant percent ground cover** measured in permanent fixed quadrats.\n\nPrimary estimand:\n- the treatment effect on native percent cover over time, especially the **treatment\u2013control difference in change by Year 3**, estimated from a repeated-measures or mixed-effects model with confidence interval.\n\n## Main confound and mitigation\n\n**Main confound:** pre-existing differences in recovery potential between treatment and control sites, such as habitat quality, restoration history, hydrology, or initial vegetation condition.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- restrict all sites to the same ecoregion,\n- use matched treatment-control pairs,\n- collect baseline quadrat data before removal,\n- demonstrate baseline native cover differs by no more than 10 percentage points,\n- randomize treatment assignment within pairs if feasible,\n- include site pair in the mixed model.\n\nThis is the simplest strong strategy for reducing bias without adding disallowed treatments or unrelated measurements.\n\n## Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n\n### 1. Bayesian change-point model for recovery lag at each site\nWhy plausible:\n- could estimate when native cover begins to recover after removal.\n\nWhy not chosen:\n- with only 3 years of follow-up, site-specific change-point estimation is likely underpowered and harder to defend as the main analysis.\n- it adds analytic complexity without improving identification of the core treatment effect as directly as the paired mixed-model BACI design.\n\n### 2. Permutation test using site-level slopes of native cover over time\nWhy plausible:\n- simple and robust to some distributional assumptions.\n\nWhy not chosen:\n- collapses repeated measurements into site-level slopes, losing information on timing and year-specific treatment effects.\n- less aligned with the success criterion than a mixed-effects repeated-measures model with confidence intervals."
