    "final_proposal": "### Core hypothesis\nLong-term ambient PM2.5 exposure, measured as the annual average at a child's residential address, is associated with an increased incidence of childhood asthma between ages 0 and 12, independent of household income and parental smoking status.\n\n### Minimal viable design\n**Design:** A pre-specified retrospective cohort study using a linked administrative and Electronic Health Record (EHR) database. \n**Population:** A cohort of at least 5,000 children followed from birth (or established baseline) up to age 12, with no prior asthma diagnosis at cohort entry.\n**Exposure Assessment:** Annual-average ambient PM2.5 concentrations assigned to each child's exact residential address using spatial interpolation (e.g., inverse-distance weighting) from the publicly available EPA Air Quality System (AQS) monitoring network. Exposure is updated dynamically if the child's address changes.\n**Statistical Analysis:** A pre-specified Cox proportional hazards model utilizing time-varying PM2.5 exposure to calculate an adjusted Hazard Ratio (HR) with a 95% Confidence Interval (CI). \n**Sensitivity Analysis:** To test robustness, a secondary model will modify the exposure window definition, comparing the primary 1-year concurrent annual average against a 3-year cumulative moving average of PM2.5 preceding the time-at-risk.\n\n### Primary outcome\nThe first documented occurrence of an ICD-coded asthma diagnosis (e.g., ICD-10 J45.x) recorded in the child's medical record between ages 0 and 12. \n\n### Main confound and mitigation\n**Confound:** Socioeconomic status and indoor air quality proxies are highly correlated with residential address (and thus ambient PM2.5) as well as asthma risk.\n**Mitigation:** The pre-specified Cox model will explicitly adjust for both household income and parental smoking status (extracted from linked maternal/pediatric intake records or administrative data), alongside baseline demographic covariates (e.g., child's sex, birth year). \n\n### Two plausible alternatives not chosen\n1. **Distributed-lag nonlinear model (DLNM) using satellite-derived PM2.5:** \n   *Reason not chosen:* While powerful for assessing complex temporal and non-linear exposure-response relationships, DLNMs add unnecessary modeling complexity. A standard time-varying Cox model using direct EPA AQS data represents the minimal sufficient complexity to estimate an adjusted HR for long-term exposure.\n2. **Propensity-score matched cohort pairing high-PM2.5 and low-PM2.5 ZIP codes:**\n   *Reason not chosen:* Dichotomizing a continuous exposure variable (PM2.5) into \"high\" and \"low\" thresholds discards valuable variance. Furthermore, aggregating exposure to the ZIP-code level compromises the hard constraint to utilize the residential address for exposure assignment.\n\n***"
  },
