    "final_proposal": "# Research Proposal: Mechanical Removal of *Phragmites australis* and Native Plant Recovery in Freshwater Wetland Restoration Sites\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nActive mechanical removal of *Phragmites australis* (common reed) from freshwater wetland restoration sites will produce a measurable increase in native plant percent ground cover within three years compared to paired untreated control sites in the same ecoregion, with the treatment effect detectable after accounting for baseline differences and temporal autocorrelation across sites.\n\nThe null hypothesis is that mean native percent ground cover does not differ between mechanically treated and untreated sites at any post-treatment time point when modeled with site pair as a random effect.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Study System\nAll sites are located within **EPA Level III Ecoregion 83 (Eastern Great Lakes and Hudson Lowlands)**, a geographically coherent region with consistent climate, hydrology, and wetland community composition. The target invasive is *Phragmites australis* (haplotype M, non-native lineage confirmed by morphology or prior regional surveys), selected because it is the single dominant invader at each site and because its dense monocultures make mechanical removal logistically tractable.\n\n### Site Selection and Pairing\n- **Minimum 8 treatment-control site pairs** (16 sites total), expandable to 12 pairs if logistical capacity allows.\n- Pairs are matched on: (a) estimated *P. australis* stem density at baseline, (b) wetland hydroperiod class (permanently vs. seasonally flooded), and (c) site area (within 20% of each other).\n- Within each pair, one site is randomly assigned to treatment; the other serves as the untreated control. Random assignment within pairs is performed using a coin flip documented before any removal activity begins.\n- Sites must be spatially separated by \u2265 500 m to reduce the probability of seed dispersal cross-contamination between treatment and control units.\n\n### Baseline Data Collection (Year 0, Pre-Treatment)\nBefore any removal occurs, the following are recorded at **all 16 sites**:\n- Native plant percent ground cover measured in **ten 1 m \u00d7 1 m fixed quadrats per site**, permanently marked with rebar and GPS coordinates. Quadrats are stratified to sample the interior, edge, and transition zones of each site proportionally.\n- *Phragmites australis* percent ground cover measured in the same fixed quadrats.\n- Hydroperiod class confirmed by water level logger installed for \u2265 30 days prior to baseline survey.\n\nBaseline native cover must not differ between treatment and control members of any pair by more than 10 percentage points (checked pair-by-pair before randomization is locked in; pairs failing this criterion are replaced before treatment begins).\n\n### Mechanical Removal Protocol (Treatment Sites Only)\n- **Method:** Cut-and-remove. Stems are cut at or below the waterline (or at ground level in drier zones) using brush cutters and hand tools in late summer (August\u2013September of Year 0), targeting the period of maximum carbohydrate depletion in rhizomes.\n- **Repeat cutting:** A second cut is applied the following spring (May\u2013June of Year 1) to suppress regrowth from rhizomes.\n- **No herbicide is applied at any point.** No seeding or replanting is performed.\n- Removed biomass is bagged and transported off-site to prevent reestablishment from cut fragments.\n- Control sites receive no intervention; access is restricted to monitoring personnel only.\n\n### Monitoring Schedule\nSurveys are conducted at **four time points**: Year 0 (pre-treatment baseline), Year 1 (one growing season post-removal), Year 2, and Year 3. All surveys occur within the same two-week window each year (late July\u2013early August) to control for phenological variation.\n\nAt each time point and each site:\n1. **Native plant percent ground cover** is estimated in all ten fixed quadrats using a point-intercept method (50 points per quadrat on a systematic grid) to minimize observer subjectivity.\n2. ***Phragmites australis* percent ground cover** is estimated in the same quadrats using the same method (addresses reinvasion tracking requirement).\n3. Observers are rotated across sites and blinded to treatment assignment where possible; inter-rater reliability is assessed by paired double-surveys at two randomly selected sites per year.\n\n### Statistical Analysis\n**Primary model:** Linear mixed-effects model (LMM) fitted in R (`lme4`/`lmerTest`) with the following structure:\n\n```\nNativeCover ~ Treatment \u00d7 Time + (1 | Pair/Site) + (Time | Site)\n```\n\n- **Fixed effects:** Treatment (binary: removal vs. control), Time (Year 0, 1, 2, 3 as ordered factor or continuous), and their interaction (the term of primary interest).\n- **Random effects:** Site nested within Pair (accounts for the paired design and between-site heterogeneity); random slope for Time within Site (accounts for sites that may recover at different rates).\n- **Repeated measures structure:** Observations within a site across years are modeled with a first-order autoregressive AR(1) covariance structure on residuals to handle temporal autocorrelation.\n- The treatment effect is reported as the estimated marginal mean difference in native cover (treatment minus control) at Year 3, with 95% confidence interval.\n- Baseline equivalence is confirmed by extracting the Year 0 treatment vs. control contrast; if it exceeds 10 percentage points at the aggregate level, the pairing process is revisited before proceeding.\n\n**Secondary analysis for reinvasion:** *Phragmites australis* cover at each time point is reported descriptively (mean \u00b1 SE by group) and included as a covariate in a sensitivity version of the primary model to test whether any treatment effect on native cover is partly mediated by ongoing suppression of the invader vs. direct competitive release.\n\n**Minimum detectable effect:** With 8 pairs, 10 quadrats per site, and conservative within-site correlation (ICC \u2248 0.4), the design has \u2265 80% power to detect a 12 percentage-point difference in native cover change between groups at \u03b1 = 0.05 (estimated via simulation under the LMM structure).\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n**Change in native plant percent ground cover from Year 0 to Year 3**, compared between mechanically treated and untreated control sites, expressed as the estimated marginal mean treatment effect with 95% confidence interval from the linear mixed-effects model. A statistically and ecologically meaningful result requires that the confidence interval excludes zero and that the point estimate exceeds 8 percentage points (a threshold considered ecologically meaningful for wetland restoration in the literature).\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n**Confound: Differential hydrological disturbance between pairs**\n\nFreshwater wetland native cover is highly sensitive to interannual variation in water levels. If treatment and control sites within a pair experience divergent hydroperiods in any given year (due to local drainage, beaver activity, or storm events), observed differences in native cover may reflect hydrology rather than removal treatment.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- **Pairing on hydroperiod class** at baseline reduces systematic differences.\n- **Continuous water level loggers** (recording every 6 hours) are installed at all 16 sites for the full 3-year study period. Hydroperiod metrics (days inundated per growing season) are extracted annually and included as a **time-varying covariate** in the primary LMM.\n- If a site pair experiences a hydrological anomaly (e.g., one site is drained or flooded by an external disturbance event), that pair is flagged and a **sensitivity analysis** excluding the affected pair is reported alongside the full-dataset results.\n- This approach preserves the paired structure and full sample size in the primary analysis while transparently accounting for hydrological confounding.\n\n---\n\n## Two Plausible Alternatives Not Chosen\n\n### Alternative 1: Bayesian Change-Point Model Estimating Recovery Lag per Site\n\nThis approach would fit a site-level Bayesian model estimating the time point at which native cover begins to increase (the \"change point\") and the subsequent rate of increase, allowing heterogeneous recovery trajectories across sites.\n\n**Why not chosen:** With only four time points (Years 0\u20133), the data are too sparse to reliably estimate a change-point parameter at the individual site level; posterior distributions would be dominated by the prior. The approach also does not naturally accommodate the paired design, making it harder to isolate the treatment effect from between-site variability. The LMM achieves the same goal of allowing heterogeneous trajectories (via random slopes) with less model complexity and better-understood frequentist inference properties for regulatory and practitioner audiences.\n\n### Alternative 2: Permutation-Based Test Using Site-Level Slopes as the Response\n\nThis approach would compute, for each site, the ordinary least squares slope of native cover over Years 0\u20133, then test whether the distribution of slopes in treatment sites stochastically dominates that in control sites using a permutation test that reshuffles treatment labels within pairs.\n\n**Why not chosen:** Collapsing the time series to a single slope discards information about the shape of recovery (e.g., whether cover increases monotonically or shows a dip in Year 1 due to disturbance from removal activity) and eliminates the ability to report time-point-specific confidence intervals required by the success criteria. It also does not directly accommodate the time-varying hydrological covariate identified as the main confound. The LMM retains the full temporal structure and satisfies all success criteria more directly.\n\n---"
  },
