    "final_proposal": "# Final Research Protocol\n\n---\n\n## Core Hypothesis\n\nAmbient PM2.5 exposure during the first two years of life (infancy and toddlerhood, windows W1\u2013W2) causes incident childhood asthma through oxidative-stress-mediated disruption of airway epithelial barriers and Th1/Th2 immune polarisation during the period of peak alveolar multiplication. This effect is:\n\n1. **Window-specific:** Larger in W1\u2013W2 than in prenatal (W0), pre-school (W3), or school-age (W4) windows, because the oxidative-stress pathway intersects with a developmentally bounded immunological sensitive period that closes by approximately 36 months of age.\n\n2. **Dose-dependent with nonlinear kinetics:** The exposure-response relationship follows a threshold-then-plateau shape, consistent with oxidative-stress saturation once pulmonary antioxidant defences are overwhelmed, rather than a linear no-threshold relationship.\n\n3. **Amplified by neighbourhood deprivation:** The effect is larger in high-ADI census tracts, where co-exposures (parental smoking, crowding, limited green space) increase baseline oxidative burden and reduce physiological reserve against additional PM2.5 insult.\n\n4. **Causally identified by quasi-experimental variation:** The association is not explained by shared-geography confounding, as demonstrated by a regression discontinuity difference-in-differences analysis exploiting Clean Air Act nonattainment designations triggered by the 2012 NAAQS revision (annual standard: 15 \u2192 12 \u00b5g/m\u00b3). Counties just above the regulatory threshold experienced policy-driven PM2.5 reductions; birth cohorts whose W1\u2013W2 windows fell in the post-reduction period show lower asthma incidence than birth cohorts in the same counties whose W1\u2013W2 windows fell before the reductions. This within-county, within-window temporal contrast is the primary source of causal identification.\n\n**The hypothesis is falsifiable in four distinct ways within this single protocol:**\n\n| Falsification condition | What it would mean |\n|---|---|\n| Window-specific DiD \u03b4_window is null | PM2.5 reductions during W1\u2013W2 do not reduce asthma; causal claim abandoned |\n| Window-specific DiD \u03b4_W4 equals \u03b4_window | No window specificity; the developmental mechanism is not supported |\n| Injury falsification DiD is non-null | DiD identifying assumption violated; quasi-experimental results unreliable |\n| Pre-designation placebo DiD is non-null | Parallel trends assumption violated; DiD results unreliable |\n\nA hypothesis that can be abandoned cleanly on four independent criteria is a stronger scientific claim than one that can only be qualified.\n\n---\n\n## Minimal Viable Design\n\n### Architecture\n\nA retrospective birth cohort embedded within a two-stage causal identification strategy. Every element of the design is present because it is required by either a hard constraint or the identification strategy. Nothing is added for completeness, novelty signalling, or reviewer appeasement.\n\n### Cohort\n\n**Source:** Children born 2010\u20132018 to Medicaid/CHIP-enrolled mothers in five states (California, Texas, New York, Illinois, Ohio), identified through linked birth certificate and Medicaid claims records.\n\n**Entry:** Fixed at birth. This is non-negotiable for the developmental window analysis: entry at first healthcare encounter would introduce left-truncation bias by missing children who develop asthma before their first recorded encounter.\n\n**Size:** Target 70,000 birth records across five states. The hard-constraint minimum of 5,000 is met with a margin of 14:1, providing adequate power for the RD bandwidth subsample (estimated 15,000\u201325,000 children within the CCT-optimal bandwidth around the 12 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 threshold) and for the ADI interaction analysis.\n\n**Eligibility:** Live singleton birth; Medicaid enrollment beginning within 90 days of birth; residential address at birth geocodable to census tract; born in a county with at least one active EPA AQS PM2.5 monitor within 50 km. Exclusion: congenital lung malformation (ICD-10 Q33.x) or bronchopulmonary dysplasia (P27.1) as competing pathways to wheeze; less than six months total follow-up.\n\n**Follow-up:** Birth through age 12, first asthma diagnosis, Medicaid disenrollment, or death, whichever comes first.\n\n### Exposure\n\n**Metric:** Annual-average PM2.5 (\u00b5g/m\u00b3) at geocoded residential address, assigned separately for each of five developmentally motivated windows:\n\n| Window | Age range | Biological rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| W0: Prenatal | Conception to birth | Lung branching morphogenesis |\n| W1: Infancy | 0\u201312 months | Peak alveolar multiplication; first allergen sensitisation |\n| W2: Toddler | 12\u201336 months | Continued alveolar growth; Th1/Th2 polarisation closes |\n| W3: Pre-school | 36\u201372 months | Airway remodelling |\n| W4: School-age | 72\u2013144 months | Diagnosis consolidation |\n\n**Source:** EPA Air Quality System (AQS) FRM/FEM monitor data, publicly available. Inverse-distance weighting from all active monitors within 50 km, distance decay exponent = 2. Prenatal exposure assigned from maternal residential address at delivery linked to birth certificate; postnatal exposure updated annually at Medicaid enrollment renewal.\n\n**TRAP proximity:** Distance from geocoded residential address to nearest functional class 1\u20132 road, from U.S. Census Bureau TIGER/Line files (public). Assigned per window using the same residential address logic as PM2.5. Enters the primary model as a confounder (adjustment set variable), not as a secondary exposure, per the pre-specified DAG.\n\n### Stage 1: Causal Identification (RD-DiD)\n\n**Event:** 2012 NAAQS revision. Counties with 3-year average PM2.5 (2011\u20132013) above 12 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 designated nonattainment in 2014\u20132015; SIP-driven reductions measurable in AQS data by 2016\u20132018.\n\n**Running variable:** County 3-year average PM2.5 (2011\u20132013) from AQS.\n\n**Threshold:** 12 \u00b5g/m\u00b3.\n\n**Bandwidth:** CCT data-driven optimal, with robustness checks at 50% and 150% of optimal.\n\n**Primary DiD estimand:**\n\n```\n\u03b4_window = [Asthma_rate(nonattainment, W1\u2013W2 post-reduction)]\n          \u2212 [Asthma_rate(nonattainment, W1\u2013W2 pre-reduction)]\n          \u2212 [Asthma_rate(attainment, W1\u2013W2 post-reduction)]\n          + [Asthma_rate(attainment, W1\u2013W2 pre-reduction)]\n```\n\nBirth cohorts with W1\u2013W2 falling entirely in the pre-reduction period (births 2010\u20132013) serve as the pre-period; birth cohorts with W1\u2013W2 falling entirely in the post-reduction period (births 2016\u20132018) serve as the post-period. Transition cohorts (births 2014\u20132015) are excluded from the primary DiD.\n\n**Contrast estimand:** Identical DiD structure for birth cohorts whose W4 falls in the post-reduction period but whose W1\u2013W2 falls in the pre-reduction period. If \u03b4_W4 is null or smaller than \u03b4_window, window specificity is quasi-experimentally confirmed.\n\n**Falsification sequence (run before any outcome analysis, results reported before examining primary estimand):**\n\n1. McCrary density test and covariate balance table at the 12 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 threshold.\n2. Pre-designation placebo DiD on pre-2014 birth cohorts only.\n3. Traumatic injury DiD using the identical model with injury (ICD-10 S00\u2013T88, fractures and lacerations) as the outcome.\n\n**Logical dependency rule (pre-specified in OSF registration):** Stage 2 results are interpreted causally only if all three falsification tests pass. If any test fails, Stage 2 results are reported as descriptive associations with explicit removal of causal language from the abstract and conclusions.\n\n### Stage 2: Effect Characterisation (Cox Model, RD Bandwidth Sample)\n\n**Model:** Cox proportional hazards, time scale = age in days from birth, robust sandwich standard errors clustered on county, estimated within the RD bandwidth sample only.\n\n```\nh(t) = h\u2080(t) \u00b7 exp[\n    \u03b2\u2081\u00b7PM2.5_W0  +  \u03b2\u2082\u00b7PM2.5_W1  +  \u03b2\u2083\u00b7PM2.5_W2\n  + \u03b2\u2084\u00b7PM2.5_W3  +  \u03b2\u2085\u00b7PM2.5_W4\n  + \u03b3\u2081\u00b7TRAP_W1   +  \u03b3\u2082\u00b7TRAP_W2\n  + \u03b4\u00b7ADI        +  \u03b6\u00b7Income      +  \u03b7\u00b7Smoking\n  + \u03b8\u00b7HealthcareAccess  +  \u03b9\u00b7Race  +  \u03ba\u00b7Sex\n  + \u03bb\u00b7BirthYear  +  \u03bc\u00b7County_FE\n]\n```\n\n**Primary estimands:** \u03b2\u2082 and \u03b2\u2083 (adjusted HRs per 1 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 for W1 and W2 respectively), with Benjamini-Hochberg FDR correction across all five window-specific tests.\n\n**Dose-response characterisation:** Restricted cubic splines (4 knots at 5th, 35th, 65th, 95th percentiles) for PM2.5_W1 and PM2.5_W2 within the bandwidth Cox model. Nonlinearity tested by likelihood ratio test (pre-specified \u03b1 = 0.05). The resulting curves constitute the policy-relevant dose-response relationship for the causally identified effect.\n\n**Burden characterisation:** ADI \u00d7 PM2.5_W1 and ADI \u00d7 PM2.5_W2 interaction terms added to the bandwidth Cox model. Stratum-specific HRs reported by ADI tertile.\n\n### Sensitivity Analyses\n\n| # | Modification | Exposure window modified |\n|---|---|---|\n| SA-1 | Replace window-specific PM2.5 with 2-year rolling average (single time-varying covariate) | **Yes** \u2705 |\n| SA-2 | Replace window-specific PM2.5 with 3-year rolling average | **Yes** \u2705 |\n| SA-3 | Distributed-lag nonlinear model with monthly PM2.5 lags 0\u201360 months | Yes |\n| SA-4 | Restrict to children with stable residential address within each window | No |\n| SA-5 | Alternative outcome definition: \u22651 ICD code plus \u22651 asthma-related prescription | No |\n| SA-6 | Exclude ICD-9/ICD-10 transition year 2015 | No |\n| SA-7 | Restrict to children within 25 km of AQS monitor | No |\n| SA-8 | E-value calculation for unmeasured confounding in Stage 2 | No |\n| SA-9 | DiD with CCT bandwidth \u00d7 50% | No |\n| SA-10 | DiD with CCT bandwidth \u00d7 150% | No |\n| SA-11 | DiD replicated using 1997 NAAQS designation events as independent replication | No |\n\nSA-1 and SA-2 satisfy the hard-constraint requirement. SA-3 tests whether the discrete window approximation is adequate. SA-9 through SA-11 test robustness of the Stage 1 identification.\n\n### Pre-Registration\n\nFull model specification, variable coding, falsification decision rules, and analysis code skeleton deposited on OSF before any data access. The logical dependency rule \u2014 Stage 2 causal interpretation contingent on Stage 1 falsification passage \u2014 is explicitly stated in the registration and cannot be modified post-hoc.\n\n---\n\n## Primary Outcome\n\n**Definition:** Incident asthma, defined as two or more ICD-coded asthma diagnoses (ICD-9: 493.xx; ICD-10: J45.xx) on separate dates within any rolling 12-month window, with no prior asthma code in the 12 months before cohort entry (birth).\n\n**Date of event:** Date of the second qualifying diagnosis.\n\n**Rationale for the two-encounter definition:** Single ICD codes carry unacceptable false-positive rates in paediatric Medicaid administrative data; the two-encounter criterion is validated against chart review in this population and substantially improves positive predictive value without meaningfully increasing false negatives, since children with genuine asthma almost universally have multiple encounters.\n\n**ICD transition:** ICD-9 codes used for encounters before October 2015; ICD-10 codes thereafter. A validated crosswalk is applied. The transition year is included as a binary covariate in the primary model and excluded entirely in SA-6.\n\n**Censoring:** Age 13, Medicaid disenrollment, death, or end of study period (31 December 2022), whichever occurs first. Disenrollment is treated as non-informative censoring in the primary analysis; SA-4 (address-stable restriction) provides a partial check on whether mobile and disenrolling families differ systematically.\n\n**Negative control outcome:** Traumatic injury (ICD-10 S00\u2013T88, restricted to fractures and lacerations) used exclusively in falsification tests F2 and F3. It is not an outcome of scientific interest; it is a design-verification tool. Its role is to confirm that the DiD identifying assumption holds and that PM2.5 does not spuriously predict conditions with no plausible PM2.5 pathway.\n\n---\n\n## Main Confound and Mitigation\n\n### The Confound: Shared-Geography Selection\n\nThe primary threat to causal inference is not any single measured confounder \u2014 income, smoking, race, or urbanicity \u2014 but the **structural correlation between residential PM2.5 levels and the full constellation of social, economic, and environmental disadvantages that independently cause childhood asthma.** This is not residual confounding in the conventional sense (an omitted variable that could in principle be measured and added). It is a property of the data-generating process: in the United States, high-PM2.5 areas are systematically also areas of concentrated poverty, residential segregation, poor housing quality, limited healthcare access, and higher rates of indoor pollution. No set of measured covariates can fully disentangle these because they are causally upstream of each other and of PM2.5 simultaneously.\n\nThis means that the conventional epidemiological response \u2014 add more covariates \u2014 cannot solve the problem. Adding ADI, income, smoking, TRAP proximity, and urbanicity reduces bias but cannot eliminate it, because the unmeasured components of shared geography (U in the DAG) remain. The E-value (SA-8) quantifies how strong U would need to be to explain away the result, but it does not eliminate U.\n\n### The Mitigation: Within-County Temporal Variation from a Regulatory Discontinuity\n\nThe only design element that breaks the shared-geography confound without randomisation is one that introduces **exposure variation that is independent of the geographic confounding structure.** The 2012 NAAQS nonattainment designation provides this variation because:\n\n- Designation is assigned by a deterministic threshold rule applied to monitored PM2.5 levels, not by the health or socioeconomic characteristics of residents.\n- Counties just above and just below the 12 \u00b5g/m\u00b3 threshold are, by the continuity assumption of the regression discontinuity design, similar on all measured and unmeasured confounders \u2014 they differ primarily in whether they received the regulatory intervention.\n- The DiD uses **within-county change over time** as the source of identification, so all stable county-level confounders \u2014 including unmeasured ones \u2014 are differenced out.\n- The window-specific DiD further restricts the comparison to birth cohorts whose W1\u2013W2 windows fall in the pre- versus post-reduction period within the same counties, so even time-varying county-level confounders are controlled to the extent that they affect both treated and control counties similarly.\n\n**Residual threats to the mitigation and how they are addressed:**\n\n| Residual threat | Response |\n|---|---|\n| Counties anticipate designation and begin reducing emissions before the threshold is crossed (Ashenfelter's dip) | Pre-designation placebo DiD (F3) tests for pre-existing divergence in asthma trends; AQS PM2.5 trends are plotted for treatment and control counties from 2010 onward |\n| Nonattainment designation triggers other health-relevant policy changes (e.g., Medicaid outreach, housing remediation) that independently reduce asthma | Injury falsification DiD (F2) tests whether designation affects a condition that would be sensitive to these co-policies; if injury rates fall too, the DiD result is confounded |\n| Counties near the threshold differ from the broader cohort, limiting generalisability | Stage 2 Cox"
  }
